00:02:40.230 --> 00:02:42.150
Today's conference
has been organized

00:02:42.150 --> 00:02:44.160
by our biological
science faculty

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:46.050
director, Janet Rich-Edwards.

00:02:46.050 --> 00:02:49.330
And I'm very grateful to
Janet for her leadership.

00:02:49.330 --> 00:02:52.050
We're here today to
consider the past, present,

00:02:52.050 --> 00:02:53.940
and future of DNA.

00:02:53.940 --> 00:02:56.890
And the very title
of today's conference

00:02:56.890 --> 00:03:00.470
alerts us to how timely,
but also in some ways

00:03:00.470 --> 00:03:04.730
how timeless, a topic
DNA actually is.

00:03:04.730 --> 00:03:09.010
Swiss scientist Friedrich
Miescher first isolated DNA

00:03:09.010 --> 00:03:12.220
in white blood cells in 1869.

00:03:12.220 --> 00:03:15.980
Its discovery revolutionized
the science of genetics

00:03:15.980 --> 00:03:20.690
and also inspired an entire
literary genre of microbiology

00:03:20.690 --> 00:03:22.326
as dramatic narrative.

00:03:22.326 --> 00:03:26.650
In 1926, The Microbe
Hunters by Paul de Kruif

00:03:26.650 --> 00:03:30.460
ignited the imaginations of an
entire generation of budding

00:03:30.460 --> 00:03:31.830
scientists.

00:03:31.830 --> 00:03:34.450
Half a century
later, The Eighth Day

00:03:34.450 --> 00:03:37.910
of Creation by Horace
Judson did the same

00:03:37.910 --> 00:03:39.890
for another generation.

00:03:39.890 --> 00:03:43.770
For decades, scores of
biologists and geneticists

00:03:43.770 --> 00:03:46.780
have attributed their
decisions to become scientists

00:03:46.780 --> 00:03:50.010
to reading The Microbe Hunters
or The Eighth Day of Creation

00:03:50.010 --> 00:03:52.390
when they were young.

00:03:52.390 --> 00:03:56.440
In subject matter, both are
books about microbiology.

00:03:56.440 --> 00:03:59.450
But in form, they are
adventure stories.

00:03:59.450 --> 00:04:01.530
As one reviewer put
it, they feature,

00:04:01.530 --> 00:04:03.290
and I quote, epics
of science that

00:04:03.290 --> 00:04:05.860
come to triumphant fruition.

00:04:05.860 --> 00:04:08.200
The Eighth Day of
Creation, for example,

00:04:08.200 --> 00:04:11.630
portrays James Watson and
Francis Crick discovery

00:04:11.630 --> 00:04:15.250
of DNA's double helix
structure in 1953

00:04:15.250 --> 00:04:19.310
as the culminating event
in molecular biology.

00:04:19.310 --> 00:04:22.960
It's a suspenseful thriller,
and discovering the double helix

00:04:22.960 --> 00:04:25.210
is the climactic moment.

00:04:25.210 --> 00:04:29.490
The book was published
35 years ago in 1979.

00:04:29.490 --> 00:04:35.120
And yet, since then DNA research
has continued to advance

00:04:35.120 --> 00:04:39.810
and has helped us to see
life on Earth holy anew.

00:04:39.810 --> 00:04:41.400
It has challenged
what we thought

00:04:41.400 --> 00:04:45.990
we knew about neanderthals,
cancer, crime fighting,

00:04:45.990 --> 00:04:48.330
human personality, and more.

00:04:48.330 --> 00:04:50.740
Its discovery has
changed medicine

00:04:50.740 --> 00:04:53.610
and spawned whole
new industries.

00:04:53.610 --> 00:04:56.270
Even in my own field
of history, which

00:04:56.270 --> 00:04:59.760
would seem to be as far
removed from cutting edge

00:04:59.760 --> 00:05:03.690
molecular biological research
as you can possibly get,

00:05:03.690 --> 00:05:07.670
it is being fundamentally
altered by DNA.

00:05:07.670 --> 00:05:11.440
For example, advances
in genomic archaeology

00:05:11.440 --> 00:05:14.480
have provided us with
better understanding

00:05:14.480 --> 00:05:18.380
of why famines affected
populations differently.

00:05:18.380 --> 00:05:20.950
Some human remains
contain genes that

00:05:20.950 --> 00:05:25.350
show unusually high prevalence
of lactase, an enzyme that

00:05:25.350 --> 00:05:29.950
breaks down lactose, the sugar
that occurs in dairy products.

00:05:29.950 --> 00:05:33.310
The more lactase a
person's body can produce,

00:05:33.310 --> 00:05:37.500
the more a person can tolerate
and derived nutritional value

00:05:37.500 --> 00:05:39.500
from milk and butter.

00:05:39.500 --> 00:05:43.500
Populations with high levels
depended less exclusively

00:05:43.500 --> 00:05:45.810
on grain for subsistence.

00:05:45.810 --> 00:05:49.510
And therefore could better
withstand poor harvests

00:05:49.510 --> 00:05:50.790
in the short term.

00:05:50.790 --> 00:05:52.860
Because they were
already accustom

00:05:52.860 --> 00:05:56.450
to supplementing low
grain yields with milk.

00:05:56.450 --> 00:05:59.540
On the other hand,
those same populations

00:05:59.540 --> 00:06:02.720
were much more vulnerable
when epidemic diseases struck

00:06:02.720 --> 00:06:04.160
cattle.

00:06:04.160 --> 00:06:06.610
Very close to home,
my own colleague

00:06:06.610 --> 00:06:09.580
in the Harvard history
department, Mike McCormick,

00:06:09.580 --> 00:06:13.580
is reevaluating the
Anglo-Saxon invasion of Britain

00:06:13.580 --> 00:06:16.170
on the basis of DNA research.

00:06:16.170 --> 00:06:19.380
Mike is not exaggerating
when he calls human genetics,

00:06:19.380 --> 00:06:22.630
and I quote him, an
extraordinary window

00:06:22.630 --> 00:06:25.670
on a vanished world of
migrations and matings

00:06:25.670 --> 00:06:29.690
that take you back literally
to the dawn of human time, end

00:06:29.690 --> 00:06:30.900
quote.

00:06:30.900 --> 00:06:33.930
The study of DNA then is
more relevant to the study

00:06:33.930 --> 00:06:36.680
of history than might
at first be obvious.

00:06:36.680 --> 00:06:41.600
At the same time, how scientists
study, understand, and apply

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:44.860
genetics also changes over time.

00:06:44.860 --> 00:06:48.720
So while DNA changes history,
it also has a history.

00:06:48.720 --> 00:06:51.760
And we are living today
in a watershed moment

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:53.300
of that history.

00:06:53.300 --> 00:06:57.920
Let's look quickly at a case
of DNA research now evolving.

00:06:57.920 --> 00:07:00.260
The emerging field of
epigenetics studies

00:07:00.260 --> 00:07:03.610
how environment can alter
the molecular processes that

00:07:03.610 --> 00:07:05.990
affect how genes get expressed.

00:07:05.990 --> 00:07:09.200
Researchers have shown
that toxins, chemicals,

00:07:09.200 --> 00:07:12.070
and some kinds of
trauma can alter

00:07:12.070 --> 00:07:16.320
how chromosomal code actually
gets suppressed or articulated.

00:07:16.320 --> 00:07:19.640
Recent studies raise the
intriguing possibility

00:07:19.640 --> 00:07:23.450
that social interactions
might do that as well.

00:07:23.450 --> 00:07:27.670
For instance, research indicates
that some genetic diseases

00:07:27.670 --> 00:07:30.970
progress differently in
socially isolated people

00:07:30.970 --> 00:07:34.830
than they do in people with
robust support networks.

00:07:34.830 --> 00:07:38.330
Learning more about how DNA
replicates and expresses itself

00:07:38.330 --> 00:07:41.960
therefore might not
necessarily reduce us

00:07:41.960 --> 00:07:45.130
to dehumanized chains
of polypeptides,

00:07:45.130 --> 00:07:48.360
as some ethicists worried
when the double helix was

00:07:48.360 --> 00:07:49.910
first discovered.

00:07:49.910 --> 00:07:53.620
It might instead help
us to better understand

00:07:53.620 --> 00:07:57.150
exactly how and why the
people in our lives,

00:07:57.150 --> 00:08:00.940
our friends and our families,
have a transformational impact

00:08:00.940 --> 00:08:02.150
on us.

00:08:02.150 --> 00:08:06.390
The study of DNA in short began
raising profound questions

00:08:06.390 --> 00:08:08.840
as soon as Miescher began
isolating white blood

00:08:08.840 --> 00:08:10.910
cells in 1869.

00:08:10.910 --> 00:08:13.200
It continues to do so today.

00:08:13.200 --> 00:08:16.570
And it will persist doing
that into the future.

00:08:16.570 --> 00:08:19.910
It is thus a most fitting
topic for consideration

00:08:19.910 --> 00:08:22.160
here at the Radcliffe
Institute, where

00:08:22.160 --> 00:08:25.840
we embrace open ended,
complicated, and cross

00:08:25.840 --> 00:08:28.410
disciplinary investigations.

00:08:28.410 --> 00:08:31.350
To get us started, I would
now like to hand things

00:08:31.350 --> 00:08:33.580
over to Janet Rich-Edwards.

00:08:33.580 --> 00:08:36.870
Janet is a Radcliffe alum
and an epidemiologist

00:08:36.870 --> 00:08:40.200
with research interests
centering on maternal and child

00:08:40.200 --> 00:08:41.200
health.

00:08:41.200 --> 00:08:44.420
She holds dual appointments
at the Harvard Medical School

00:08:44.420 --> 00:08:47.400
and the Harvard T.H Chan
School of Public Health.

00:08:47.400 --> 00:08:51.860
And she also serves as director
of developmental epidemiology

00:08:51.860 --> 00:08:54.490
at the Conners Center for
Women's Health and Gender

00:08:54.490 --> 00:08:57.510
Biology at Brigham
and Women's Hospital.

00:08:57.510 --> 00:09:00.430
Her research interests
include the implications

00:09:00.430 --> 00:09:05.290
of pregnancy complications for
future cardiovascular disease

00:09:05.290 --> 00:09:08.940
and the impact of childhood
abuse on chronic disease

00:09:08.940 --> 00:09:10.070
outcomes.

00:09:10.070 --> 00:09:10.570
Janet?

00:09:18.980 --> 00:09:19.960
-Good morning.

00:09:19.960 --> 00:09:20.840
Thank you Dean Cohen.

00:09:20.840 --> 00:09:22.506
And thank you all for
coming here today.

00:09:22.506 --> 00:09:25.480
And special thanks
to our speakers.

00:09:25.480 --> 00:09:28.450
Last Sunday, as my husband
and I were up on the roof

00:09:28.450 --> 00:09:31.420
watching the lunar
eclipse, we recalled

00:09:31.420 --> 00:09:34.310
the thrill of Apollo
11 landing there

00:09:34.310 --> 00:09:36.940
and the moment when Neil
Armstrong stepped out

00:09:36.940 --> 00:09:39.630
of that module onto
the moon's surface.

00:09:39.630 --> 00:09:41.659
I was seven years old.

00:09:41.659 --> 00:09:43.200
We had just had
sheer wonder that man

00:09:43.200 --> 00:09:44.950
was stepping on the moon.

00:09:44.950 --> 00:09:46.760
My husband, looking
up at that blood moon,

00:09:46.760 --> 00:09:50.080
said, it's still pretty
amazing to think about.

00:09:50.080 --> 00:09:51.180
And here's what I thought.

00:09:51.180 --> 00:09:52.467
Yeah, it is.

00:09:52.467 --> 00:09:54.300
But it ain't nothing
compared to what you're

00:09:54.300 --> 00:09:56.840
going to hear about on Friday.

00:09:56.840 --> 00:09:59.600
I'm that excited
about today's program.

00:09:59.600 --> 00:10:03.490
For as marvelous as it
is to go to the moon,

00:10:03.490 --> 00:10:05.600
it's equally
marvelous and perhaps

00:10:05.600 --> 00:10:09.950
even more pretentious
for the planet's welfare

00:10:09.950 --> 00:10:13.000
to be able to go into
the mitochondria.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:15.240
As you'll hear today,
the science of DNA

00:10:15.240 --> 00:10:17.130
is not only telling
us about our past.

00:10:17.130 --> 00:10:20.300
It's already improving human
health and planetary ecology.

00:10:20.300 --> 00:10:23.730
And its potential for the
future seems limitless.

00:10:23.730 --> 00:10:26.100
But this technology
is new, very new.

00:10:26.100 --> 00:10:30.080
And like any sharp tool,
can be used for good or ill.

00:10:30.080 --> 00:10:32.240
And so we need to
develop it thoughtfully

00:10:32.240 --> 00:10:33.416
and with safeguards.

00:10:33.416 --> 00:10:34.790
And so in addition
to the science

00:10:34.790 --> 00:10:36.830
today, we'll be discussing
the ethical aspects

00:10:36.830 --> 00:10:37.663
of this new world.

00:10:42.060 --> 00:10:42.560
There we go.

00:10:42.560 --> 00:10:45.500
When I was a kid, DNA
was pretty simple.

00:10:45.500 --> 00:10:51.320
You had your nucleotides, the
base pairs, A, T, G, and C.

00:10:51.320 --> 00:10:54.800
And you knew that the DNA
in the nuclei of your cells

00:10:54.800 --> 00:10:59.480
was transcribed into RNA, which
left the nucleus as messenger

00:10:59.480 --> 00:11:02.860
RNA bearing the code to
guide the translation

00:11:02.860 --> 00:11:05.660
and assemblage of
proteins from the building

00:11:05.660 --> 00:11:09.240
blocks of amino acids.

00:11:09.240 --> 00:11:12.880
Your genes on your DNA
are the sections of DNA

00:11:12.880 --> 00:11:15.740
that actually code for these
proteins that make up your cell

00:11:15.740 --> 00:11:18.890
walls, your antibodies,
your enzymes, your hormones,

00:11:18.890 --> 00:11:21.230
your muscles, basically you.

00:11:21.230 --> 00:11:24.490
As you probably know,
there are long stretches

00:11:24.490 --> 00:11:27.600
of DNA between the genes,
sections that don't actually

00:11:27.600 --> 00:11:29.010
code for proteins.

00:11:29.010 --> 00:11:33.490
We've learned that this
so-called junk DNA contains

00:11:33.490 --> 00:11:35.970
instructions for
gene regulation,

00:11:35.970 --> 00:11:39.270
like switches that turn
things on and off invisibly.

00:11:39.270 --> 00:11:41.970
I would say, unlike a Volkswagen
diesel exhaust system.

00:11:44.960 --> 00:11:48.850
The various combinations
of the four nucleotides

00:11:48.850 --> 00:11:53.730
form-- the four nucleotides form
64 distinct codes, or codons,

00:11:53.730 --> 00:11:57.070
that match up with 20
different amino acids.

00:11:57.070 --> 00:12:03.440
These amino acids,
sorry, form the proteins

00:12:03.440 --> 00:12:05.460
that form your body and
shape your behavior.

00:12:05.460 --> 00:12:06.850
But think about it.

00:12:06.850 --> 00:12:10.130
Four nucleotides,
20 amino acids,

00:12:10.130 --> 00:12:13.570
there are hundreds of naturally
occurring amino acids out there

00:12:13.570 --> 00:12:15.560
that are just left on the table.

00:12:15.560 --> 00:12:18.250
What if we could recruit
some of those amino acids

00:12:18.250 --> 00:12:19.910
to make new proteins?

00:12:19.910 --> 00:12:22.300
What if we could make more
effective medicines with them?

00:12:22.300 --> 00:12:24.410
What if we could make new fuels?

00:12:24.410 --> 00:12:28.090
If we had a larger
vocabulary of nucleotides,

00:12:28.090 --> 00:12:30.630
could we deploy DNA
to make new things?

00:12:30.630 --> 00:12:33.980
But the first question is, can
we even add nucleotides to DNA

00:12:33.980 --> 00:12:35.570
and get it to work?

00:12:35.570 --> 00:12:38.350
And that's exactly what Floyd
Romesberg's lab at the Scripps

00:12:38.350 --> 00:12:40.250
Research Institute has done.

00:12:40.250 --> 00:12:42.270
As you'll hear
today, he succeeded

00:12:42.270 --> 00:12:47.470
in creating a synthetic DNA with
two new nucleotides, x and y.

00:12:47.470 --> 00:12:49.760
With six letters
in your alphabet,

00:12:49.760 --> 00:12:53.510
there's a possibility now
of 216 codons that can now

00:12:53.510 --> 00:12:57.104
code up to 172 amino acids.

00:12:57.104 --> 00:12:58.520
And you can see
that the potential

00:12:58.520 --> 00:13:02.260
for creating new proteins
then explodes from here.

00:13:02.260 --> 00:13:05.940
It's as if the original
four letters limited us

00:13:05.940 --> 00:13:09.010
to the vocabulary of Hop on Pop.

00:13:09.010 --> 00:13:12.559
With all due respect to Dr.
Seuss who I love, with two more

00:13:12.559 --> 00:13:14.350
letters, we begin to
be able to write words

00:13:14.350 --> 00:13:16.050
that get us to Harry Potter.

00:13:16.050 --> 00:13:18.930
And who knows, with more
nucleotides, suddenly

00:13:18.930 --> 00:13:21.980
we can write Infinite Jest.

00:13:21.980 --> 00:13:25.230
And then there's your
mitochondrial DNA.

00:13:25.230 --> 00:13:27.560
If this is a cell,
here's your nuclear DNA

00:13:27.560 --> 00:13:28.980
right there in the red.

00:13:28.980 --> 00:13:31.910
These little bodies here
are your mitochondria.

00:13:31.910 --> 00:13:36.370
They are your generating
bodies in every cell.

00:13:36.370 --> 00:13:38.670
The mitochondria exist
outside of the nucleus.

00:13:38.670 --> 00:13:42.520
And they have their own DNA,
a primitive circular DNA

00:13:42.520 --> 00:13:45.930
that we probably inherited
from bacteria long, long ago.

00:13:45.930 --> 00:13:48.459
When I was in school, we use
to learn about mitochondria

00:13:48.459 --> 00:13:49.750
at the very end of the section.

00:13:49.750 --> 00:13:53.280
It was an afterthought.

00:13:53.280 --> 00:13:56.970
You inherit your nuclear
DNA from both your parents.

00:13:56.970 --> 00:14:00.040
Half your code comes from the
nucleus of your father's sperm

00:14:00.040 --> 00:14:02.520
and half from the nucleus
of your mother's egg.

00:14:02.520 --> 00:14:05.530
When they merge, your
nuclear DNA is formed.

00:14:05.530 --> 00:14:10.240
But the egg also carries
mitochondria in a cytoplasm.

00:14:10.240 --> 00:14:12.000
If you're a woman and
you have children,

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:13.970
you'll pass the same
mitochondria along

00:14:13.970 --> 00:14:15.400
to your children.

00:14:15.400 --> 00:14:17.370
In fact, the mitochondria
in your cells,

00:14:17.370 --> 00:14:20.330
whether you're a woman or a
man, are the same mitochondria

00:14:20.330 --> 00:14:22.650
in your mother's mother's
mother's mother's mother's

00:14:22.650 --> 00:14:25.840
line, all the way on back.

00:14:25.840 --> 00:14:28.850
So while your nuclear
DNA is inherited

00:14:28.850 --> 00:14:31.690
from all your ancestors,
your mitochondrial DNA

00:14:31.690 --> 00:14:33.620
comes from your
maternal lineage.

00:14:33.620 --> 00:14:39.660
This fact offers up
both promise and peril.

00:14:39.660 --> 00:14:42.120
Mitochondria are rather
prone to mutation.

00:14:42.120 --> 00:14:45.500
They lack some of the
genetic repair mechanisms

00:14:45.500 --> 00:14:47.310
that we have in nuclear DNA.

00:14:47.310 --> 00:14:50.450
And over time, over
millennia, the mutations

00:14:50.450 --> 00:14:53.270
allow us to track who
our ancestors were

00:14:53.270 --> 00:14:57.230
by looking at these mutation
patterns across populations.

00:14:57.230 --> 00:15:00.400
If you're a man
or a woman, we can

00:15:00.400 --> 00:15:02.540
trace your maternal
genetic lineage

00:15:02.540 --> 00:15:04.800
through your mitochondria.

00:15:04.800 --> 00:15:06.500
Now, men have a second option.

00:15:06.500 --> 00:15:08.730
We can also trace a
man's father's father's

00:15:08.730 --> 00:15:11.750
father's father's line
through his paternal lineage

00:15:11.750 --> 00:15:14.570
through his y chromosome.

00:15:14.570 --> 00:15:17.220
So I was curious about this.

00:15:17.220 --> 00:15:20.190
Back in 2009, I ordered
a gene testing kit

00:15:20.190 --> 00:15:22.800
from the National Genographic
Project, which we'll hear about

00:15:22.800 --> 00:15:24.750
from Spencer Wells today.

00:15:24.750 --> 00:15:27.730
You can see here that it's
just a simple cheek swab.

00:15:27.730 --> 00:15:30.840
I was curious about my own
lineage, but even more curious

00:15:30.840 --> 00:15:32.720
about my husband's lineage.

00:15:32.720 --> 00:15:34.010
Mark is African-American.

00:15:34.010 --> 00:15:37.040
He's a dead ringer
for Barack Obama.

00:15:37.040 --> 00:15:37.960
He is.

00:15:37.960 --> 00:15:39.460
You couldn't believe
how many people

00:15:39.460 --> 00:15:41.340
ask him if he is Barack Obama.

00:15:41.340 --> 00:15:45.330
Or even "are you
Osama?" has happened.

00:15:45.330 --> 00:15:47.750
What do you say?

00:15:47.750 --> 00:15:50.150
Like many Americans,
the records that

00:15:50.150 --> 00:15:53.090
would allow us to learn
about his family heritage

00:15:53.090 --> 00:15:54.750
just don't exist.

00:15:54.750 --> 00:15:57.170
So we were very curious
to look at his DNA

00:15:57.170 --> 00:16:01.130
and trace back to
his African roots.

00:16:01.130 --> 00:16:03.580
So first we did my
mitochondrial DNA.

00:16:03.580 --> 00:16:05.020
And here's what we found.

00:16:05.020 --> 00:16:08.120
Like all humans alive
today, my maternal line

00:16:08.120 --> 00:16:12.230
can be traced back to
Ethiopia 150,000 years ago.

00:16:12.230 --> 00:16:14.630
My maternal
ancestors left Africa

00:16:14.630 --> 00:16:16.820
in the second wave
of people who did

00:16:16.820 --> 00:16:18.410
through the Saudi
peninsula, probably

00:16:18.410 --> 00:16:21.480
following better game after
the Ice Age retreated.

00:16:21.480 --> 00:16:23.060
We came up through Central Asia.

00:16:23.060 --> 00:16:25.764
Then banged a left and into
Europe, where we probably

00:16:25.764 --> 00:16:27.430
would have bumped
into the Neanderthals.

00:16:27.430 --> 00:16:28.805
And John Hawks
will be telling us

00:16:28.805 --> 00:16:31.630
more about that
mixture in our lineage.

00:16:31.630 --> 00:16:34.380
And then I discovered,
not to my great surprise,

00:16:34.380 --> 00:16:37.820
that most of my genes hail
from Britain and Ireland.

00:16:37.820 --> 00:16:40.000
So then we ran Mark's DNA.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.450
Smart scientist and
feminist that I am,

00:16:42.450 --> 00:16:45.260
given the choice between
running his mitochondrial DNA

00:16:45.260 --> 00:16:50.590
or his y chromosome DNA, I said,
oh run your y chromosome DNA.

00:16:50.590 --> 00:16:54.030
We were so excited to see
where in Africa his family had

00:16:54.030 --> 00:16:55.130
come from.

00:16:55.130 --> 00:17:00.230
So when we got his results,
there was something of a shock.

00:17:00.230 --> 00:17:04.500
Mark's paternal lineage
is more Irish than my own.

00:17:04.500 --> 00:17:08.550
Now, I have to say we
were both dismayed.

00:17:08.550 --> 00:17:12.329
Because confronting
us in Mark's genes

00:17:12.329 --> 00:17:14.910
was a story we
weren't sure we liked,

00:17:14.910 --> 00:17:16.560
was the evidence of history.

00:17:16.560 --> 00:17:18.210
We were looking at
a legacy that spoke

00:17:18.210 --> 00:17:20.980
of slavery, of human
ownership probably,

00:17:20.980 --> 00:17:23.460
of race and gender dominance.

00:17:23.460 --> 00:17:25.359
It gave us some pause.

00:17:25.359 --> 00:17:28.069
Of course, if we thought
about it for half a second,

00:17:28.069 --> 00:17:30.020
Mark's paternal line
was not the place

00:17:30.020 --> 00:17:32.370
to look for his
African heritage.

00:17:32.370 --> 00:17:34.700
We should have checked
his maternal line.

00:17:34.700 --> 00:17:36.830
So that's what we did next.

00:17:36.830 --> 00:17:40.860
Mark's mitochondrial DNA, of
course, told a different story.

00:17:40.860 --> 00:17:42.600
His mitochondrial
mutations lead us

00:17:42.600 --> 00:17:46.380
to West Africa, probably
a Fulbe or Fulani tribe.

00:17:46.380 --> 00:17:49.480
If we reran those results
today, what is it,

00:17:49.480 --> 00:17:51.020
six years later,
we would probably

00:17:51.020 --> 00:17:52.720
get even greater specificity.

00:17:52.720 --> 00:17:55.020
Because the more people
who join this project,

00:17:55.020 --> 00:17:58.060
the better that it is able
to map human migration.

00:17:58.060 --> 00:18:01.430
But our experience finding
out about our heritage

00:18:01.430 --> 00:18:03.870
was, I would say, not
an unmixed blessing.

00:18:03.870 --> 00:18:06.430
And I think there are real
ethical quandaries when

00:18:06.430 --> 00:18:08.390
the genetic story
line contradicts

00:18:08.390 --> 00:18:11.840
our own personal or
our group's or tribe's

00:18:11.840 --> 00:18:15.050
identity and our beliefs
about our origins.

00:18:15.050 --> 00:18:16.640
But bringing up
the question of who

00:18:16.640 --> 00:18:20.680
has the right to determine
your group's heritage.

00:18:20.680 --> 00:18:23.880
There's also a therapeutic
side to mitochondria as well.

00:18:23.880 --> 00:18:25.630
Mitochondria can be diseased.

00:18:25.630 --> 00:18:27.770
They get flaws in
their own DNA, which

00:18:27.770 --> 00:18:29.220
can be devastating to health.

00:18:29.220 --> 00:18:31.390
We'll hear this afternoon
from Alison Murdoch

00:18:31.390 --> 00:18:33.860
of Newcastle University
about the brave new way

00:18:33.860 --> 00:18:36.130
to prevent mitochondrial
disease that

00:18:36.130 --> 00:18:37.990
is passed from mother to child.

00:18:37.990 --> 00:18:39.240
I'll give you a brief outline.

00:18:39.240 --> 00:18:41.042
There are a few ways to do this.

00:18:41.042 --> 00:18:42.510
This is one of them.

00:18:42.510 --> 00:18:45.470
If a woman has
defective mitochondria

00:18:45.470 --> 00:18:47.350
and she goes to have
a child, there's

00:18:47.350 --> 00:18:50.010
a strong likelihood
she'll pass it on.

00:18:50.010 --> 00:18:52.270
But once she and her
partner conceive,

00:18:52.270 --> 00:18:56.180
it's possible now to extract
their healthy nuclear DNA

00:18:56.180 --> 00:18:59.370
from the unhealthy egg.

00:18:59.370 --> 00:19:03.850
If another woman with healthy
mitochondria donates an egg,

00:19:03.850 --> 00:19:07.810
it's possible to strip out
the nuclear DNA from that one,

00:19:07.810 --> 00:19:10.950
and replace it with the
prospective parent's

00:19:10.950 --> 00:19:12.350
nuclear DNA.

00:19:12.350 --> 00:19:18.296
This gives the patient couple a
chance to have a healthy child.

00:19:18.296 --> 00:19:20.045
This has been done
successfully in humans.

00:19:20.045 --> 00:19:21.880
But as you can
imagine, the process

00:19:21.880 --> 00:19:25.080
of creating life from
three parents effectively,

00:19:25.080 --> 00:19:29.060
instead of the usual two, has
raised some ethical issues.

00:19:29.060 --> 00:19:30.940
Dr. Murdoch will tell
us about the technique

00:19:30.940 --> 00:19:32.420
and about the new
legislation that

00:19:32.420 --> 00:19:36.630
has made this legal in the UK.

00:19:36.630 --> 00:19:39.320
We are also joined today by
Jacob Corn from UCal Berkeley.

00:19:39.320 --> 00:19:40.820
He will talk about
the technique you

00:19:40.820 --> 00:19:43.850
may have heard of called CRISPR,
which makes it possible to,

00:19:43.850 --> 00:19:47.350
if you will, copy edit
the genome, specific genes

00:19:47.350 --> 00:19:50.510
or their transcription
factors, those on off switches

00:19:50.510 --> 00:19:52.150
in the junk DNA.

00:19:52.150 --> 00:19:54.130
This genome editing
has the potential

00:19:54.130 --> 00:19:57.320
not to just prevent as in
the mitochondrial scenario

00:19:57.320 --> 00:19:59.670
you just saw, but
actually to cure

00:19:59.670 --> 00:20:03.700
many diseases, such as cystic
fibrosis or sickle cell anemia.

00:20:03.700 --> 00:20:06.800
This of course has enormous
ethical implications.

00:20:06.800 --> 00:20:10.050
This April, scientists in
China reported the first CRISPR

00:20:10.050 --> 00:20:13.380
manipulation of a
non-viable human embryo.

00:20:13.380 --> 00:20:15.930
If you follow the news, you'll
know that many scientists have

00:20:15.930 --> 00:20:17.990
urged a moratorium
on applying CRISPR

00:20:17.990 --> 00:20:20.820
to human germ cells,
that's egg cells and sperm

00:20:20.820 --> 00:20:23.860
cells, until the full
implications can be discussed

00:20:23.860 --> 00:20:27.630
among scientific and
government organizations.

00:20:27.630 --> 00:20:30.870
But genetic engineering is
already being used to create

00:20:30.870 --> 00:20:33.800
transgenic animals,
sometimes known as Chimera, ,

00:20:33.800 --> 00:20:37.160
as for the mythical beast that
was a part lion, part eagle,

00:20:37.160 --> 00:20:38.270
part goat.

00:20:38.270 --> 00:20:41.130
In this case, a
human hormone gene

00:20:41.130 --> 00:20:43.460
is inserted into
a sheep's genome.

00:20:43.460 --> 00:20:47.050
The resulting transgenic sheep,
otherwise perfectly normal,

00:20:47.050 --> 00:20:50.100
then excretes the human
hormone into its milk,

00:20:50.100 --> 00:20:53.060
where it can be harvested to
create inexpensive medicines

00:20:53.060 --> 00:20:55.100
and potential vaccines.

00:20:55.100 --> 00:20:58.520
ZMapp, the experimental
Ebola drug,

00:20:58.520 --> 00:21:02.160
is a product of one of these
transgenic molecular pharmacy

00:21:02.160 --> 00:21:04.120
experiments.

00:21:04.120 --> 00:21:06.430
But it's not just medicines.

00:21:06.430 --> 00:21:09.940
You may have heard of the
spider goat, a regular goat who

00:21:09.940 --> 00:21:12.920
has received some DNA from
the golden orb spider.

00:21:12.920 --> 00:21:15.890
This cartoon from
Modern Farmer Magazine--

00:21:15.890 --> 00:21:20.120
believe it or not, wow it's
really modern-- is facetious.

00:21:20.120 --> 00:21:22.940
This goat does not
actually fling webs.

00:21:22.940 --> 00:21:25.390
But it does secrete
proteins into its milk

00:21:25.390 --> 00:21:28.880
that can be made into an elastic
fiber that is 10 times stronger

00:21:28.880 --> 00:21:29.960
than steel.

00:21:29.960 --> 00:21:32.966
Imagine that, elastic
and stronger than steel.

00:21:32.966 --> 00:21:34.340
This has the
potential to be made

00:21:34.340 --> 00:21:38.100
into body armor, parachutes,
surgical sutures,

00:21:38.100 --> 00:21:41.180
and other fantastic stuff.

00:21:41.180 --> 00:21:42.750
Other applications
of DNA science

00:21:42.750 --> 00:21:44.560
will allow us to
protect the planet.

00:21:44.560 --> 00:21:47.760
Many of you may have heard a
recent NPR broadcast discussing

00:21:47.760 --> 00:21:50.850
the technique of sampling
ocean water to measure

00:21:50.850 --> 00:21:52.860
the free floating
DNA that is cast off,

00:21:52.860 --> 00:21:56.870
just shed, by fish,
sharks, plants, whales,

00:21:56.870 --> 00:21:59.120
and other things as an
inexpensive way of creating

00:21:59.120 --> 00:22:01.470
a real time ocean census.

00:22:01.470 --> 00:22:04.160
This would allow us to follow
migrations of hard to track

00:22:04.160 --> 00:22:05.980
animals.

00:22:05.980 --> 00:22:10.606
Or take leeches, or more
specifically the leech's lunch.

00:22:10.606 --> 00:22:11.980
They turn out to
be quite useful.

00:22:11.980 --> 00:22:14.410
Because they suck the blood
from just about anything.

00:22:14.410 --> 00:22:17.550
And they provide a good
tool for censusing a forest.

00:22:17.550 --> 00:22:19.080
In the Yunnan
province of Vietnam,

00:22:19.080 --> 00:22:22.040
rangers collect leeches off
trees, note their locations

00:22:22.040 --> 00:22:24.140
with a GPS, bring
them back to the lab,

00:22:24.140 --> 00:22:25.410
and put them in the blender.

00:22:25.410 --> 00:22:29.920
If you then use a process
called metabarcoding, which

00:22:29.920 --> 00:22:31.810
amplifies sections
of DNA, you can tell

00:22:31.810 --> 00:22:33.940
what species are in the forest.

00:22:33.940 --> 00:22:37.690
And using this,
they've discovered

00:22:37.690 --> 00:22:42.050
that the shy and elusive saola,
aka the Asian unicorn, which

00:22:42.050 --> 00:22:47.590
has not been seen in the wild
since 1999, is not extinct.

00:22:47.590 --> 00:22:51.480
This information could be
used to protect its habitat.

00:22:51.480 --> 00:22:52.600
But could we go further?

00:22:52.600 --> 00:22:55.340
Could we, for example,
use DNA from one species,

00:22:55.340 --> 00:22:58.730
even an extinct species like the
mammoth, to help another one?

00:22:58.730 --> 00:23:01.290
Beth Shapiro of UCal Santa
Cruz will, for example,

00:23:01.290 --> 00:23:03.300
talk about how to
clone a mammoth

00:23:03.300 --> 00:23:05.520
and perhaps how
mammoth DNA might

00:23:05.520 --> 00:23:08.010
help to save modern day
elephants by increasing

00:23:08.010 --> 00:23:09.350
their range.

00:23:09.350 --> 00:23:12.280
We will also explore with Greg
Hampikian of the Innocence

00:23:12.280 --> 00:23:16.120
Project the use of DNA for
better or worse to solve

00:23:16.120 --> 00:23:17.380
crimes.

00:23:17.380 --> 00:23:19.270
While the intention is
to free the innocent

00:23:19.270 --> 00:23:21.090
and convict the
guilty, there's also

00:23:21.090 --> 00:23:24.250
the potential of flawed science
and bad forensic technique

00:23:24.250 --> 00:23:25.770
to convict the innocent.

00:23:25.770 --> 00:23:28.470
He'll be talking
to us about that.

00:23:28.470 --> 00:23:30.740
