00:26:38.340 --> 00:26:40.950
was mouthing off
about ancient DNA,

00:26:40.950 --> 00:26:44.750
which she was a
pioneer in producing

00:26:44.750 --> 00:26:46.680
progress in ancient DNA.

00:26:46.680 --> 00:26:48.620
And I was simply
asked by journalists

00:26:48.620 --> 00:26:51.920
whether we could go from
reading it to writing it.

00:26:51.920 --> 00:26:56.620
And I didn't have the common
sense to dodge that question.

00:26:56.620 --> 00:27:00.490
Anyway, that led to
us holding a meeting

00:27:00.490 --> 00:27:10.880
that Beth, a very tiny one at
Harvard, really was the star

00:27:10.880 --> 00:27:13.480
and really made
a big impression.

00:27:13.480 --> 00:27:18.660
And she has worked not
just with passenger pigeon,

00:27:18.660 --> 00:27:21.970
but with mammoths, giant
bears, camels, and horses,

00:27:21.970 --> 00:27:28.460
all the extinct large animals
that stimulates us when we

00:27:28.460 --> 00:27:31.270
were young kids and ever since.

00:27:31.270 --> 00:27:41.270
I think this kind of field
work is the stuff of Hollywood

00:27:41.270 --> 00:27:43.450
crusaders and so on.

00:27:43.450 --> 00:27:46.170
And she has this lovely book.

00:27:46.170 --> 00:27:48.880
I love the title, but
I also like the cover.

00:27:48.880 --> 00:27:53.030
Because it not only has
a mammoth and the words

00:27:53.030 --> 00:27:55.340
how to clone a mammoth,
but a mirror mammoth

00:27:55.340 --> 00:27:57.010
and how to clone
a mirror mammoth.

00:27:57.010 --> 00:28:02.520
So that's an inside
joke, but anyway.

00:28:02.520 --> 00:28:06.010
And Spencer Wells has a really
special place in my heart.

00:28:06.010 --> 00:28:10.450
In 2005, he was in
the process without,

00:28:10.450 --> 00:28:13.560
I think as he would say
without knowing it, founding

00:28:13.560 --> 00:28:17.800
the incredible field of
direct to consumer DNA

00:28:17.800 --> 00:28:21.000
analysis in the form of
the Genographic Project.

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:23.310
And he's been an explorer
in residence in the National

00:28:23.310 --> 00:28:31.230
Geographic, which I think all
of us admire that sort of work.

00:28:31.230 --> 00:28:34.050
And he's led that
project for 10 years.

00:28:34.050 --> 00:28:37.650
And we've already seen
some slides from that.

00:28:37.650 --> 00:28:39.120
But about that
time, I was involved

00:28:39.120 --> 00:28:43.870
in, a little after
that, with 23 and Me

00:28:43.870 --> 00:28:45.540
and with the Personal
Genome Project.

00:28:45.540 --> 00:28:48.220
And he helped us out
in those early days

00:28:48.220 --> 00:28:50.260
of the Personal Genome Project.

00:28:50.260 --> 00:28:53.860
And he's written many
books, such as-- here's

00:28:53.860 --> 00:28:56.960
one of the early ones
I read before I met him

00:28:56.960 --> 00:28:59.650
2002, The Journey Of Man.

00:28:59.650 --> 00:29:02.670
He's written two, the
start, Pandora's Seed.

00:29:02.670 --> 00:29:08.410
He began his PhD when he was
19 years old here at Harvard.

00:29:08.410 --> 00:29:13.300
And then both he and Beth spent
a considerable amount of time

00:29:13.300 --> 00:29:14.440
at Oxford.

00:29:14.440 --> 00:29:18.420
So without further ado,
we will begin with John.

00:29:18.420 --> 00:29:19.150
Thank you.

00:29:28.510 --> 00:29:32.150
-All right, so here we are.

00:29:32.150 --> 00:29:35.000
I've just come from
Gibraltar, where

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:37.850
I was at a meeting with--
Gibraltar's a cool place

00:29:37.850 --> 00:29:39.810
for Neanderthals
for lots of reasons.

00:29:39.810 --> 00:29:42.960
Most notably because of
Gorham's and Vanguard Caves,

00:29:42.960 --> 00:29:46.550
which are some of the most
important sites representing

00:29:46.550 --> 00:29:49.190
later Neanderthals,
and really even up

00:29:49.190 --> 00:29:51.190
to the end of their existence.

00:29:51.190 --> 00:29:55.420
Last year at Gorham's Cave was
announced the first known case

00:29:55.420 --> 00:29:58.750
of Neanderthals engraving
on the walls of a cave.

00:29:58.750 --> 00:30:02.120
And so we now have the
Neanderthal hash tag

00:30:02.120 --> 00:30:07.440
as a legacy of their
social media savvy.

00:30:07.440 --> 00:30:10.080
It's a really exciting place,
and I love going there.

00:30:10.080 --> 00:30:13.210
And the exciting part
about this latest trip

00:30:13.210 --> 00:30:16.720
was that we had a
meeting that involved

00:30:16.720 --> 00:30:20.030
some of the really big
names in understanding

00:30:20.030 --> 00:30:24.090
Neanderthals and their
contribution to our evolution.

00:30:24.090 --> 00:30:27.440
People like Milford Wolpoff,
Chris Stringer, Erik Trinkaus,

00:30:27.440 --> 00:30:31.150
people that in the '90s were
at each other's throats.

00:30:31.150 --> 00:30:34.760
Because they disagreed about
almost everything fundamental

00:30:34.760 --> 00:30:38.220
about the way that modern
humans originated and how

00:30:38.220 --> 00:30:41.920
Neanderthals did or didn't
contribute to our populations.

00:30:41.920 --> 00:30:44.170
And the thing that was
exciting about this last week

00:30:44.170 --> 00:30:47.250
for me is I put
together, as a summary

00:30:47.250 --> 00:30:51.050
to the conference,
a list of facts

00:30:51.050 --> 00:30:55.060
that now everyone involved in
understanding human evolution

00:30:55.060 --> 00:30:57.220
universally agrees on.

00:30:57.220 --> 00:31:00.130
And the thing about
it is that these facts

00:31:00.130 --> 00:31:01.680
are facts that
have largely arisen

00:31:01.680 --> 00:31:05.070
through the application
of ancient DNA technology

00:31:05.070 --> 00:31:07.270
to ancient fossil remains.

00:31:07.270 --> 00:31:09.550
It is hard to
overstate the extent

00:31:09.550 --> 00:31:11.910
to which our present
understanding

00:31:11.910 --> 00:31:14.190
of human evolution has emerged.

00:31:14.190 --> 00:31:16.750
Especially the later
phases of human evolution

00:31:16.750 --> 00:31:19.760
has emerged within
the last 10 years.

00:31:19.760 --> 00:31:23.510
And in large part due to
our systematic investigation

00:31:23.510 --> 00:31:26.750
of the microscopic and
submicroscopic aspects

00:31:26.750 --> 00:31:29.330
of fossils, including
ancient DNA.

00:31:29.330 --> 00:31:32.360
So I thought that one
way to talk about the way

00:31:32.360 --> 00:31:35.380
that we've changed our
understanding of evolution

00:31:35.380 --> 00:31:39.640
by looking at ancient remains
and the DNA in ancient remains

00:31:39.640 --> 00:31:41.520
is to go through this list.

00:31:41.520 --> 00:31:45.520
And I can tell you that the
leading people in the field who

00:31:45.520 --> 00:31:48.170
have been leaders for
30 years last week

00:31:48.170 --> 00:31:50.780
saw this list and
all signed off on it.

00:31:50.780 --> 00:31:53.427
So I tell you that
this is really stuff

00:31:53.427 --> 00:31:54.385
that we now understand.

00:31:57.230 --> 00:31:58.960
So one is that
living people today

00:31:58.960 --> 00:32:00.700
have Neanderthal ancestors.

00:32:00.700 --> 00:32:02.580
And many of you have
heard that, of course,

00:32:02.580 --> 00:32:04.950
living Europeans,
living East Asians,

00:32:04.950 --> 00:32:09.290
living Native American
peoples have around 3% or so

00:32:09.290 --> 00:32:11.030
of Neanderthal ancestry.

00:32:11.030 --> 00:32:12.970
And peoples in
sub-Saharan Africa

00:32:12.970 --> 00:32:15.510
don't have that kind of level.

00:32:15.510 --> 00:32:19.020
But nevertheless, because humans
are all geologically hugely

00:32:19.020 --> 00:32:21.565
connected-- if you count
back your ancestors,

00:32:21.565 --> 00:32:24.700
it doubles every
generation back in time

00:32:24.700 --> 00:32:28.270
until it encompasses nearly
the entire human population.

00:32:28.270 --> 00:32:31.490
Living sub-Saharan Africans
have Neanderthal ancestors,

00:32:31.490 --> 00:32:34.310
even though their genetic
component from Neanderthals

00:32:34.310 --> 00:32:35.360
is much lower.

00:32:35.360 --> 00:32:39.340
Living people today come in some
small part from Neanderthals.

00:32:39.340 --> 00:32:42.360
But this contribution
is regionally

00:32:42.360 --> 00:32:45.950
distributed among living
people in surprising ways.

00:32:45.950 --> 00:32:48.740
So this is a chart that
shows shared derived

00:32:48.740 --> 00:32:51.720
alleles with Neanderthals,
so mutations people have

00:32:51.720 --> 00:32:53.500
in common with Neanderthals.

00:32:53.500 --> 00:32:55.780
And there's a lot of
them in our genomes.

00:32:55.780 --> 00:32:58.490
But the difference between
different populations

00:32:58.490 --> 00:33:01.110
is the signature that
some of these populations

00:33:01.110 --> 00:33:03.290
have more Neanderthal
than others.

00:33:03.290 --> 00:33:06.020
That's where we get
this 3% figure from.

00:33:06.020 --> 00:33:08.250
And the higher you
are in this chart,

00:33:08.250 --> 00:33:10.700
the more Neanderthal you are.

00:33:10.700 --> 00:33:13.240
East Asians, are
more Neanderthal

00:33:13.240 --> 00:33:14.880
derived than Europeans.

00:33:14.880 --> 00:33:16.940
They have a little
more on average.

00:33:16.940 --> 00:33:19.470
This is counterintuitive,
because Neanderthals

00:33:19.470 --> 00:33:22.310
are known for being a
Western Eur-Asian population.

00:33:22.310 --> 00:33:24.030
They're known best from Europe.

00:33:24.030 --> 00:33:28.720
So we've discovered that
this population has a legacy.

00:33:28.720 --> 00:33:31.220
We've discovered that this
legacy is not distributed

00:33:31.220 --> 00:33:32.722
as we might have anticipated.

00:33:32.722 --> 00:33:33.805
This is super interesting.

00:33:37.580 --> 00:33:40.430
DNA evidence has come from
Neanderthals, not only

00:33:40.430 --> 00:33:42.575
across their European range.

00:33:42.575 --> 00:33:43.950
And these are all
sites that have

00:33:43.950 --> 00:33:46.720
generated whole mitochondrial
genomes of Neanderthals.

00:33:46.720 --> 00:33:49.580
And there's a few more now
than when I made the chart.

00:33:49.580 --> 00:33:52.420
But also surprisingly
across a Central Asian

00:33:52.420 --> 00:33:55.650
range that we did not
formerly recognize

00:33:55.650 --> 00:33:57.990
as being Neanderthal central.

00:33:57.990 --> 00:34:00.770
We now think that this is
the hotbed of Neanderthals.

00:34:00.770 --> 00:34:03.250
And that the European
Neanderthal population

00:34:03.250 --> 00:34:05.230
was continually
being replenished

00:34:05.230 --> 00:34:07.710
from this eastern source.

00:34:07.710 --> 00:34:09.270
But the other thing
that we've begun

00:34:09.270 --> 00:34:11.280
to appreciate with
the investigation

00:34:11.280 --> 00:34:15.760
of ancient remains that are
less morphologically useful,

00:34:15.760 --> 00:34:19.820
the skulls and whole
skeletons tell us immediately

00:34:19.820 --> 00:34:21.050
what something looks like.

00:34:21.050 --> 00:34:24.840
But most of the fossil
record is fragments.

00:34:24.840 --> 00:34:28.000
And in particular,
those fragments

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:30.310
now are generating super
interesting evidence

00:34:30.310 --> 00:34:32.219
about ancient populations.

00:34:32.219 --> 00:34:33.799
So this is Denisova Cave.

00:34:33.799 --> 00:34:35.340
I've had the privilege
of going there

00:34:35.340 --> 00:34:36.964
are a number of times
at the invitation

00:34:36.964 --> 00:34:39.199
of the Russian
Academy of Sciences.

00:34:39.199 --> 00:34:41.639
It's a beautiful place
with important excavations

00:34:41.639 --> 00:34:44.159
that cover the
last 120,000 years

00:34:44.159 --> 00:34:47.670
of archaeological history.

00:34:47.670 --> 00:34:56.230
And this cave has produced
in one little pinky

00:34:56.230 --> 00:35:01.370
an entire genome at what is
now high coverage that tells us

00:35:01.370 --> 00:35:03.660
about the prehistory
of a population

00:35:03.660 --> 00:35:06.310
that archaeologists did
not suspect existed,

00:35:06.310 --> 00:35:11.710
a population that is as
distinct from known Neanderthals

00:35:11.710 --> 00:35:15.550
as the most different living
people are from each other.

00:35:15.550 --> 00:35:18.730
So there was an ancient
population represented

00:35:18.730 --> 00:35:20.570
at this place, Denisova Cave.

00:35:20.570 --> 00:35:24.010
This aging population we've
begun to call the Denisovans.

00:35:24.010 --> 00:35:26.300
And the Denisovans
have contributed

00:35:26.300 --> 00:35:30.530
their genetic heritage to some
human populations, largely

00:35:30.530 --> 00:35:33.830
the populations of Australia
and Highland New Guinea,

00:35:33.830 --> 00:35:36.950
but in a very small fraction
across most of Eastern

00:35:36.950 --> 00:35:38.560
Asia and the new world.

00:35:38.560 --> 00:35:44.190
So we've got not one, but
multiple ancient populations

00:35:44.190 --> 00:35:47.520
that we've now sampled
with ancient DNA.

00:35:47.520 --> 00:35:49.730
And they co-existed.

00:35:49.730 --> 00:35:52.080
We didn't expect this at all.

00:35:52.080 --> 00:35:54.530
And the idea that you would
have bone fragments that

00:35:54.530 --> 00:35:56.970
were basically
useless for any kind

00:35:56.970 --> 00:36:00.340
of morphological
understanding create what

00:36:00.340 --> 00:36:04.110
is denser evidence of the
heritage of an ancient group

00:36:04.110 --> 00:36:07.380
than we have gotten
from most living people

00:36:07.380 --> 00:36:09.290
is just astounding.

00:36:09.290 --> 00:36:11.860
This is not only true of the
Neanderthals and Denisovans.

00:36:11.860 --> 00:36:14.760
We can now look inside
of human genomes

00:36:14.760 --> 00:36:17.330
and make some
estimation of what we

00:36:17.330 --> 00:36:20.870
call ghost lineages,
ancient populations that

00:36:20.870 --> 00:36:23.530
contributed to each other.

00:36:23.530 --> 00:36:27.300
If we look at my field guide
to Pleistocene hookups,

00:36:27.300 --> 00:36:30.310
you will see that we understand
quite an enormous amount

00:36:30.310 --> 00:36:33.770
about the contributions
of different populations

00:36:33.770 --> 00:36:35.620
to each other in the past.

00:36:35.620 --> 00:36:39.270
The Denisovan population,
which is known only

00:36:39.270 --> 00:36:41.370
from a pinky and
two teeth, we know

00:36:41.370 --> 00:36:45.010
from looking at that genome has
contributions from a mystery

00:36:45.010 --> 00:36:49.050
population, a ghost lineage of
ancient humans, that separated

00:36:49.050 --> 00:36:52.480
from the main line of our
human evolutionary history

00:36:52.480 --> 00:36:55.990
more than a million years
ago, much more differentiated

00:36:55.990 --> 00:36:57.500
than Neanderthals,
and Denisovans,

00:36:57.500 --> 00:36:59.370
and modern humans
are from each other.

00:36:59.370 --> 00:37:02.350
We know from looking within
the genomes of living Africans,

00:37:02.350 --> 00:37:06.710
using the same signatures that
we recognize from ancient genes

00:37:06.710 --> 00:37:10.300
to recognize the contribution
of ancient populations.

00:37:10.300 --> 00:37:13.350
We can now look for those
same signatures in cases

00:37:13.350 --> 00:37:15.440
where the ancient
genes don't exist.

00:37:15.440 --> 00:37:19.760
And we can find ancient African
populations as differentiated

00:37:19.760 --> 00:37:23.340
as they are from living
people, as Neanderthals

00:37:23.340 --> 00:37:25.610
are from living people,
that have contributed

00:37:25.610 --> 00:37:28.200
to living African populations.

00:37:28.200 --> 00:37:32.400
Our evolutionary
history involves

00:37:32.400 --> 00:37:35.250
many archaic and
modern groups of humans

00:37:35.250 --> 00:37:37.780
that in every instance
we have discovered

00:37:37.780 --> 00:37:39.820
interbred with each
other and contributed

00:37:39.820 --> 00:37:44.390
to later populations,
mostly to a minor degree.

00:37:44.390 --> 00:37:46.890
This is a very different
picture of our evolution

00:37:46.890 --> 00:37:50.080
than we had in the year 2005.

00:37:50.080 --> 00:37:51.640
No one would have
said that this is

00:37:51.640 --> 00:37:53.920
what our evolutionary
history looked like.

00:37:53.920 --> 00:37:56.970
It's looking much more like
a braided stream in which you

00:37:56.970 --> 00:38:00.180
have these populations that
are separated for quite

00:38:00.180 --> 00:38:03.160
a long time, maybe with
some minimal interbreeding

00:38:03.160 --> 00:38:04.160
between them.

00:38:04.160 --> 00:38:07.690
But populations that have become
quite inbred, quite separate

00:38:07.690 --> 00:38:08.650
from each other.

00:38:08.650 --> 00:38:12.460
And sometimes later in time
they come back into contact

00:38:12.460 --> 00:38:13.800
to contribute to each other.

00:38:13.800 --> 00:38:18.000
Sometimes of course, they
must have gone extinct.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:20.520
This goes now back
as far in time

00:38:20.520 --> 00:38:23.270
as 400,000 years
where the earliest

00:38:23.270 --> 00:38:25.725
hominin nuclear and
mitochondrial DNA

00:38:25.725 --> 00:38:27.766
has been recovered from
a site called Sima de los

00:38:27.766 --> 00:38:31.380
Huesos, which is at the moment
the most productive hominin

00:38:31.380 --> 00:38:33.290
fossil site in the
world for producing

00:38:33.290 --> 00:38:37.190
skeletal remains of what
we now recognize from DNA

00:38:37.190 --> 00:38:40.890
are fundamentally the ancestors
of European Neanderthals.

00:38:40.890 --> 00:38:45.570
So there is so much to learn
from these ancient specimens

00:38:45.570 --> 00:38:47.540
that we're now
through technology

00:38:47.540 --> 00:38:49.790
being able to recover.

00:38:49.790 --> 00:38:52.830
All right, when we look at
these ancient populations,

00:38:52.830 --> 00:38:54.230
I like this tree.

00:38:54.230 --> 00:38:56.560
It's a cluster.

00:38:56.560 --> 00:38:59.130
And it doesn't really recognize
all of the complexities

00:38:59.130 --> 00:39:00.050
of this relationship.

00:39:00.050 --> 00:39:02.090
But it's a good measure
of genetic difference.

00:39:02.090 --> 00:39:04.780
Because when we look at the
known Neanderthal nuclear

00:39:04.780 --> 00:39:08.000
sequences, we now have a
substantial additional sequence

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:10.150
in this from the Altai.

00:39:10.150 --> 00:39:12.580
They are really homogeneous.

00:39:12.580 --> 00:39:15.120
There's very little genetic
difference among them

00:39:15.120 --> 00:39:17.150
compared to the genetic
differences among living

00:39:17.150 --> 00:39:20.770
peoples and compared to the
genetic difference between them

00:39:20.770 --> 00:39:22.190
and the Denisovans.

00:39:22.190 --> 00:39:25.700
So Neanderthals are inbred.

00:39:25.700 --> 00:39:28.770
And when we look at particular
Neanderthal specimens,

00:39:28.770 --> 00:39:31.180
this is a graph from a
paper describing the Altai

00:39:31.180 --> 00:39:35.540
Neanderthal specimen, in
some cases the inbreeding is

00:39:35.540 --> 00:39:36.310
profound.

00:39:36.310 --> 00:39:39.510
This individual was
actually inbred.

00:39:39.510 --> 00:39:42.840
His or-- I believe it's a
female-- her parents were

00:39:42.840 --> 00:39:46.320
in fact relatives and second
degree relatives, something

00:39:46.320 --> 00:39:51.410
like uncle niece or
grandfather granddaughter.

00:39:51.410 --> 00:39:54.080
This is highly inbred.

00:39:54.080 --> 00:39:58.740
And when we look generally
at ancient human populations,

00:39:58.740 --> 00:40:01.120
including-- this is
a chart that shows

00:40:01.120 --> 00:40:05.770
population size estimates over
time, going back in the past.

00:40:05.770 --> 00:40:08.870
And the Neanderthals,
the Denisovans,

00:40:08.870 --> 00:40:12.740
and in fact, the ancestors
of most modern human groups

00:40:12.740 --> 00:40:15.290
have passed through
very small stages

00:40:15.290 --> 00:40:18.160
where they were highly
endogamous, highly inbred.

00:40:18.160 --> 00:40:20.360
It's something that we've
learned from ancient DNA

00:40:20.360 --> 00:40:23.380
that every population that
we know about that existed

00:40:23.380 --> 00:40:25.870
in humans before
40,000 years ago

00:40:25.870 --> 00:40:29.030
was much more inbred
than living people are.

00:40:29.030 --> 00:40:33.580
We come from a heritage that
is many small groups that

00:40:33.580 --> 00:40:36.870
were dynamic, that were
continually limited

00:40:36.870 --> 00:40:39.570
in their genetic
variability by the expansion

00:40:39.570 --> 00:40:42.770
and probably replacement
of many small populations

00:40:42.770 --> 00:40:48.830
and the rejoining of these
populations later in time.

00:40:48.830 --> 00:40:51.170
This point goes to address that.

00:40:51.170 --> 00:40:53.510
I mentioned earlier, we've
got Neanderthal sequences

00:40:53.510 --> 00:40:55.610
from Central Asia
and from Europe.

00:40:55.610 --> 00:40:58.030
What we now know is
that the European ones

00:40:58.030 --> 00:40:59.950
seem to differentiate
between those

00:40:59.950 --> 00:41:02.280
that existed before
50,000 years ago

00:41:02.280 --> 00:41:05.010
and those that existed
after 50,000 years ago.

00:41:05.010 --> 00:41:07.300
And the ones later seem
to have been replenished

00:41:07.300 --> 00:41:10.280
from probably a Central Asian
source, as far as we understand

00:41:10.280 --> 00:41:11.190
the data.

00:41:11.190 --> 00:41:13.010
In other words,
Neanderthals were not

00:41:13.010 --> 00:41:17.300
a static population that was
sitting in Europe well adapted

00:41:17.300 --> 00:41:18.400
to the Ice Ages.

00:41:18.400 --> 00:41:20.130
It was a dynamic population.

00:41:20.130 --> 00:41:22.980
It was a population that ranged
over large areas of space

00:41:22.980 --> 00:41:25.680
and continually expanded
across them with groups

00:41:25.680 --> 00:41:27.040
replacing other groups.

00:41:27.040 --> 00:41:30.170
We're looking at human
evolutionary history that

00:41:30.170 --> 00:41:33.540
is much more dynamic
than we anticipated just

00:41:33.540 --> 00:41:35.280
by looking at fossil remains.

00:41:35.280 --> 00:41:38.400
Looking at the fossils, we
tended to connect the dots

00:41:38.400 --> 00:41:40.620
and say as we go back
in the past, what

00:41:40.620 --> 00:41:42.630
we're doing is we're
linking ancestors

00:41:42.630 --> 00:41:43.710
and their descendants.

00:41:43.710 --> 00:41:47.510
What we now understand is
that we cannot link ancestors

00:41:47.510 --> 00:41:49.320
and descendants in
any direct sense.

00:41:49.320 --> 00:41:53.840
What we're linking is points
along this very complex

00:41:53.840 --> 00:41:57.140
reticulate structure,
some of which

00:41:57.140 --> 00:41:58.600
are separated for a while.

00:41:58.600 --> 00:42:01.470
And so maybe maintain a
morphological contiguity

00:42:01.470 --> 00:42:02.320
with each other.

00:42:02.320 --> 00:42:06.150
But many of which are not
particularly closely connected.

00:42:06.150 --> 00:42:09.780
Many of the things that we
think in anatomical terms were

00:42:09.780 --> 00:42:12.950
probably important might be
epiphenomenon of selection

00:42:12.950 --> 00:42:14.600
maintaining them
over time within

00:42:14.600 --> 00:42:16.020
these geographic regions.

00:42:19.390 --> 00:42:23.160
When we go to more recent
phases of our human evolutionary

00:42:23.160 --> 00:42:27.090
history, ancient DNA has
been equal in its import.

00:42:27.090 --> 00:42:29.250
Although to my colleagues
who are anthropologists

00:42:29.250 --> 00:42:31.770
working in human evolution,
they haven't yet quite

00:42:31.770 --> 00:42:35.030
come to as good a grip of
the importance of this.

00:42:35.030 --> 00:42:38.130
This is the earliest known
modern European skull

00:42:38.130 --> 00:42:39.060
in Europe.

00:42:39.060 --> 00:42:42.620
It's from a Romanian site called
Oase, which is deep in a cave

00:42:42.620 --> 00:42:45.110
that you have to get
under water dive through

00:42:45.110 --> 00:42:48.360
to get to where the
cranial remains are.

00:42:48.360 --> 00:42:52.010
When we look at Oase
compared to-- this

00:42:52.010 --> 00:42:56.310
is a chart that shows its
genetic similarity to Europeans

00:42:56.310 --> 00:42:59.010
at the top and Asians and
Native American populations

00:42:59.010 --> 00:42:59.690
the bottom.

00:42:59.690 --> 00:43:02.340
You can see that
this Oase individual

00:43:02.340 --> 00:43:06.350
is closer to the Asians
than it is to Europeans.

00:43:06.350 --> 00:43:08.225
The first modern Europeans
were not European.

00:43:10.810 --> 00:43:12.970
When you look at
this skull compared

00:43:12.970 --> 00:43:15.050
to other ancient
specimens, these

00:43:15.050 --> 00:43:17.990
are all ancient DNA specimens
from slightly later phases

00:43:17.990 --> 00:43:21.040
of evolution, you can see that
it's about equally related

00:43:21.040 --> 00:43:24.450
to them as it is to Asians
and Native Americans.

00:43:24.450 --> 00:43:27.650
Our archaeological
record of modern humans,

00:43:27.650 --> 00:43:30.900
the one that we thought
was sampling the ancestors

00:43:30.900 --> 00:43:35.320
of today's Europeans, today's
Asians, and so on, doesn't.

00:43:35.320 --> 00:43:39.510
It samples ancient populations
that by and large have not

00:43:39.510 --> 00:43:43.020
contributed to great degree
to any living people.

00:43:43.020 --> 00:43:46.600
This is a chart of the
mitochondrial haplotypes found

00:43:46.600 --> 00:43:49.150
in the hunter
gatherers that lived

00:43:49.150 --> 00:43:51.190
before the advent of
farming in Europe.

00:43:51.190 --> 00:43:54.010
83% of them have a
haplogroup mitochondrial

00:43:54.010 --> 00:43:59.910
called haplogroup U. This is the
same proportions of haplogroups

00:43:59.910 --> 00:44:02.610
in the first farmers in Europe.

00:44:02.610 --> 00:44:04.730
And as you can see,
that haplogroup U,

00:44:04.730 --> 00:44:07.850
which was 83% of this
population, is only 12%

00:44:07.850 --> 00:44:08.790
of this one.

00:44:08.790 --> 00:44:11.970
There are new haplotypes,
including mine, haplogroup H,

00:44:11.970 --> 00:44:15.650
that arrived in Europe
after the advent of farming.

00:44:15.650 --> 00:44:19.450
So Europe is a dynamic place.

00:44:19.450 --> 00:44:23.000
And we now have through ancient
DNA time slices of this.

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:26.220
And we can show that the
ancestors that we once

00:44:26.220 --> 00:44:28.490
were thinking we're
tracing our descent

00:44:28.490 --> 00:44:30.590
from these first
Europeans actually

00:44:30.590 --> 00:44:34.750
have almost nothing to do with
today's European populations.

00:44:34.750 --> 00:44:40.670
And Europe has undergone a
succession of colonizations

00:44:40.670 --> 00:44:42.270
from other places.

00:44:42.270 --> 00:44:44.780
This is almost certainly
not unique to Europe.

00:44:44.780 --> 00:44:47.510
This is almost certainly the
history of recent humans,

00:44:47.510 --> 00:44:49.810
that our population
has been dynamic.

00:44:49.810 --> 00:44:51.770
And the ancient
archaeological remains

00:44:51.770 --> 00:44:55.960
that we have are
by and large not

00:44:55.960 --> 00:44:59.340
the ancestors of living people.

00:44:59.340 --> 00:45:00.840
So of course, the
other side of that

00:45:00.840 --> 00:45:03.520
is that once we look
at ancient DNA remains,

00:45:03.520 --> 00:45:05.840
we can get a better
resolution on how

00:45:05.840 --> 00:45:10.680
those ancient DNA remains are
connected to living people.

00:45:10.680 --> 00:45:13.670
And through that
process, reconstruct

00:45:13.670 --> 00:45:15.710
the ancestral populations.

00:45:15.710 --> 00:45:18.710
So this is some of the
work from David Reich's lab

00:45:18.710 --> 00:45:19.790
here at Harvard.

00:45:19.790 --> 00:45:22.370
And you can see that there
is a reconstruction here

00:45:22.370 --> 00:45:26.550
of where Europeans came from
based on what we've learned

00:45:26.550 --> 00:45:29.440
from ancient genomes from
Europe and from other parts

00:45:29.440 --> 00:45:30.400
of the world.

00:45:30.400 --> 00:45:33.140
And you can start to say
that there were populations

00:45:33.140 --> 00:45:36.430
in the past that we
haven't necessarily

00:45:36.430 --> 00:45:39.420
sampled well
archaeologically that are

00:45:39.420 --> 00:45:42.940
source populations that have
contributed to today's people

00:45:42.940 --> 00:45:44.400
through mixture.

00:45:44.400 --> 00:45:45.790
And we can start
to get a picture

00:45:45.790 --> 00:45:47.920
of how those mixtures happened.

00:45:47.920 --> 00:45:50.570
This is all happening
through ancient DNA.

00:45:50.570 --> 00:45:53.650
As a consequence, when we look
at recent prehistoric humans,

00:45:53.650 --> 00:45:56.380
the kinds of cultural
changes that we see-- I'm

00:45:56.380 --> 00:45:58.550
going to use the example
of language shifts.

00:45:58.550 --> 00:46:00.660
But things like the
advent of farming,

00:46:00.660 --> 00:46:02.792
things like the advent
of the Bronze Age,

00:46:02.792 --> 00:46:04.250
the things that
archaeologists have

00:46:04.250 --> 00:46:08.340
been trying to track for more
than 150 years, those things we

00:46:08.340 --> 00:46:11.620
now recognize are in
large part mediated

00:46:11.620 --> 00:46:14.770
by the growth and
dispersal of relatively

00:46:14.770 --> 00:46:17.050
consanguineous populations.

00:46:17.050 --> 00:46:19.800
These are people that actually
expanded and carried with them

00:46:19.800 --> 00:46:22.610
stuff, and the ways
that they made things,

00:46:22.610 --> 00:46:24.295
and the languages they used.

00:46:24.295 --> 00:46:26.420
And of course, we've had
this idea for a long time.

00:46:26.420 --> 00:46:28.790
Of course, many of you
know the Proto-European

00:46:28.790 --> 00:46:32.000
as an ancestor of today's
Indo-European languages

00:46:32.000 --> 00:46:35.740
is reconstructed to have
originated somewhere

00:46:35.740 --> 00:46:37.030
in Central Asia.

00:46:37.030 --> 00:46:40.020
And we've studied
the language shifts

00:46:40.020 --> 00:46:42.570
that have happened through
probably the spread

00:46:42.570 --> 00:46:43.700
of these language groups.

00:46:43.700 --> 00:46:47.750
For example, the Celtic
languages into Western Europe,

00:46:47.750 --> 00:46:50.440
the way that people must-- the
way that languages must have

00:46:50.440 --> 00:46:56.330
moved and the Iranian languages
of Central Asia and into India.

00:46:56.330 --> 00:47:00.190
We now can recognize that
these sorts of phenomenon

00:47:00.190 --> 00:47:02.040
were actually
mediated by people.

00:47:02.040 --> 00:47:03.560
The people were moving.

00:47:03.560 --> 00:47:09.260
And that phenomenon that we can
see in recent prehistoric times

00:47:09.260 --> 00:47:12.590
was almost certainly the mode
of dispersal of ancient people

00:47:12.590 --> 00:47:18.240
long before we have these kinds
of archaeological records.

00:47:18.240 --> 00:47:19.990
Well, we've learned
not only about the way

00:47:19.990 --> 00:47:21.490
that populations
move and interact.

00:47:21.490 --> 00:47:24.115
We've learned about the way that
these populations have changed

00:47:24.115 --> 00:47:25.250
through natural selection.

00:47:25.250 --> 00:47:27.150
One of the realizations
that we have had,

00:47:27.150 --> 00:47:32.800
and I'm using slide of Tibet
here to remind myself that,

00:47:32.800 --> 00:47:35.660
is that genes that we've gotten
from these ancient groups

00:47:35.660 --> 00:47:38.270
sometimes are useful
to us and actually

00:47:38.270 --> 00:47:41.550
make us able to do things
that we wouldn't do otherwise.

00:47:41.550 --> 00:47:44.810
In Tibet, people are highly
able to live at high altitude

00:47:44.810 --> 00:47:46.460
and to have more
normal birth weight

00:47:46.460 --> 00:47:49.330
children at high altitude
by function of changes

00:47:49.330 --> 00:47:52.730
to their circulatory system,
changes to their blood.

00:47:52.730 --> 00:47:55.750
One gene involved in
this, a gene called EPAS1,

00:47:55.750 --> 00:47:58.870
has an allele which is common
in Tibetan peoples, which

00:47:58.870 --> 00:48:01.810
is very rare in nearby
peoples in lowland China.

00:48:01.810 --> 00:48:05.040
And that this allele's
most close relatives

00:48:05.040 --> 00:48:08.430
that we know of in anywhere,
any archaeological or living

00:48:08.430 --> 00:48:11.830
population, are the
Denisova genome.

00:48:11.830 --> 00:48:14.060
So we have here the
origination of what

00:48:14.060 --> 00:48:16.270
is today an effective
adaptation to a very

00:48:16.270 --> 00:48:18.200
unique extreme environment.

00:48:18.200 --> 00:48:20.100
We don't know the
Denisovans were

00:48:20.100 --> 00:48:21.970
living in the highland
plateau of Tibet.

00:48:21.970 --> 00:48:24.310
We don't have an archaeological
record put in there.

00:48:24.310 --> 00:48:27.430
But we can say that the
raw material of variation

00:48:27.430 --> 00:48:31.230
that came from this population
was made use of in later humans

00:48:31.230 --> 00:48:33.220
to adapt to this
extreme environment.

00:48:33.220 --> 00:48:37.150
We're in other words, changing
as a function of interbreeding

00:48:37.150 --> 00:48:38.420
with these ancient people.

00:48:38.420 --> 00:48:41.520
It's useful to us in some cases.

00:48:41.520 --> 00:48:43.730
And of course, I am sorry
I put up this table.

00:48:43.730 --> 00:48:47.280
But they did have
a graph for this.

00:48:47.280 --> 00:48:49.530
And of course, we've
been changing recently.

00:48:49.530 --> 00:48:51.360
And this is a great
chart that shows it.

00:48:51.360 --> 00:48:54.920
These are three genes that
are involved in pigmentation

00:48:54.920 --> 00:48:56.570
in human populations.

00:48:56.570 --> 00:48:59.040
And the one that I want
to draw your attention to

00:48:59.040 --> 00:49:01.080
is all the way over
here on the right side.

00:49:01.080 --> 00:49:04.980
This is the frequency of
the light pigmented version

00:49:04.980 --> 00:49:07.760
of these genes today
in the Ukraine.

00:49:07.760 --> 00:49:11.810
So this one HERC2, which
is eye color related,

00:49:11.810 --> 00:49:14.660
has frequency today of 65%.

00:49:14.660 --> 00:49:20.100
This one SLC45A2, which is
pigmentation related, is 92%.

00:49:20.100 --> 00:49:23.190
These are the frequencies
in Ukrainian archaeological

00:49:23.190 --> 00:49:25.700
samples from around
5,000 years ago.

00:49:25.700 --> 00:49:28.250
You can see that these
genes that make people

00:49:28.250 --> 00:49:30.672
light pigmented today are new.

00:49:30.672 --> 00:49:32.130
They haven't been
around that long,

00:49:32.130 --> 00:49:34.020
and they've been
growing in frequency

00:49:34.020 --> 00:49:35.860
during archaeological time.

00:49:35.860 --> 00:49:37.940
In other words, when
we look at the past,

00:49:37.940 --> 00:49:41.530
the recent past, the
past of a few generations

00:49:41.530 --> 00:49:44.700
ago, we're looking at
people that in many cases

00:49:44.700 --> 00:49:48.336
are different from the people
that are their descendants.

00:49:48.336 --> 00:49:50.460
And of course, there have
been population movements

00:49:50.460 --> 00:49:52.420
that also contribute
to those differences.

00:49:52.420 --> 00:49:54.439
But when we look over
time, some things

00:49:54.439 --> 00:49:55.480
are becoming more common.

00:49:55.480 --> 00:49:58.230
Because they're useful,
things like milk drinking,

00:49:58.230 --> 00:50:01.870
lactase persistence, things like
genes related to pigmentation.

00:50:01.870 --> 00:50:03.800
We've discovered
through ancient DNA

00:50:03.800 --> 00:50:07.120
the beginnings states of
some populations in these.

00:50:07.120 --> 00:50:11.470
And you can see how the
genes grow over time.

00:50:11.470 --> 00:50:12.980
Humans are changing.

00:50:12.980 --> 00:50:14.900
And it's a really
exciting thing to think

00:50:14.900 --> 00:50:17.420
that we can see that
happen now through looking

00:50:17.420 --> 00:50:19.600
at the ancient genes.

00:50:19.600 --> 00:50:21.950
Finally, ancient DNA
is changing the way

00:50:21.950 --> 00:50:24.660
that we actually conduct
archaeological excavations.

00:50:24.660 --> 00:50:25.660
And this is a great one.

00:50:25.660 --> 00:50:27.201
This is from a site
called El Sidron.

00:50:27.201 --> 00:50:29.010
And this is my
friend Antonio Rosas

00:50:29.010 --> 00:50:32.170
at the bottom, who's one of the
main anthropologists working

00:50:32.170 --> 00:50:32.870
at the site.

00:50:32.870 --> 00:50:35.920
And you can see the guy in
the bunny suit who is getting

00:50:35.920 --> 00:50:37.420
ready to go into this cave.

00:50:37.420 --> 00:50:39.420
This cave is a really
constrained place.

00:50:39.420 --> 00:50:42.440
And you've got to work in this
little place wearing this bunny

00:50:42.440 --> 00:50:43.060
suit.

00:50:43.060 --> 00:50:45.760
And he's got his samples
that he's carrying out.

00:50:45.760 --> 00:50:47.700
We're actually
really careful now

00:50:47.700 --> 00:50:49.820
about how we treat
ancient remains

00:50:49.820 --> 00:50:52.890
knowing that some of the most
valuable evidence that can come

00:50:52.890 --> 00:50:55.580
from them is DNA that, as
I'm sure Beth will tell you,

00:50:55.580 --> 00:50:57.780
is highly fragmented,
hard to get,

00:50:57.780 --> 00:51:01.820
and demands that we tried
to eliminate, to the extent

00:51:01.820 --> 00:51:05.510
that we can,
contamination sources.

00:51:05.510 --> 00:51:08.190
I've been recently involved
in the Rising Star Project.

00:51:08.190 --> 00:51:10.910
And last month, we
were fortunately

00:51:10.910 --> 00:51:14.710
able to announce the fossil
remains that we've discovered,

00:51:14.710 --> 00:51:19.320
which now at more
than 1,500 specimens

00:51:19.320 --> 00:51:23.490
are the most abundant fossil
hominin site ever discovered

00:51:23.490 --> 00:51:24.990
in Africa.

00:51:24.990 --> 00:51:28.610
We named on this basis a
new species, Homo naledi.

00:51:28.610 --> 00:51:30.500
There was some news about this.

00:51:30.500 --> 00:51:33.260
And so it's a really
exciting thing.

00:51:33.260 --> 00:51:36.770
We're working in a very
constrained cave, a cave where

00:51:36.770 --> 00:51:40.500
our team has to access the
chamber with the fossils

00:51:40.500 --> 00:51:43.890
through a very narrow 18
centimeter wide crack that

00:51:43.890 --> 00:51:46.280
is a 12 meter free climb
down to the bottom,

00:51:46.280 --> 00:51:48.960
that they have to wedge
themselves down through.

00:51:48.960 --> 00:51:52.400
To do this kind of work, we
recruited through Facebook

00:51:52.400 --> 00:51:57.710
a number of, where else
would you find them,

00:51:57.710 --> 00:51:59.420
extremely skilled
archaeologists who

00:51:59.420 --> 00:52:02.500
also have this kind of climbing
and caving ability and also

00:52:02.500 --> 00:52:08.464
have the dimensions to fit
through this very narrow chasm.

00:52:08.464 --> 00:52:10.130
And I'll tell you
that there's all kinds

00:52:10.130 --> 00:52:13.340
of exciting things about this
and the way that we work.

00:52:13.340 --> 00:52:17.120
But we're working in this fossil
chamber that, at the moment,

00:52:17.120 --> 00:52:19.540
is a bed of fossil hominin bone.

00:52:19.540 --> 00:52:21.539
And our team is on
bare foot protocol

00:52:21.539 --> 00:52:23.705
to make sure that they're
not stepping on something.

00:52:23.705 --> 00:52:26.090
It gives them that
sensory ability.

00:52:26.090 --> 00:52:28.950
Now, when I told my
ancient DNA colleagues

00:52:28.950 --> 00:52:33.540
that I've got barefoot people
walking through the cave

00:52:33.540 --> 00:52:36.160
to make sure that we
don't damage things

00:52:36.160 --> 00:52:37.650
they started to scream.

00:52:37.650 --> 00:52:41.480
I mean, it was like, oh
my god, the contamination.

00:52:41.480 --> 00:52:43.240
In fact, we do
quite a lot to try

00:52:43.240 --> 00:52:45.240
to avoid contamination
and collect

00:52:45.240 --> 00:52:47.580
samples that are
collected in relatively

00:52:47.580 --> 00:52:48.955
sterile circumstances.

00:52:48.955 --> 00:52:50.580
And of course,
technology has developed

00:52:50.580 --> 00:52:53.720
to the point where we can
differentiate in a lot of cases

00:52:53.720 --> 00:52:56.630
the kind of modern
contaminants from ancient DNA,

00:52:56.630 --> 00:52:58.830
actual endogenous ancient DNA.

00:52:58.830 --> 00:53:03.730
So we're pretty-- even
our excavation conducted

00:53:03.730 --> 00:53:06.340
under relatively
extreme circumstances

00:53:06.340 --> 00:53:09.270
is one in which we're
changing practices

00:53:09.270 --> 00:53:13.140
to make it possible to get
evidence from this ancient DNA

00:53:13.140 --> 00:53:14.040
source.

00:53:14.040 --> 00:53:16.730
You start seeing that take hold
across a field, where people

00:53:16.730 --> 00:53:18.370
recognize the importance of it.

00:53:18.370 --> 00:53:21.890
They recognize universally
what you're learning from it.

00:53:21.890 --> 00:53:25.950
And they recognize that this
is contributing new information

00:53:25.950 --> 00:53:28.810
that they could not have
gotten by any other means.

00:53:28.810 --> 00:53:31.670
And what it tells
you is that we now

00:53:31.670 --> 00:53:34.690
have a field that's been
transformed by the application

00:53:34.690 --> 00:53:36.420
of DNA technology.

00:53:36.420 --> 00:53:39.320
And it is hard to
imagine where this is

00:53:39.320 --> 00:53:41.040
going to take us in the future.

00:53:41.040 --> 00:53:43.860
But if you told me 10 years
ago that it would take us

00:53:43.860 --> 00:53:48.030
to the point where some of
these real bold elephants

00:53:48.030 --> 00:53:52.090
of anthropology were all
sitting at a table agreeing

00:53:52.090 --> 00:53:54.180
with each other about
the basic facts,

00:53:54.180 --> 00:53:56.780
I would say that you were
talking about science fiction.

00:53:56.780 --> 00:54:01.290
So ancient DNA has done
more than contribute

00:54:01.290 --> 00:54:03.300
to our knowledge
of human evolution.

00:54:03.300 --> 00:54:06.040
It's actually advanced
the process of science

00:54:06.040 --> 00:54:09.487
by making us able to look
at facts where previously we

00:54:09.487 --> 00:54:11.570
were working only with
theoretical preconceptions.

00:54:24.550 --> 00:54:25.145
-Beth Shapiro.

00:54:25.145 --> 00:54:27.300
-Very impressive timing.

00:54:27.300 --> 00:54:29.345
-Yeah, that was amazing.

00:54:29.345 --> 00:54:30.720
-Make sure this
is going to work,

00:54:30.720 --> 00:54:35.710
because I am too short
to stand behind a podium.

00:54:35.710 --> 00:54:36.900
I've come to accept that.

00:54:36.900 --> 00:54:38.570
It's life, right?

00:54:38.570 --> 00:54:42.600
All right, so this is the past,
present, and future of stuff.

00:54:42.600 --> 00:54:46.300
So I thought I would start by
just talking about the past,

00:54:46.300 --> 00:54:48.830
present, and future of
this field that I work in,

00:54:48.830 --> 00:54:52.160
that John so very nicely
gave a overwhelmingly

00:54:52.160 --> 00:54:54.740
supportive introduction to.

00:54:54.740 --> 00:54:55.400
Let's see.

00:54:55.400 --> 00:54:58.110
I will get to cloning
mammoths, but it

00:54:58.110 --> 00:55:00.510
will be toward the end
in the future section.

00:55:00.510 --> 00:55:02.930
Because we haven't done it yet.

00:55:02.930 --> 00:55:06.830
Although, George is
trying very hard.

00:55:06.830 --> 00:55:10.030
So ancient DNA, it all
started way, way back

00:55:10.030 --> 00:55:14.370
in the early 1980s when
a team of researchers

00:55:14.370 --> 00:55:16.760
in Allan Wilson's
lab at Berkeley,

00:55:16.760 --> 00:55:19.170
they called themselves
the extinct species study

00:55:19.170 --> 00:55:22.760
group, extracted in sequence
the tiny little fragment

00:55:22.760 --> 00:55:26.450
of mitochondrial
DNA from the skin,

00:55:26.450 --> 00:55:28.080
museum preserved
skin, of this guy.

00:55:28.080 --> 00:55:29.460
This is a quagga.

00:55:29.460 --> 00:55:31.780
They were able to sequence
a little bit of DNA

00:55:31.780 --> 00:55:32.610
from this thing.

00:55:32.610 --> 00:55:38.070
And wait for it, it turns out
it's related to the zebra.

00:55:38.070 --> 00:55:43.310
So it wasn't exactly a
overwhelming exciting

00:55:43.310 --> 00:55:47.090
scientific result.
But the idea that DNA

00:55:47.090 --> 00:55:50.150
was preserved in things
after they died was new.

00:55:50.150 --> 00:55:51.500
And this was pretty exciting.

00:55:51.500 --> 00:55:54.020
It actually set off a
whirlwind of research.

00:55:54.020 --> 00:55:56.530
People started to extract DNA
from pretty much everything

00:55:56.530 --> 00:55:57.510
they could find.

00:55:57.510 --> 00:56:01.150
There were mummies that
had DNA in them, probably.

00:56:01.150 --> 00:56:04.070
There were Miocene aged leaves.

00:56:04.070 --> 00:56:08.130
And before we knew it, there
were dinosaur DNA sequences

00:56:08.130 --> 00:56:13.220
being published from things
that were entombed in amber.

00:56:13.220 --> 00:56:18.990
The problem with all of this
stuff is that it wasn't real.

00:56:18.990 --> 00:56:22.090
We come to know now
despite being published

00:56:22.090 --> 00:56:24.140
in very high profile
journals there

00:56:24.140 --> 00:56:27.880
were quite a few papers that
should have been retracted.

00:56:27.880 --> 00:56:29.800
I don't think ever
have been retracted.

00:56:29.800 --> 00:56:34.170
But everything about dinosaur
DNA, for example, is not true.

00:56:34.170 --> 00:56:37.650
And the reason is because
DNA does not last forever.

00:56:37.650 --> 00:56:40.560
As soon as an
organism dies, the DNA

00:56:40.560 --> 00:56:42.140
that's within all
of its cells starts

00:56:42.140 --> 00:56:44.840
to break down into smaller
and smaller pieces.

00:56:44.840 --> 00:56:48.120
One of the things that causes
this DNA decay is the sun.

00:56:48.120 --> 00:56:50.420
So when we're alive
and we go outside,

00:56:50.420 --> 00:56:53.360
the sun, UV radiation from
the sun, hits our cells

00:56:53.360 --> 00:56:54.810
and actually breaks our DNA.

00:56:54.810 --> 00:56:57.160
But we have proofreading
enzymes that will

00:56:57.160 --> 00:56:58.920
go along and fix this damage.

00:56:58.920 --> 00:57:01.045
So we don't get cancer
every time we walk outside.

00:57:01.045 --> 00:57:04.120
Of course, these are all
energy requiring processes.

00:57:04.120 --> 00:57:06.050
And after you're
dead, you no longer

00:57:06.050 --> 00:57:10.750
have any energy, so UV
radiation, oxygen, water,

00:57:10.750 --> 00:57:13.610
enzymes that are in microbes
that are in the gut.

00:57:13.610 --> 00:57:17.034
If the gut bursts during
decay, all those microbes

00:57:17.034 --> 00:57:18.700
go circulating around
the body, starting

00:57:18.700 --> 00:57:21.790
breaking down that DNA into
smaller and smaller fragments.

00:57:21.790 --> 00:57:24.340
Also tons of
microorganisms in the soil.

00:57:24.340 --> 00:57:26.690
When these fossils are
sitting in the soil,

00:57:26.690 --> 00:57:29.060
these microorganisms
will colonize the bone,

00:57:29.060 --> 00:57:32.440
break down the DNA into
smaller and smaller pieces

00:57:32.440 --> 00:57:34.700
until eventually DNA,
which when you're

00:57:34.700 --> 00:57:38.170
alive you can think of as these
massive long strands of party

00:57:38.170 --> 00:57:40.830
streamers, look
more like confetti.

00:57:40.830 --> 00:57:43.800
But not really attractive
confetti like this,

00:57:43.800 --> 00:57:47.160
like the confetti from
the New Year's parade

00:57:47.160 --> 00:57:51.040
that emerges after the last
snow melts in the Kmart parking

00:57:51.040 --> 00:57:58.780
lot in April, or May if
you're in Edmonton, as many

00:57:58.780 --> 00:58:00.330
of my friends are.

00:58:00.330 --> 00:58:01.930
So yes, DNA degrades.

00:58:01.930 --> 00:58:05.070
And this process will
continue at a rate that

00:58:05.070 --> 00:58:08.110
depends on where the bone
is actually preserved

00:58:08.110 --> 00:58:10.210
in cold and dry places.

00:58:10.210 --> 00:58:12.940
Or cold places that are pretty
much temperature stable,

00:58:12.940 --> 00:58:15.100
the DNA lasts for
longer than it tends

00:58:15.100 --> 00:58:18.430
to last in warm and hot places.

00:58:18.430 --> 00:58:20.850
And today, the oldest
DNA that is known

00:58:20.850 --> 00:58:23.840
comes from this place where I
spent a lot of my time outside

00:58:23.840 --> 00:58:26.610
of Dawson City in
Canada's Yukon territory,

00:58:26.610 --> 00:58:29.910
where we find all of this
frozen sediment that's up there.

00:58:29.910 --> 00:58:34.650
And this oldest DNA is
about 700,000 years old.

00:58:34.650 --> 00:58:36.290
The reason that we
know it's that old

00:58:36.290 --> 00:58:41.000
is because in places like
this part of the world,

00:58:41.000 --> 00:58:42.880
we find these
volcanic ash layers.

00:58:42.880 --> 00:58:44.430
This white layer
here is actually

00:58:44.430 --> 00:58:46.880
from an eruption, a volcanic
eruption, that happened.

00:58:46.880 --> 00:58:50.260
This particular eruption
was about 80,000 years ago.

00:58:50.260 --> 00:58:52.570
And we know that by dating
it using different methods

00:58:52.570 --> 00:58:54.940
like thermal
luminescence dating.

00:58:54.940 --> 00:58:58.620
So we found this particular
bone, this 700,000 year old

00:58:58.620 --> 00:59:01.580
bone, in association
with an ash layer

00:59:01.580 --> 00:59:04.410
from an eruption that happened
somewhere around 680,000

00:59:04.410 --> 00:59:05.950
or 700,000 years.

00:59:05.950 --> 00:59:07.980
So we know how
old this bone was.

00:59:07.980 --> 00:59:11.800
And the DNA in this bone
was in terrible condition.

00:59:11.800 --> 00:59:12.970
There was very little of it.

00:59:12.970 --> 00:59:15.350
It was highly damaged
and highly fragmented.

00:59:15.350 --> 00:59:18.040
But we were still able to
generate enough data from it

00:59:18.040 --> 00:59:21.510
to sequence a complete
genome of a horse-- it's just

00:59:21.510 --> 00:59:24.730
a regular horse, the kind of
horse that still lives all

00:59:24.730 --> 00:59:27.510
over the place today,
Equus caballus--

00:59:27.510 --> 00:59:30.970
and start to learn about how
horses had evolved and changed

00:59:30.970 --> 00:59:32.220
through time.

00:59:32.220 --> 00:59:36.990
Now, 700,000 years is a lot
more recent than 65 million,

00:59:36.990 --> 00:59:39.540
or 85 million, or even
100 million years,

00:59:39.540 --> 00:59:42.410
which is how far back we have
to go to get dinosaur DNA.

00:59:42.410 --> 00:59:46.160
So for the time being
at least, Jurassic Park,

00:59:46.160 --> 00:59:49.270
at least as it was in
the mind of Michael

00:59:49.270 --> 00:59:51.530
Crichton and the many
writers, and producers,

00:59:51.530 --> 00:59:54.740
and directors who continued
this chain of fantastic

00:59:54.740 --> 00:59:59.580
blockbuster scientific
films, will remain

00:59:59.580 --> 01:00:01.820
a thing of science fiction.

01:00:01.820 --> 01:00:03.130
Sorry.

01:00:03.130 --> 01:00:05.000
But it is not all sadness.

01:00:05.000 --> 01:00:07.210
And there are some
incredibly well

01:00:07.210 --> 01:00:09.550
preserved remains
that are found.

01:00:09.550 --> 01:00:13.220
And that we now know have
quite a lot of DNA in them.

01:00:13.220 --> 01:00:15.910
That mummified mammoth that
you see up here in the corner,

01:00:15.910 --> 01:00:18.700
this is one that was found up
in the New Siberian islands

01:00:18.700 --> 01:00:20.380
a couple of summers
ago that was thought

01:00:20.380 --> 01:00:21.815
to be associated with blood.

01:00:21.815 --> 01:00:26.070
It was of a thick red,
black, viscous substance.

01:00:26.070 --> 01:00:28.350
That I'm told they've
discovered now was not blood,

01:00:28.350 --> 01:00:31.385
but instead what is officially
known as corpse juice.

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:37.500
Nonetheless, whether or not
it's blood or corpse juice,

01:00:37.500 --> 01:00:40.470
this is an incredibly
well preserved specimen.

01:00:40.470 --> 01:00:44.370
And we are able to extract and
sequence DNA from these things.

01:00:44.370 --> 01:00:48.510
So the field is called ancient
DNA for obvious reasons.

01:00:48.510 --> 01:00:50.790
And as I explain
it now, I'm just

01:00:50.790 --> 01:00:53.230
going to go through a
little bit, a short history,

01:00:53.230 --> 01:00:56.240
of different parts of it, my
involvement with ancient DNA

01:00:56.240 --> 01:00:58.470
really in the past
and the present

01:00:58.470 --> 01:01:00.350
and then get to the future.

01:01:00.350 --> 01:01:02.800
So the past of ancient
DNA is not very long.

01:01:02.800 --> 01:01:05.770
I started working in
ancient DNA in 1999.

01:01:05.770 --> 01:01:08.970
I was at Oxford University
in Allan Cooper's lab.

01:01:08.970 --> 01:01:10.860
We were one of the only
labs at the time that

01:01:10.860 --> 01:01:13.390
were really focusing
on extracting DNA

01:01:13.390 --> 01:01:14.360
from ancient remains.

01:01:14.360 --> 01:01:17.920
So it was pretty lucky that
we got in there at this time.

01:01:17.920 --> 01:01:20.800
I work mostly in a part of
the world called Beringia.

01:01:20.800 --> 01:01:22.000
This is Beringia here.

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:24.830
It spans Alaska,
the Yukon territory

01:01:24.830 --> 01:01:28.380
here, across the Bering
Strait and into-- that's

01:01:28.380 --> 01:01:30.720
the part of the world that
Sarah Palin, remember her,

01:01:30.720 --> 01:01:32.740
can see from her backyard.

01:01:32.740 --> 01:01:35.280
It's too bad she's not involved
in this particular race yet.

01:01:35.280 --> 01:01:36.784
Isn't it?

01:01:36.784 --> 01:01:39.608
No it's not.

01:01:39.608 --> 01:01:41.910
Do you see that
the sea level here?

01:01:41.910 --> 01:01:43.980
This light coloration
here indicates

01:01:43.980 --> 01:01:48.230
the sea level is a lot--
it's shallower there.

01:01:48.230 --> 01:01:50.520
And so during the
Ice Ages when a lot

01:01:50.520 --> 01:01:52.900
of the water on the
planet was taken up

01:01:52.900 --> 01:01:54.750
into forming massive
glaciers that it

01:01:54.750 --> 01:01:56.500
sat on top of the
continents, the sea

01:01:56.500 --> 01:01:57.700
was lower than it is today.

01:01:57.700 --> 01:01:59.370
And this was actually exposed.

01:01:59.370 --> 01:02:01.720
It was a very
important land bridge

01:02:01.720 --> 01:02:05.470
for the movement of plants and
animals between the continents.

01:02:05.470 --> 01:02:07.300
And we had lots of movements.

01:02:07.300 --> 01:02:11.310
Horses and camels moved from
North America into Asia.

01:02:11.310 --> 01:02:13.930
Bison, things like that,
humans moved from Asia

01:02:13.930 --> 01:02:15.360
into North America.

01:02:15.360 --> 01:02:18.180
It was a really very
important conduit.

01:02:18.180 --> 01:02:20.270
Today, Beringia looks
a lot like this.

01:02:20.270 --> 01:02:22.080
I'm in this-- I'm
taking this picture

01:02:22.080 --> 01:02:24.090
from this lovely helicopter.

01:02:24.090 --> 01:02:26.902
This is in the Taimyr Peninsula
in North Central Siberia.

01:02:26.902 --> 01:02:28.610
I'll show you the
helicopter in a minute.

01:02:28.610 --> 01:02:31.430
Because it's awesome.

01:02:31.430 --> 01:02:33.280
But in the past it
looked more like this,

01:02:33.280 --> 01:02:39.110
where there was a rich
diversity of plants and animals

01:02:39.110 --> 01:02:42.220
and included things like
mammoths, and mastodons,

01:02:42.220 --> 01:02:43.020
and woolly rhinos.

01:02:43.020 --> 01:02:44.603
They never made it
into North America,

01:02:44.603 --> 01:02:46.589
but they were pretty
abundant in Siberia.

01:02:46.589 --> 01:02:48.130
There were a couple
different species

01:02:48.130 --> 01:02:49.560
of horses in North America.

01:02:49.560 --> 01:02:51.770
There were crazy
things like giant bears

01:02:51.770 --> 01:02:54.920
that if stood up like this
would be 15 16 feet tall.

01:02:54.920 --> 01:02:57.750
We killed them.

01:02:57.750 --> 01:03:05.070
My favorite extinct animal, the
giant beaver, my size beaver.

01:03:05.070 --> 01:03:07.160
It's just the funniest
extinct animal.

01:03:07.160 --> 01:03:09.080
And so we go out
into these places.

01:03:09.080 --> 01:03:10.892
And we fly in these
stellar machineries.

01:03:10.892 --> 01:03:13.100
I told you I was going to
show you a picture of this.

01:03:13.100 --> 01:03:14.030
You'll notice that
there is actually

01:03:14.030 --> 01:03:16.530
some glass missing from
some of these windows, which

01:03:16.530 --> 01:03:17.440
is really good.

01:03:17.440 --> 01:03:20.220
Because these gas
tanks here that

01:03:20.220 --> 01:03:22.630
take up most of the inside,
that's where we sat.

01:03:22.630 --> 01:03:26.110
And after we took off
and celebrated the fact

01:03:26.110 --> 01:03:27.900
that we had gotten
off on the air,

01:03:27.900 --> 01:03:30.480
some of the people who were
sitting on these gas tanks

01:03:30.480 --> 01:03:36.130
decided that smoking was
a good way to celebrate.

01:03:36.130 --> 01:03:39.350
So at least we had the windows
to let the cigarette smoke out.

01:03:39.350 --> 01:03:42.310
We stay in five
star accommodation.

01:03:42.310 --> 01:03:43.050
That's my tent.

01:03:43.050 --> 01:03:46.770
I took this picture by backing
up and unfocusing my camera.

01:03:46.770 --> 01:03:49.300
So you could see the depth
of field of mosquitoes

01:03:49.300 --> 01:03:51.390
that we would deal with there.

01:03:51.390 --> 01:03:54.144
And we wander along
collecting bones.

01:03:54.144 --> 01:03:56.310
This is actually from near
Dawson City in the Yukon.

01:03:56.310 --> 01:03:58.240
There is active
gold mining going

01:03:58.240 --> 01:04:01.690
on there called placer mining
where these miners are washing

01:04:01.690 --> 01:04:04.690
away this frozen dirt to try
to get to the gold bearing

01:04:04.690 --> 01:04:05.750
gravels that are beneath.

01:04:05.750 --> 01:04:08.390
But as they're doing
that, thousands of bones,

01:04:08.390 --> 01:04:09.970
really well preserved
bones that look

01:04:09.970 --> 01:04:13.220
like they could be a couple
years old or even modern,

01:04:13.220 --> 01:04:13.950
come out of this.

01:04:13.950 --> 01:04:15.330
And we walk around
and collect them.

01:04:15.330 --> 01:04:16.913
In an average day
of working up there,

01:04:16.913 --> 01:04:21.380
we can collect something like 30
or 40 bags that look like this.

01:04:21.380 --> 01:04:25.760
Those are mostly horse, bison,
reindeer, and mammoth bones.

01:04:25.760 --> 01:04:27.510
But when we get lucky,
we get a carnivore.

01:04:27.510 --> 01:04:29.426
They had smaller
populations, but we can still

01:04:29.426 --> 01:04:32.210
find them, sometimes wolves
and bears, giant bears.

01:04:32.210 --> 01:04:34.050
We take a chunk out
of each of these bones

01:04:34.050 --> 01:04:36.010
and take them back to the lab.

01:04:36.010 --> 01:04:37.330
And we can do this over time.

01:04:37.330 --> 01:04:40.150
So we know how old all of
these different bones are.

01:04:40.150 --> 01:04:42.300
And we measure the amount
of genetic diversity

01:04:42.300 --> 01:04:44.530
that's in these
populations over time

01:04:44.530 --> 01:04:47.750
by extracting DNA and
sequencing a bit of that.

01:04:47.750 --> 01:04:50.640
And then we can use those
measures of genetic diversity

01:04:50.640 --> 01:04:53.380
and a statistical approach
called coalescent theory

01:04:53.380 --> 01:04:56.700
to translate diversity
into population size.

01:04:56.700 --> 01:04:59.680
And so we could come up with
these plots of how populations

01:04:59.680 --> 01:05:01.295
changed in size,
a big population

01:05:01.295 --> 01:05:03.820
sometime in the past
going to a smaller

01:05:03.820 --> 01:05:05.940
population in the present day.

01:05:05.940 --> 01:05:08.080
And we've generated
population level data

01:05:08.080 --> 01:05:11.440
sets, hundreds of individuals,
for about a dozen species

01:05:11.440 --> 01:05:11.940
so far.

01:05:11.940 --> 01:05:13.840
And here's just four
of them to give you

01:05:13.840 --> 01:05:16.630
a taste of what we can learn.

01:05:16.630 --> 01:05:19.560
The top graphs with
the colored background

01:05:19.560 --> 01:05:21.590
show a reconstruction
of how much

01:05:21.590 --> 01:05:24.580
habitat was available to
these animals over time.

01:05:24.580 --> 01:05:28.450
And this time scale goes
through the last 50,000 years.

01:05:28.450 --> 01:05:30.940
The tick marks here are
the fossils, the dates,

01:05:30.940 --> 01:05:33.510
that we use to make
these reconstructions.

01:05:33.510 --> 01:05:36.100
So the top line is the amount
of habitat that they had.

01:05:36.100 --> 01:05:38.610
And then this lower line with
these confidence intervals

01:05:38.610 --> 01:05:42.060
around it are how big
their populations are.

01:05:42.060 --> 01:05:44.650
So you can see from
this that as the amount

01:05:44.650 --> 01:05:47.830
of habitat available to each
of these species increases,

01:05:47.830 --> 01:05:49.570
so do their populations.

01:05:49.570 --> 01:05:51.900
And as the amount of
habitat decreases,

01:05:51.900 --> 01:05:53.520
so do their populations.

01:05:53.520 --> 01:05:56.970
So these animals are really
responding opportunistically,

01:05:56.970 --> 01:05:59.732
dynamically to the
amount of stuff

01:05:59.732 --> 01:06:00.940
that's there for them to eat.

01:06:00.940 --> 01:06:03.070
You notice that
none of the species

01:06:03.070 --> 01:06:04.781
that I've put up on
here-- and you'll

01:06:04.781 --> 01:06:06.280
notice with these
stuffed toys here,

01:06:06.280 --> 01:06:09.370
you can clearly see that this
is horses, bison, caribou,

01:06:09.370 --> 01:06:11.190
and musk ox.

01:06:11.190 --> 01:06:12.450
None of these are extinct.

01:06:12.450 --> 01:06:14.300
That's because when
species are extinct,

01:06:14.300 --> 01:06:18.160
it's very hard to reconstruct
their population dynamics.

01:06:18.160 --> 01:06:21.790
What we found in doing this work
is that as populations declined

01:06:21.790 --> 01:06:26.690
toward extinction, we didn't see
a decline in genetic diversity.

01:06:26.690 --> 01:06:29.620
What instead we saw
was that we were

01:06:29.620 --> 01:06:32.520
seeing an increase in the
amount of genetic distance

01:06:32.520 --> 01:06:33.670
between individuals.

01:06:33.670 --> 01:06:36.170
So what it looks like is
happening as species approach

01:06:36.170 --> 01:06:39.850
extinction is the habitats are
becoming more and more patchy.

01:06:39.850 --> 01:06:43.890
And individuals are getting
stuck in these patchy habitats.

01:06:43.890 --> 01:06:45.860
And then all of
these patchy habitats

01:06:45.860 --> 01:06:47.340
are declining simultaneously.

01:06:47.340 --> 01:06:50.700
So this approach of looking
at one genetic locus or two

01:06:50.700 --> 01:06:53.600
genetic locus and
trying to find out

01:06:53.600 --> 01:06:55.960
when extinction is
happening in this way

01:06:55.960 --> 01:06:59.740
doesn't work in the case
of these types of animals.

01:06:59.740 --> 01:07:03.430
Fortunately, we have moved
on to the present day

01:07:03.430 --> 01:07:06.500
where we don't have to use
these one locus or two locus

01:07:06.500 --> 01:07:07.660
analyses anymore.

01:07:07.660 --> 01:07:10.350
Because instead, we
have this crazy type

01:07:10.350 --> 01:07:12.300
of new sequencing
technology that

01:07:12.300 --> 01:07:16.990
lets us see every little bit of
surviving DNA in these bones.

01:07:16.990 --> 01:07:18.710
We call this next
generation sequencing.

01:07:18.710 --> 01:07:20.390
This is one of
the fancy machines

01:07:20.390 --> 01:07:22.040
that you can buy for
around $1 million

01:07:22.040 --> 01:07:24.170
and go out and sequence
a whole bunch of DNA.

01:07:24.170 --> 01:07:27.810
And this has been absolutely
fantastic for ancient DNA.

01:07:27.810 --> 01:07:29.920
Will people working
with modern DNA

01:07:29.920 --> 01:07:31.950
complain a little bit
about these machines,

01:07:31.950 --> 01:07:34.950
because they can only sequence
short fragments of DNA

01:07:34.950 --> 01:07:35.640
at a time?

01:07:35.640 --> 01:07:38.150
We don't care at
all, because we only

01:07:38.150 --> 01:07:39.950
have short fragments of DNA.

01:07:39.950 --> 01:07:41.350
And for this
reason, Alumina like

01:07:41.350 --> 01:07:43.400
to parade me around when
they're doing their sales

01:07:43.400 --> 01:07:44.820
pitches as the person
who goes up and says

01:07:44.820 --> 01:07:45.505
this is a great machine.

01:07:45.505 --> 01:07:46.963
It does everything
I need it to do.

01:07:46.963 --> 01:07:49.582
Absolutely everything, nothing
wrong with it whatsoever.

01:07:49.582 --> 01:07:51.540
So the kind of things
that we can do-- and here

01:07:51.540 --> 01:07:52.350
is just a plot.

01:07:52.350 --> 01:07:54.850
This is a paper that
we published recently,

01:07:54.850 --> 01:07:56.100
a couple weeks ago.

01:07:56.100 --> 01:07:58.360
This is a plot from
some bones that we

01:07:58.360 --> 01:07:59.470
collected in the Arctic.

01:07:59.470 --> 01:08:01.630
They're about 120,000 years old.

01:08:01.630 --> 01:08:05.230
And in the early 2000s, we
tried to extract DNA from them

01:08:05.230 --> 01:08:07.500
and amplify them up using
the traditional way.

01:08:07.500 --> 01:08:09.350
And we found absolutely nothing.

01:08:09.350 --> 01:08:12.220
We couldn't get any DNA out
of these bones whatsoever.

01:08:12.220 --> 01:08:13.890
And they're cool
bones, because they

01:08:13.890 --> 01:08:15.930
belong to a really
interesting species

01:08:15.930 --> 01:08:18.260
that I'll show you a
picture of in a minute.

01:08:18.260 --> 01:08:20.870
So we decided we would go
back to these bones now using

01:08:20.870 --> 01:08:23.420
this new next generation
sequencing technology

01:08:23.420 --> 01:08:25.779
and see if there
is DNA in there,

01:08:25.779 --> 01:08:28.140
just two short
fragments of DNA to be

01:08:28.140 --> 01:08:30.970
able to amplify using the
traditional technologies.

01:08:30.970 --> 01:08:31.760
And it's true.

01:08:31.760 --> 01:08:33.974
This is the fragment
length distribution

01:08:33.974 --> 01:08:34.890
for these three bones.

01:08:34.890 --> 01:08:36.890
You see that the mean
fragment length of them

01:08:36.890 --> 01:08:39.090
is around 30 base pairs long.

01:08:39.090 --> 01:08:40.540
That's not just confetti.

01:08:40.540 --> 01:08:43.060
That's like the punch holes
from the pieces of paper

01:08:43.060 --> 01:08:45.140
that you would get to
throw up in the air.

01:08:45.140 --> 01:08:50.640
Normally we get millions of
bases at a time, 35, again,

01:08:50.640 --> 01:08:51.990
and somewhere around 30.

01:08:51.990 --> 01:08:53.840
These are terribly preserved.

01:08:53.840 --> 01:08:56.100
The bottom plots also
show that the ends

01:08:56.100 --> 01:08:59.300
of each of these molecules
have typical types of damage

01:08:59.300 --> 01:09:00.830
that you see in ancient DNA.

01:09:00.830 --> 01:09:03.430
And this is a really cool
thing that this next generation

01:09:03.430 --> 01:09:05.479
sequencing technology
lets us see too.

01:09:05.479 --> 01:09:07.020
And gets back to
what John was saying

01:09:07.020 --> 01:09:10.479
about how we can tell the
difference between modern DNA

01:09:10.479 --> 01:09:14.040
contaminating DNA and
the real ancient stuff.

01:09:14.040 --> 01:09:16.450
Modern DNA doesn't
have this damage.

01:09:16.450 --> 01:09:17.770
But ancient DNA does.

01:09:17.770 --> 01:09:19.580
So if we have a
bone, a human bone,

01:09:19.580 --> 01:09:22.670
that we know has human DNA in
it, the first thing we can do

01:09:22.670 --> 01:09:24.950
is only look at
the molecules that

01:09:24.950 --> 01:09:26.859
have this signature of damage.

01:09:26.859 --> 01:09:29.950
And that will exclude, for the
most part, the contamination

01:09:29.950 --> 01:09:30.670
that's in there.

01:09:30.670 --> 01:09:33.060
So this particular
individual, this species

01:09:33.060 --> 01:09:35.920
that we were interested in,
is the North American camel,

01:09:35.920 --> 01:09:37.550
Camelops hesternus.

01:09:37.550 --> 01:09:40.060
And it was a long
paleontological mystery,

01:09:40.060 --> 01:09:43.779
which kind of camel this thing
was most closely related to.

01:09:43.779 --> 01:09:46.680
New world camels, which
are lamas, and alpacas,

01:09:46.680 --> 01:09:49.109
and vicunas, things like
that, or old world camels,

01:09:49.109 --> 01:09:51.609
the dromedary and
Bactrian camels.

01:09:51.609 --> 01:09:53.250
Most people thought
it was new world.

01:09:53.250 --> 01:09:55.780
Turns out we have this
paleontological information

01:09:55.780 --> 01:09:56.900
from aging DNA.

01:09:56.900 --> 01:09:58.800
That in fact, they are
more closely related

01:09:58.800 --> 01:10:01.400
to old world camels
than new world camels.

01:10:01.400 --> 01:10:03.230
So it's not as
exciting as humans

01:10:03.230 --> 01:10:05.680
have-- there's a new human.

01:10:05.680 --> 01:10:07.800
But camels are interesting.

01:10:07.800 --> 01:10:10.700
Other things we can do
with ancient DNA-- I'm just

01:10:10.700 --> 01:10:13.500
going to do one more
thing to try to give you

01:10:13.500 --> 01:10:17.050
just a taste of what
we can do after we have

01:10:17.050 --> 01:10:21.440
these ancient genome--
is study the consequences

01:10:21.440 --> 01:10:22.980
of the evolutionary
consequences,

01:10:22.980 --> 01:10:25.070
genomic consequences,
of different processes.

01:10:25.070 --> 01:10:27.050
And one of these
is domestication.

01:10:27.050 --> 01:10:28.760
We had a paper
last year where we

01:10:28.760 --> 01:10:31.180
looked at the process
of horse domestication.

01:10:31.180 --> 01:10:35.430
So ancient DNA on these orange
things are ancient horses.

01:10:35.430 --> 01:10:37.500
The blue ones are modern horses.

01:10:37.500 --> 01:10:40.710
These are the Przewalskis,
which is a wild modern horse.

01:10:40.710 --> 01:10:42.950
You see that according
to mitochondrial DNA

01:10:42.950 --> 01:10:47.420
there is a ton of
diversity in horses.

01:10:47.420 --> 01:10:49.480
A lot of horse females
were presumably

01:10:49.480 --> 01:10:52.700
used in the domestication
process, but very few males.

01:10:52.700 --> 01:10:55.290
We have nuclear genomes now
from a couple of different horse

01:10:55.290 --> 01:10:56.170
genomes.

01:10:56.170 --> 01:10:58.120
And because there seems
to be a lot of-- there

01:10:58.120 --> 01:11:00.490
seems to be a mixture
between these wild horses

01:11:00.490 --> 01:11:01.370
and modern horses.

01:11:01.370 --> 01:11:04.850
We can't learn about the process
of domestication looking only

01:11:04.850 --> 01:11:06.020
at modern DNA.

01:11:06.020 --> 01:11:08.570
So we sequenced complete
genomes from a couple of horses

01:11:08.570 --> 01:11:10.940
that we know were not
domestic, because they lived

01:11:10.940 --> 01:11:12.800
before domestication happened.

01:11:12.800 --> 01:11:15.300
And were able to then
scan through their genomes

01:11:15.300 --> 01:11:17.710
using a variety of
approaches and identify

01:11:17.710 --> 01:11:20.370
parts of the genome
that look like they

01:11:20.370 --> 01:11:22.910
have been under selection
since domestication.

01:11:22.910 --> 01:11:25.580
These are the genes
that were the product

01:11:25.580 --> 01:11:27.500
of the domestication process.

01:11:27.500 --> 01:11:29.400
And we found a lot
of different things

01:11:29.400 --> 01:11:30.940
that we expected to find.

01:11:30.940 --> 01:11:32.960
We found genes that
have been associated

01:11:32.960 --> 01:11:36.150
with different behavior,
being nicer, being calmer,

01:11:36.150 --> 01:11:37.840
being tamer.

01:11:37.840 --> 01:11:39.305
Genes associated
with pigmentation,

01:11:39.305 --> 01:11:41.180
we knew that these genes
were under selection

01:11:41.180 --> 01:11:42.300
and domestication.

01:11:42.300 --> 01:11:45.490
And genes associated
with their agility,

01:11:45.490 --> 01:11:47.069
ataxia genes, et cetera.

01:11:47.069 --> 01:11:48.610
We also found a
whole bunch of things

01:11:48.610 --> 01:11:49.943
that we don't know what they do.

01:11:49.943 --> 01:11:52.190
So the next step
in this is to try

01:11:52.190 --> 01:11:54.150
to use different
types of experiments

01:11:54.150 --> 01:11:56.700
and make these genes
express in tissue culture

01:11:56.700 --> 01:11:58.120
and figure out what's going on.

01:11:58.120 --> 01:12:01.060
So ancient DNA can
show us where to look

01:12:01.060 --> 01:12:05.470
to better understand different
evolutionary processes.

01:12:05.470 --> 01:12:06.930
And now on to the future.

01:12:06.930 --> 01:12:10.570
So what does the future of
ancient DNA have for us?

01:12:10.570 --> 01:12:13.590
So we study a lot of
different things in my lab.

01:12:13.590 --> 01:12:16.510
We study all of these
large mammals that used

01:12:16.510 --> 01:12:17.950
to live during the Ice Age.

01:12:17.950 --> 01:12:19.390
We study domestication.

01:12:19.390 --> 01:12:21.810
We study adaptation
to climate change.

01:12:21.810 --> 01:12:25.530
We try to better understand
how populations and species

01:12:25.530 --> 01:12:28.870
responded to changes to their
habitat that were associated

01:12:28.870 --> 01:12:30.040
with the last Ice Age.

01:12:30.040 --> 01:12:34.250
Because we want to be able to
make more informed decisions

01:12:34.250 --> 01:12:36.120
about how to use what
limited resources

01:12:36.120 --> 01:12:38.160
we have today to
preserve species

01:12:38.160 --> 01:12:40.580
in the face of predicted
climate change.

01:12:40.580 --> 01:12:42.610
And often when we
publish these papers,

01:12:42.610 --> 01:12:44.210
because they're
about big mammals

01:12:44.210 --> 01:12:48.130
that people think are fun, we
get some popular press coverage

01:12:48.130 --> 01:12:48.880
for these things.

01:12:48.880 --> 01:12:49.546
And people call.

01:12:49.546 --> 01:12:51.500
And I'm always really
excited to talk

01:12:51.500 --> 01:12:54.830
to people about the kind of
cool and interesting science

01:12:54.830 --> 01:12:56.140
that we're doing.

01:12:56.140 --> 01:12:59.896
But they really only ever want
me to answer one question.

01:13:03.880 --> 01:13:09.560
And so to answer this question
I wrote this book, which

01:13:09.560 --> 01:13:14.029
basically says no, not yet.

01:13:14.029 --> 01:13:15.570
And I'm not going
to go through a lot

01:13:15.570 --> 01:13:19.220
of the details in this book
anyway in this talk right now.

01:13:19.220 --> 01:13:22.271
But in the book I do go through
the technical challenges

01:13:22.271 --> 01:13:24.270
associated with bringing
a mammoth back to life,

01:13:24.270 --> 01:13:27.000
as well as talk about some
of the ethical and ecological

01:13:27.000 --> 01:13:28.852
questions that are
going to come about.

01:13:28.852 --> 01:13:30.310
Of course, it would
be remiss of me

01:13:30.310 --> 01:13:32.449
since I'm standing
here not to highlight

01:13:32.449 --> 01:13:34.740
some of the really cool stuff
that is being done there,

01:13:34.740 --> 01:13:37.230
in particular by this
motley crew of-- are

01:13:37.230 --> 01:13:38.600
you wearing the same thing?

01:13:48.660 --> 01:13:50.220
These guys have
been doing-- and I'm

01:13:50.220 --> 01:13:52.060
sure we're going to get a chance
to talk about it when we have

01:13:52.060 --> 01:13:53.320
the discussion section here.

01:13:53.320 --> 01:13:56.370
But they have been doing
some fantastic work, at least

01:13:56.370 --> 01:13:59.020
to set us off on the
right foot to figure out

01:13:59.020 --> 01:14:02.110
what we would need to do
if we were going to bring

01:14:02.110 --> 01:14:03.824
a mammoth back to life.

01:14:03.824 --> 01:14:05.490
I think one of the
most important things

01:14:05.490 --> 01:14:08.360
to remember when we think about
bringing a mammoth back to life

01:14:08.360 --> 01:14:11.310
is that the Asian elephant
and the woolly mammoth, Asian

01:14:11.310 --> 01:14:13.564
elephants are known to
be the closest living

01:14:13.564 --> 01:14:15.980
relative of woolly mammoths,
are separated from each other

01:14:15.980 --> 01:14:19.530
by somewhere around 5 to 7
million years of evolution.

01:14:19.530 --> 01:14:21.970
And this is not very much.

01:14:21.970 --> 01:14:23.940
This is not very much change.

01:14:23.940 --> 01:14:26.170
So when you look at
an Asian elephant,

01:14:26.170 --> 01:14:29.390
you're actually looking at
something that is about 99%

01:14:29.390 --> 01:14:31.660
mammoth already anyway.

01:14:31.660 --> 01:14:33.630
So if you're going to
take an Asian elephant

01:14:33.630 --> 01:14:36.130
and turn it into a
mammoth, all you have to do

01:14:36.130 --> 01:14:40.320
is identify that last
1% and change that.

01:14:40.320 --> 01:14:43.010
1% of 4 billion or so
base pairs is still

01:14:43.010 --> 01:14:44.470
like a million and
a half changes.

01:14:44.470 --> 01:14:46.470
But he's a pretty smart guy.

01:14:46.470 --> 01:14:48.465
I'm sure we can figure
out how to do this.

01:14:48.465 --> 01:14:49.840
We're also having--
we're getting

01:14:49.840 --> 01:14:53.865
a much better understanding
of the types of differences,

01:14:53.865 --> 01:14:56.910
the types of genetic changes
we might need to make.

01:14:56.910 --> 01:15:00.400
One of the first discoveries
that differentiated mammoths

01:15:00.400 --> 01:15:04.090
and Asian elephants came
from Kevin Campbell's group

01:15:04.090 --> 01:15:05.130
in Manitoba.

01:15:05.130 --> 01:15:09.270
They were looking at
hemoglobin, a protein that is

01:15:09.270 --> 01:15:11.310
a part of the red blood cells.

01:15:11.310 --> 01:15:13.930
And they discovered by
sequencing hemoglobin

01:15:13.930 --> 01:15:17.630
from elephants and mammoths
that part of this gene--

01:15:17.630 --> 01:15:18.920
it's made up of several genes.

01:15:18.920 --> 01:15:20.640
But part of it
was different only

01:15:20.640 --> 01:15:23.380
by three different changes.

01:15:23.380 --> 01:15:26.211
Three nucleotide changes led
to three different amino acid

01:15:26.211 --> 01:15:26.710
changes.

01:15:26.710 --> 01:15:30.710
So the protein sequences in
hemoglobin were really similar.

01:15:30.710 --> 01:15:33.080
They wanted to
know though, what's

01:15:33.080 --> 01:15:34.300
up with these three changes.

01:15:34.300 --> 01:15:36.050
Why are these three
changes actually important?

01:15:36.050 --> 01:15:37.510
And so they
expressed these genes

01:15:37.510 --> 01:15:40.720
and measured their ability to
carry oxygen around the body,

01:15:40.720 --> 01:15:43.570
this is what hemoglobin
do, in different types

01:15:43.570 --> 01:15:44.240
of environments.

01:15:44.240 --> 01:15:47.650
And they found that the woolly
mammoth version of hemoglobin

01:15:47.650 --> 01:15:50.400
was much more efficient
than the Asian elephant

01:15:50.400 --> 01:15:54.720
version at carrying oxygen
around the body when it's cold.

01:15:54.720 --> 01:15:55.650
Pretty good.

01:15:55.650 --> 01:15:58.900
So this is obviously one of the
adaptations that occurred along

01:15:58.900 --> 01:16:01.140
the lineage to woolly
mammoth since the divergence

01:16:01.140 --> 01:16:03.850
between woolly mammoth
and the Asian elephant.

01:16:03.850 --> 01:16:06.680
So George and his team are
looking through these genomes

01:16:06.680 --> 01:16:07.180
now.

01:16:07.180 --> 01:16:08.420
There are a whole
bunch of genomes

01:16:08.420 --> 01:16:10.600
that have been published
recently for woolly mammoths,

01:16:10.600 --> 01:16:12.016
as there are a lot
of genomes that

01:16:12.016 --> 01:16:14.030
are becoming available
for Asian elephants,

01:16:14.030 --> 01:16:16.414
and making lists of the
genes that are different,

01:16:16.414 --> 01:16:18.830
and trying to figure out whether
they're important or not.

01:16:18.830 --> 01:16:21.070
And then using CRISPR
technology, which we'll

01:16:21.070 --> 01:16:23.650
hear about later, to try
to swap these genes out,

01:16:23.650 --> 01:16:26.540
cut and paste your way
from an Asian elephant

01:16:26.540 --> 01:16:28.390
into a woolly mammoth.

01:16:28.390 --> 01:16:32.100
So why might we want to
do this, just a little end

01:16:32.100 --> 01:16:35.200
on why we might want to go
through all of these problems

01:16:35.200 --> 01:16:38.100
considering there are
major technical, ethical,

01:16:38.100 --> 01:16:41.310
and ecological hurdles that
we will encounter along

01:16:41.310 --> 01:16:43.200
the way to doing this?

01:16:43.200 --> 01:16:44.950
In the purpose-- for
the case of mammoths,

01:16:44.950 --> 01:16:47.470
there are really two
reasons that are discussed.

01:16:47.470 --> 01:16:50.110
And the first is ecological.

01:16:50.110 --> 01:16:52.942
There is a place in
Northeastern Siberia that's

01:16:52.942 --> 01:16:54.900
led by a guy in the
Russian Academy of Sciences

01:16:54.900 --> 01:16:56.270
called Sergey Zimov.

01:16:56.270 --> 01:16:59.120
And he calls this
Pleistocene Park.

01:16:59.120 --> 01:17:01.270
Pleistocene was much more
recent than the Jurassic,

01:17:01.270 --> 01:17:04.730
so well within the realm
of possibility here.

01:17:04.730 --> 01:17:07.830
Pleistocene Park is a
great and exciting place.

01:17:07.830 --> 01:17:10.540
And Sergey already has
introduced into Pleistocene

01:17:10.540 --> 01:17:12.950
Park a couple of
different big animals

01:17:12.950 --> 01:17:15.660
that are reminiscent of
the Pleistocene, the Ice

01:17:15.660 --> 01:17:18.480
Ages, where we had things
like mammoths and mastodons.

01:17:18.480 --> 01:17:21.880
He has bison from North America,
about five different species

01:17:21.880 --> 01:17:23.277
of deer.

01:17:23.277 --> 01:17:25.610
There are some horses that
he's introduced to this area.

01:17:25.610 --> 01:17:30.990
And he's shown that over the
course of just a few summers

01:17:30.990 --> 01:17:34.630
that just having these large
mammals on this landscape,

01:17:34.630 --> 01:17:36.700
just their presence
alone, has been

01:17:36.700 --> 01:17:42.540
enough to reestablish this rich
grassland that used to be part

01:17:42.540 --> 01:17:45.050
of this landscape in Siberia.

01:17:45.050 --> 01:17:47.970
Just having these animals
there churning over the soil,

01:17:47.970 --> 01:17:50.400
distributing nutrients,
distributing seeds

01:17:50.400 --> 01:17:52.270
makes the grass come back.

01:17:52.270 --> 01:17:55.170
In essence, they provide
their own habitat.

01:17:55.170 --> 01:17:57.550
And he's also seen
that other species that

01:17:57.550 --> 01:18:00.300
are in danger of extinction,
because their habitat is

01:18:00.300 --> 01:18:02.160
declining, like
the saiga antelope,

01:18:02.160 --> 01:18:03.990
have started visiting the park.

01:18:03.990 --> 01:18:05.240
This is a picture of his park.

01:18:05.240 --> 01:18:07.580
Over here on this side,
he has the animals.

01:18:07.580 --> 01:18:10.000
And he has them
fenced out over here.

01:18:10.000 --> 01:18:12.590
You see that this is actually--
you can't see it very well,

01:18:12.590 --> 01:18:13.510
the colors here.

01:18:13.510 --> 01:18:17.110
But there is some green
little patches of green

01:18:17.110 --> 01:18:17.990
all around here.

01:18:17.990 --> 01:18:19.690
And they're actually
very different.

01:18:19.690 --> 01:18:22.110
It's much more speciose,
more biodiversity,

01:18:22.110 --> 01:18:23.620
than you get on
this particular side

01:18:23.620 --> 01:18:25.340
where you don't have animals.

01:18:25.340 --> 01:18:27.310
This is also early spring.

01:18:27.310 --> 01:18:30.270
And this means that there
has been enough grass

01:18:30.270 --> 01:18:33.170
that some of it is still
surviving this harsh Siberian

01:18:33.170 --> 01:18:33.900
winter.

01:18:33.900 --> 01:18:36.460
So these guys really
are ecosystem engineers

01:18:36.460 --> 01:18:40.070
and bringing these animals
back, this large herbivore.

01:18:40.070 --> 01:18:42.230
I mean, elephants play
important fundamental roles

01:18:42.230 --> 01:18:43.480
in their ecosystem in Africa.

01:18:43.480 --> 01:18:45.260
There's no reason
to assume mammoths

01:18:45.260 --> 01:18:47.010
didn't do the same in Siberia.

01:18:47.010 --> 01:18:49.460
So he argues,
Georgia argues, and I

01:18:49.460 --> 01:18:52.620
would argue that bringing
back these large herbivores

01:18:52.620 --> 01:18:55.130
will help to
reestablish interactions

01:18:55.130 --> 01:18:57.320
in this ecosystem
that have been missing

01:18:57.320 --> 01:18:59.250
since their disappearance.

01:18:59.250 --> 01:19:01.200
And the same argument
could be made

01:19:01.200 --> 01:19:02.650
for many other extinct species.

01:19:02.650 --> 01:19:04.610
Not to bring them back
just for the purpose

01:19:04.610 --> 01:19:07.860
of looking at an extinct
species and seeing it in a zoo,

01:19:07.860 --> 01:19:10.680
but to reestablish
interactions in ecosystems

01:19:10.680 --> 01:19:14.490
that have been missing since the
time of extinction that perhaps

01:19:14.490 --> 01:19:17.540
can be used to
reinvigorate that ecosystem

01:19:17.540 --> 01:19:22.320
and save living species, which
is actually the second reason.

01:19:22.320 --> 01:19:24.000
This research is
not only teaching us

01:19:24.000 --> 01:19:25.877
about what Asian
elephants might have done

01:19:25.877 --> 01:19:26.960
or might have looked like.

01:19:26.960 --> 01:19:29.470
But it's teaching
us about elephants.

01:19:29.470 --> 01:19:33.790
And Asian elephants are in
danger of going extinct.

01:19:33.790 --> 01:19:35.640
What if we could
use this technology

01:19:35.640 --> 01:19:38.980
to take some of these genes that
have been shaped by evolution

01:19:38.980 --> 01:19:43.400
in past to reinvigorate
the diversity, the genomes,

01:19:43.400 --> 01:19:46.120
the survivability of
species that are in danger

01:19:46.120 --> 01:19:47.400
of going extinct today.

01:19:47.400 --> 01:19:50.660
If we could take an elephant
and give it the capacity

01:19:50.660 --> 01:19:54.150
to live in colder climates,
we could expand the range

01:19:54.150 --> 01:19:55.950
that an elephant could live in.

01:19:55.950 --> 01:19:59.540
Saving elephants, rather than
bringing mammoths back to life.

01:19:59.540 --> 01:20:01.120
So I'm going to leave it there.

01:20:01.120 --> 01:20:02.550
But we can talk
about the ethics,

01:20:02.550 --> 01:20:06.610
and ecological challenges, and
technical challenges later.

01:20:06.610 --> 01:20:08.950
But for now, thank
you very much.

01:20:21.650 --> 01:20:26.270
-Wow, what an amazing
time to be a scientist.

01:20:26.270 --> 01:20:29.710
If you had told me 10 years
ago that ancient DNA labs would

01:20:29.710 --> 01:20:32.100
routinely be producing the
data they're producing today,

01:20:32.100 --> 01:20:34.250
I would have laughed
you out of the room.

01:20:34.250 --> 01:20:37.850
So it's really incredible to see
how the field has progressed.

01:20:37.850 --> 01:20:41.530
But let's step back.

01:20:41.530 --> 01:20:43.380
Let's think about
modern humans, which is

01:20:43.380 --> 01:20:44.830
what I'm going to talk about.

01:20:44.830 --> 01:20:48.340
And let's think about this
whole issue of human migration

01:20:48.340 --> 01:20:51.020
patterns, and in
particular, why humans

01:20:51.020 --> 01:20:53.840
are dispersed so widely
around the earth,

01:20:53.840 --> 01:20:56.280
and why we're so diverse.

01:20:56.280 --> 01:21:00.360
Put yourself back in time,
European age of exploration.

01:21:00.360 --> 01:21:02.090
You're cruising
around the Pacific

01:21:02.090 --> 01:21:04.580
with Captain Cook at the
end of the 18th century.

01:21:04.580 --> 01:21:08.020
And every time you crash ashore
on one of these remote islands,

01:21:08.020 --> 01:21:09.854
you find people there.

01:21:09.854 --> 01:21:12.020
And they're somewhat like
people you've seen before,

01:21:12.020 --> 01:21:13.000
but different in some ways.

01:21:13.000 --> 01:21:14.458
The language is
slightly different.

01:21:14.458 --> 01:21:16.520
They may look a
little bit different.

01:21:16.520 --> 01:21:18.660
Why are people so
widely dispersed,

01:21:18.660 --> 01:21:20.940
and how do we account for
the diversity that we see?

01:21:20.940 --> 01:21:23.980
We see a dizzying
amount of phenotypic

01:21:23.980 --> 01:21:27.130
diversity, facial
appearance and so on.

01:21:27.130 --> 01:21:29.240
That's really the
overarching problem

01:21:29.240 --> 01:21:32.750
in the field of human
population genetics.

01:21:32.750 --> 01:21:36.410
And like any big overarching
problem or theme,

01:21:36.410 --> 01:21:39.090
you can break it down into
sub themes or questions

01:21:39.090 --> 01:21:42.470
that we can start to chip away
at using the tools of science,

01:21:42.470 --> 01:21:44.610
gathering data, formulating
hypotheses, coming

01:21:44.610 --> 01:21:46.200
down on one side or the other.

01:21:46.200 --> 01:21:48.560
First question we can
ask is one of origins.

01:21:48.560 --> 01:21:50.980
Are we in fact all
related to each other?

01:21:50.980 --> 01:21:53.640
And if so, how closely?

01:21:53.640 --> 01:21:55.230
And the second is
one of journey.

01:21:55.230 --> 01:21:58.150
If we do spring from a
common source as a species,

01:21:58.150 --> 01:22:00.260
how do we come to occupy
every corner of the globe

01:22:00.260 --> 01:22:03.020
in the process of generating
these patterns of diversity

01:22:03.020 --> 01:22:05.500
that we see today?

01:22:05.500 --> 01:22:08.040
Well, the question of
origins, as with so many

01:22:08.040 --> 01:22:10.630
other big questions
in biology, seems

01:22:10.630 --> 01:22:13.490
have been answered over a
century ago by Charles Darwin.

01:22:13.490 --> 01:22:16.420
He wrote in his second most
famous book, The Descent

01:22:16.420 --> 01:22:18.322
of Man, "In each great
region of the world

01:22:18.322 --> 01:22:20.530
the living mammals are
closely related to the extinct

01:22:20.530 --> 01:22:21.880
species of the same region.

01:22:21.880 --> 01:22:24.200
It's therefore probable
that Africa was formerly

01:22:24.200 --> 01:22:26.300
inhabited by extinct
apes closely allied

01:22:26.300 --> 01:22:27.800
to the gorilla and chimpanzee.

01:22:27.800 --> 01:22:30.870
And as these two species are
now man's nearest allies,

01:22:30.870 --> 01:22:33.120
it's somewhat more probable
that our early progenitors

01:22:33.120 --> 01:22:36.350
lived on the African
continent than elsewhere."

01:22:36.350 --> 01:22:39.590
OK, so Darwin solved
the origins problem.

01:22:39.590 --> 01:22:41.320
Except he didn't really.

01:22:41.320 --> 01:22:44.426
He of course, is talking about
our shared ancestry with apes.

01:22:44.426 --> 01:22:45.800
And he was absolutely
right, even

01:22:45.800 --> 01:22:49.334
though he didn't have any data
to support that at the time.

01:22:49.334 --> 01:22:50.750
We now know from
the fossil record

01:22:50.750 --> 01:22:52.840
that apes do appear
first in Africa

01:22:52.840 --> 01:22:55.604
around 23 million years
ago, the great apes.

01:22:55.604 --> 01:22:57.020
At a time when
Africa was actually

01:22:57.020 --> 01:22:58.936
disconnected from the
rest of the world's land

01:22:58.936 --> 01:23:00.670
masses due to plate tectonics.

01:23:00.670 --> 01:23:02.990
It bumps into the
Arabian Peninsula

01:23:02.990 --> 01:23:05.930
between 16 and 18
million years ago.

01:23:05.930 --> 01:23:08.800
And at that point, we have the
first so-called African exodus.

01:23:08.800 --> 01:23:12.130
The apes that left at that time
and ended up in Southeast Asia

01:23:12.130 --> 01:23:15.089
ultimately evolved into the
gibbons and the orangutans.

01:23:15.089 --> 01:23:16.630
And the ones that
stayed on in Africa

01:23:16.630 --> 01:23:20.172
ultimately became gorillas,
and chimps, and yes, us.

01:23:20.172 --> 01:23:21.630
So yeah, Darwin's
absolutely right.

01:23:21.630 --> 01:23:25.470
If you go far enough back
in time 23 million years,

01:23:25.470 --> 01:23:27.740
you find that humans are an
African species in common

01:23:27.740 --> 01:23:29.210
with all other great apes.

01:23:29.210 --> 01:23:32.180
But that's not really
the question I'm asking.

01:23:32.180 --> 01:23:35.070
Rather I want to know about
us as a species, Homo sapiens,

01:23:35.070 --> 01:23:38.130
individuals that we would
recognize as being like us

01:23:38.130 --> 01:23:42.440
if they were sitting out
here in the seventh row.

01:23:42.440 --> 01:23:44.380
That question has been
approached historically

01:23:44.380 --> 01:23:46.160
through the study of
paleoanthropology,

01:23:46.160 --> 01:23:49.020
going out and digging up
bones and saying typically

01:23:49.020 --> 01:23:51.940
on the basis of morphology,
often skull shape,

01:23:51.940 --> 01:23:53.780
this looks a little
bit more like my cousin

01:23:53.780 --> 01:23:56.050
Frank than that does.

01:23:56.050 --> 01:23:57.150
This is the missing link.

01:23:57.150 --> 01:23:59.240
This is where we all came from.

01:23:59.240 --> 01:24:00.890
What I would like
to suggest though

01:24:00.890 --> 01:24:04.290
as a geneticist who values
large amounts of data

01:24:04.290 --> 01:24:06.310
is that while the field
of paleoanthropology

01:24:06.310 --> 01:24:08.810
gives us lots of
fascinating possibilities

01:24:08.810 --> 01:24:11.530
about human origins
and dispersal patterns,

01:24:11.530 --> 01:24:13.260
it doesn't give us
the probabilities

01:24:13.260 --> 01:24:15.380
about direct lines of
descent that we really

01:24:15.380 --> 01:24:18.700
want unless we're lucky enough
to get ancient DNA out of them.

01:24:18.700 --> 01:24:21.390
Possibilities about our
past and our origins,

01:24:21.390 --> 01:24:23.710
but not the probabilities
about direct connections

01:24:23.710 --> 01:24:25.830
to those individuals.

01:24:25.830 --> 01:24:26.830
This is a great example.

01:24:26.830 --> 01:24:29.038
What you're looking at here
are three extinct species

01:24:29.038 --> 01:24:30.090
of hominids.

01:24:30.090 --> 01:24:33.050
From left to right, Homo
habilis, Homo erectus,

01:24:33.050 --> 01:24:36.930
and paranthropus boisei,
robust australopithecine,

01:24:36.930 --> 01:24:40.414
all uncovered from the same
location in northern Kenya

01:24:40.414 --> 01:24:42.080
and all dating to
roughly the same time,

01:24:42.080 --> 01:24:43.880
about 2 million years ago.

01:24:43.880 --> 01:24:46.520
So which one of these guys am
I actually directly related to,

01:24:46.520 --> 01:24:48.270
descended from?

01:24:48.270 --> 01:24:49.230
I don't know.

01:24:49.230 --> 01:24:51.930
Possibilities about our past
and our origins, but now

01:24:51.930 --> 01:24:55.030
the probabilities
we really want.

01:24:55.030 --> 01:24:57.080
Well we as
geneticists of course,

01:24:57.080 --> 01:24:58.780
take a slightly
different approach.

01:24:58.780 --> 01:25:00.340
We turn the problem on its head.

01:25:00.340 --> 01:25:02.300
Instead of digging
things up out of the past

01:25:02.300 --> 01:25:04.883
and guessing at how they may or
may not connect to the present

01:25:04.883 --> 01:25:06.905
and to us, we start
in the present.

01:25:06.905 --> 01:25:08.290
And we work our
way back in time.

01:25:08.290 --> 01:25:10.250
Because we know it's
an absolute certainty

01:25:10.250 --> 01:25:13.030
that everybody alive
today had parents.

01:25:13.030 --> 01:25:14.840
And those parents had
parents and so on.

01:25:14.840 --> 01:25:16.800
So it should be possible
to build a family

01:25:16.800 --> 01:25:18.709
tree for everyone alive.

01:25:18.709 --> 01:25:20.500
And I'm sure that a
few people in this room

01:25:20.500 --> 01:25:22.830
have done that, built
a genealogical tree.

01:25:22.830 --> 01:25:24.340
It's the second
most popular hobby

01:25:24.340 --> 01:25:26.560
in the country after gardening.

01:25:26.560 --> 01:25:29.950
Told it's poised to overtake
gardening very soon.

01:25:29.950 --> 01:25:32.520
But no matter how far back
you can trace your family line

01:25:32.520 --> 01:25:34.960
and ultimately it all ends at
Charlemagne for some reason

01:25:34.960 --> 01:25:37.780
if you're from Europe.

01:25:37.780 --> 01:25:39.760
The point is that you
eventually run out

01:25:39.760 --> 01:25:41.730
of the written record
about your ancestors.

01:25:41.730 --> 01:25:44.020
And we simply enter this
dark and mysterious realm

01:25:44.020 --> 01:25:46.649
we call history, and
ultimately prehistory.

01:25:46.649 --> 01:25:48.440
But it turns out, of
course, that we're all

01:25:48.440 --> 01:25:51.640
carrying a written
historical document

01:25:51.640 --> 01:25:54.150
inside of ourselves,
inside of nearly every cell

01:25:54.150 --> 01:25:56.110
in our body in our DNA.

01:25:56.110 --> 01:25:59.280
And that allows us to see
back beyond that brick wall,

01:25:59.280 --> 01:26:02.734
as the genealogists call the
place where the records stop.

01:26:02.734 --> 01:26:04.650
Back to the very earliest
days of our species.

01:26:04.650 --> 01:26:06.608
And we've already had a
bit of a primer on DNA.

01:26:06.608 --> 01:26:09.190
But just to reiterate,
long linear molecule,

01:26:09.190 --> 01:26:11.930
the famous double helix
described by Watson and Crick

01:26:11.930 --> 01:26:15.790
in 1953 composed of four
subunits-- A, C, G, and T.

01:26:15.790 --> 01:26:18.370
And it's the sequence of
these A's, C's, G's, and T's

01:26:18.370 --> 01:26:20.460
that basically
provides a blueprint

01:26:20.460 --> 01:26:21.960
to make another
version of yourself.

01:26:21.960 --> 01:26:23.335
And in every
generation, you have

01:26:23.335 --> 01:26:27.640
to copy all of this information
to pass it on to your kids.

01:26:27.640 --> 01:26:29.080
And it's a lot of information.

01:26:29.080 --> 01:26:31.970
There are billions of
A's C's G's and T's

01:26:31.970 --> 01:26:33.640
in the human genome.

01:26:33.640 --> 01:26:37.040
And so it's like copying
a very long text.

01:26:37.040 --> 01:26:38.120
Imagine a long book.

01:26:38.120 --> 01:26:39.600
Say, War and Peace.

01:26:39.600 --> 01:26:42.230
But it's like copying
1,000 volumes of that.

01:26:42.230 --> 01:26:45.160
And you've got to do it in
eight hours, which is roughly

01:26:45.160 --> 01:26:48.462
what it takes with yourselves
to replicate your genome.

01:26:48.462 --> 01:26:50.170
And this is really
important information.

01:26:50.170 --> 01:26:51.336
So what are you going to do?

01:26:51.336 --> 01:26:53.490
Well, you're going to
get your cup of coffee,

01:26:53.490 --> 01:26:55.220
or whatever it is that
keeps you focused.

01:26:55.220 --> 01:26:56.870
And you're going to
check and double-check

01:26:56.870 --> 01:26:59.244
very carefully as you're
copying all of this information,

01:26:59.244 --> 01:27:00.790
because it's so important.

01:27:00.790 --> 01:27:04.300
But inevitably, what is going
to happen as you're copying?

01:27:04.300 --> 01:27:06.530
You're going to make a
typo, a spelling mistake.

01:27:06.530 --> 01:27:08.390
Those happen at the
DNA level as well

01:27:08.390 --> 01:27:12.690
during this copying process, at
a rate of around 100 mutations,

01:27:12.690 --> 01:27:15.340
as we call them, per
genome per generation,

01:27:15.340 --> 01:27:18.130
as the DNA is being
copied to be passed on.

01:27:18.130 --> 01:27:20.140
And as these mutations
get passed down

01:27:20.140 --> 01:27:23.330
to children, grandchildren,
great-grandchildren,

01:27:23.330 --> 01:27:26.010
they become what we
call markers of descent.

01:27:26.010 --> 01:27:28.050
So if you share one
of these changes, one

01:27:28.050 --> 01:27:30.970
of these markers in your
DNA, with another person,

01:27:30.970 --> 01:27:33.050
that means you share an
ancestor-- the person

01:27:33.050 --> 01:27:35.430
in the past who first had
that mutation in their DNA

01:27:35.430 --> 01:27:38.300
and passed it on
to the two of you.

01:27:38.300 --> 01:27:40.200
This is actual
DNA sequence data.

01:27:40.200 --> 01:27:42.050
Old-fashioned Sanger
sequencing, which

01:27:42.050 --> 01:27:45.200
is still the gold standard
for clinical diagnostics.

01:27:45.200 --> 01:27:47.300
Five individuals-- one,
two, three, four, five--

01:27:47.300 --> 01:27:49.780
have had the same region
of their genome sequenced.

01:27:49.780 --> 01:27:50.714
They've been lined up.

01:27:50.714 --> 01:27:52.630
The first thing you'll
notice as you read down

01:27:52.630 --> 01:27:56.230
through these sequences is that
they're basically identical.

01:27:56.230 --> 01:28:00.860
In fact, humans are 99.9%
identical at the DNA level.

01:28:00.860 --> 01:28:02.300
We only differ,
on average, at one

01:28:02.300 --> 01:28:05.840
in every thousand nucleotides
positions from someone we're

01:28:05.840 --> 01:28:07.760
not even closely related to.

01:28:07.760 --> 01:28:11.039
So it's actually quite difficult
to find these genetic markers.

01:28:11.039 --> 01:28:12.830
But if you look carefully
enough, down here

01:28:12.830 --> 01:28:16.776
in this region, GGGG GAG.

01:28:16.776 --> 01:28:20.340
A single letter change from
a G to an A, that's a marker.

01:28:20.340 --> 01:28:22.390
If you share that
with another person,

01:28:22.390 --> 01:28:23.870
you share an
ancestor-- the person

01:28:23.870 --> 01:28:28.010
who first had that change and
passed it on to the two of you.

01:28:28.010 --> 01:28:31.090
And by looking at the pattern
of these markers in people

01:28:31.090 --> 01:28:32.750
from all over the
world, focusing

01:28:32.750 --> 01:28:35.380
in particular on what you heard
about earlier-- mitochondrial

01:28:35.380 --> 01:28:37.460
DNA, the Y
chromosome-- we've been

01:28:37.460 --> 01:28:40.890
able to construct family trees
for everybody alive today.

01:28:40.890 --> 01:28:44.190
Everybody in this room-- in
fact, everybody walking around

01:28:44.190 --> 01:28:46.720
on planet Earth all
7.2 billion of us

01:28:46.720 --> 01:28:50.140
falls somewhere onto one of
the branches of these trees.

01:28:50.140 --> 01:28:53.430
Now, these are very,
very simplified versions

01:28:53.430 --> 01:28:54.930
of the assays we
actually when we're

01:28:54.930 --> 01:28:57.230
designed in the essays
in the laboratory.

01:28:57.230 --> 01:28:59.570
But they still look
complicated, sitting out there

01:28:59.570 --> 01:29:02.510
in the audience in the morning.

01:29:02.510 --> 01:29:05.011
So let's simplify them, combine
them, turn them on the sides

01:29:05.011 --> 01:29:06.801
so the roots at the
bottom and the branches

01:29:06.801 --> 01:29:08.170
are at the top like a real tree.

01:29:08.170 --> 01:29:10.440
What's the take-home
message here?

01:29:10.440 --> 01:29:13.810
Well, it's that the longest
branches in the human family

01:29:13.810 --> 01:29:17.650
tree, the branches with the
most mutational changes in them,

01:29:17.650 --> 01:29:22.000
if you will, are found only
in African populations.

01:29:22.000 --> 01:29:23.550
And what that means
is that because

01:29:23.550 --> 01:29:26.610
of this molecular clock-like
process, the mutations ticking

01:29:26.610 --> 01:29:28.700
off at 100 per genome
per generation,

01:29:28.700 --> 01:29:31.450
Africans have been accumulating
genetic variation for longer

01:29:31.450 --> 01:29:33.020
than any other group.

01:29:33.020 --> 01:29:36.100
And, therefore, our species
originated in Africa.

01:29:36.100 --> 01:29:38.280
And at some point in
the past, a small group

01:29:38.280 --> 01:29:40.130
carrying a subset
of African diversity

01:29:40.130 --> 01:29:42.594
set out to leave
Africa and colonized

01:29:42.594 --> 01:29:43.510
the rest of the world.

01:29:43.510 --> 01:29:43.740
OK.

01:29:43.740 --> 01:29:45.410
So we're back where
Darwin started.

01:29:45.410 --> 01:29:48.310
Except we're not.

01:29:48.310 --> 01:29:50.450
We're not talking about
23 million years ago.

01:29:50.450 --> 01:29:51.850
We're talking
about an event that

01:29:51.850 --> 01:29:55.040
happened within the last 200,000
years, which is in agreement

01:29:55.040 --> 01:29:56.260
with the fossil record.

01:29:56.260 --> 01:29:59.380
Modern humans first appear
at Omo Kibish in Ethiopia,

01:29:59.380 --> 01:30:01.290
195,000 years ago.

01:30:01.290 --> 01:30:05.160
That's roughly the coalescence
point for mitochondrial DNA.

01:30:05.160 --> 01:30:08.260
And it's only in the
last 60,000 years--

01:30:08.260 --> 01:30:10.790
2,000 human
generations-- that we've

01:30:10.790 --> 01:30:13.830
set out to colonize
the rest of the planet.

01:30:13.830 --> 01:30:16.280
An early coastal migration
leading very rapidly

01:30:16.280 --> 01:30:17.650
to Australia.

01:30:17.650 --> 01:30:20.140
Later inland migrations
moving to Europe,

01:30:20.140 --> 01:30:22.800
crossing the Bering land
bridge into the Americas--

01:30:22.800 --> 01:30:26.380
the great paleolithic
wanderings of our species.

01:30:26.380 --> 01:30:30.530
And it's really detailing
these migration patterns.

01:30:30.530 --> 01:30:32.910
That's been the goal of
the Genographic project

01:30:32.910 --> 01:30:35.950
over the course of
the last decade.

01:30:35.950 --> 01:30:38.406
Now, what is
Genographic all about?

01:30:38.406 --> 01:30:39.530
You referred to it earlier.

01:30:39.530 --> 01:30:41.710
Thank you very
much for the intro.

01:30:41.710 --> 01:30:44.420
At its core, it's
a research effort.

01:30:44.420 --> 01:30:47.140
It's an effort to make
sense of the human journey,

01:30:47.140 --> 01:30:48.430
the human story.

01:30:48.430 --> 01:30:50.060
And this is field
research that's

01:30:50.060 --> 01:30:52.360
being carried out by a
consortium of scientists

01:30:52.360 --> 01:30:54.550
around the world,
working primarily

01:30:54.550 --> 01:30:58.020
with indigenous people, world's
traditional and indigenous

01:30:58.020 --> 01:30:58.520
groups.

01:30:58.520 --> 01:31:01.880
Now, why are indigenous people
so important to this effort?

01:31:01.880 --> 01:31:03.830
Well, think about
your own ancestry.

01:31:03.830 --> 01:31:05.430
I'll think about mine out loud.

01:31:05.430 --> 01:31:08.080
I have ancestors from all over
northern and western Europe.

01:31:08.080 --> 01:31:11.250
I lived until very
recently in Washington, DC.

01:31:11.250 --> 01:31:13.640
Just recently moved
to Austin, Texas.

01:31:13.640 --> 01:31:16.310
What does my DNA tell you
about the ancient patterns

01:31:16.310 --> 01:31:17.550
in any of those places?

01:31:17.550 --> 01:31:19.840
It's hard to say,
because I'm a mutt.

01:31:19.840 --> 01:31:23.500
And I've moved around a lot
recently, or my ancestors have.

01:31:23.500 --> 01:31:25.130
Ideally, we want
people who have lived

01:31:25.130 --> 01:31:28.292
in the same place for a long
period of time, thousands,

01:31:28.292 --> 01:31:30.250
tens of thousands, even,
in the case of Africa,

01:31:30.250 --> 01:31:31.900
hundreds of thousands of years.

01:31:31.900 --> 01:31:34.310
The world's indigenous
and traditional people.

01:31:34.310 --> 01:31:37.820
And they give us that glimpse
of the ancient genetic patterns

01:31:37.820 --> 01:31:40.170
linked to a particular
geographic location that

01:31:40.170 --> 01:31:44.240
allow us to make sense of
these human migrations.

01:31:44.240 --> 01:31:45.900
But when we were
designing the project,

01:31:45.900 --> 01:31:48.420
I felt very strongly
that it should not just

01:31:48.420 --> 01:31:51.531
be the story of the world's
100, maybe 200, million

01:31:51.531 --> 01:31:52.280
indigenous people.

01:31:52.280 --> 01:31:53.970
It's the story of all of us.

01:31:53.970 --> 01:31:55.270
All 7.2 billion.

01:31:55.270 --> 01:31:56.924
So we wanted to open
it up to members

01:31:56.924 --> 01:31:59.090
of the general public who
were interested in testing

01:31:59.090 --> 01:32:01.710
their own DNA, getting
the results back, but also

01:32:01.710 --> 01:32:05.110
joining the project, increasing
the size of the database,

01:32:05.110 --> 01:32:09.370
giving us more power to
detail these migratory routes.

01:32:09.370 --> 01:32:11.670
So the public participation
side, a very important

01:32:11.670 --> 01:32:13.160
component.

01:32:13.160 --> 01:32:15.232
By selling the kits
we help to fund

01:32:15.232 --> 01:32:16.940
the research we're
doing out in the field

01:32:16.940 --> 01:32:18.939
with the indigenous
populations, who, obviously,

01:32:18.939 --> 01:32:20.420
can't afford to buy a kit.

01:32:20.420 --> 01:32:22.980
And also, the third
component, the legacy fund.

01:32:22.980 --> 01:32:26.030
This is a way to give something
tangible back to the world's

01:32:26.030 --> 01:32:29.410
indigenous and traditional
groups, many of whom

01:32:29.410 --> 01:32:32.760
are leading ways of life
that are endangered today.

01:32:32.760 --> 01:32:34.260
They're often forced
to leave behind

01:32:34.260 --> 01:32:36.680
their ancient villages,
their homelands, typically

01:32:36.680 --> 01:32:38.810
moving to a growing megacity.

01:32:38.810 --> 01:32:41.050
They become part
of the melting pot.

01:32:41.050 --> 01:32:44.300
Their kids stop speaking
the original language.

01:32:44.300 --> 01:32:46.499
They lose the culture
within a generation or two.

01:32:46.499 --> 01:32:48.040
We're actually going
through a period

01:32:48.040 --> 01:32:50.900
of cultural mass extinction
at the moment that parallels

01:32:50.900 --> 01:32:53.050
the biodiversity crisis.

01:32:53.050 --> 01:32:56.090
Linguists tell us that of the
6,000-some-odd languages spoken

01:32:56.090 --> 01:32:58.570
on Earth today, by the
end of this century,

01:32:58.570 --> 01:33:03.290
between half and 90% will be
extinct, no longer spoken.

01:33:03.290 --> 01:33:05.819
We're losing a language
every two weeks.

01:33:05.819 --> 01:33:07.360
So through the legacy
grants, we want

01:33:07.360 --> 01:33:09.390
to do something to raise
awareness about this,

01:33:09.390 --> 01:33:14.112
and if we can, to slow
it, or even to halt it.

01:33:14.112 --> 01:33:15.070
Well, how are we doing?

01:33:15.070 --> 01:33:17.190
How have we done in the project?

01:33:17.190 --> 01:33:20.830
Well, an easy way is
to look at numbers.

01:33:20.830 --> 01:33:23.920
On the indigenous side, we've
sampled roughly 72,000 people

01:33:23.920 --> 01:33:26.070
representing over 1,000
different populations

01:33:26.070 --> 01:33:27.620
from every inhabited continent.

01:33:27.620 --> 01:33:30.110
Not Antarctica, obviously.

01:33:30.110 --> 01:33:32.400
Published more than
50 scientific papers.

01:33:32.400 --> 01:33:34.250
Have several more
in the pipeline.

01:33:34.250 --> 01:33:36.860
So that's gone very well.

01:33:36.860 --> 01:33:39.450
The big surprise,
though, for me,

01:33:39.450 --> 01:33:42.810
has been the excitement on
the part of the general public

01:33:42.810 --> 01:33:45.110
in getting their own DNA tested.

01:33:45.110 --> 01:33:47.170
When we were
designing the project,

01:33:47.170 --> 01:33:51.170
I had a bet with the then-CEO
of National Geographic, John

01:33:51.170 --> 01:33:53.990
Fahey, about how many of these
kits we were going to sell.

01:33:53.990 --> 01:33:55.660
He said, Spencer,
if you sell 1,000

01:33:55.660 --> 01:33:58.640
of these things in the next
few years, you'll be lucky.

01:33:58.640 --> 01:34:01.342
Nobody's going to pay $100
to get their DNA tested.

01:34:01.342 --> 01:34:03.299
I said, I don't know, John.

01:34:03.299 --> 01:34:03.840
I don't know.

01:34:03.840 --> 01:34:06.130
I think there's
something to this.

01:34:06.130 --> 01:34:10.620
The day we launched the project,
10,000 people ordered kits.

01:34:10.620 --> 01:34:14.060
And we hit 100,000 eight months
later at the end of 2005.

01:34:14.060 --> 01:34:15.990
And we're up to
around 700,000, now.

01:34:15.990 --> 01:34:18.190
More than 140
different countries.

01:34:18.190 --> 01:34:21.060
We've even sold two
to Vatican City.

01:34:21.060 --> 01:34:22.410
Very curious about those two.

01:34:26.394 --> 01:34:29.060
And it's raised a fair amount of
money, obviously, for the field

01:34:29.060 --> 01:34:32.230
research, and also the legacy
fund, which we've given away

01:34:32.230 --> 01:34:34.530
$2.5 million so far.

01:34:34.530 --> 01:34:37.350
Just some examples of
projects that we've funded.

01:34:37.350 --> 01:34:40.010
Project to save the Yaghnobi
language, the last remnant

01:34:40.010 --> 01:34:43.710
of ancient Sogdian, once the
lingua franca of the Silk Road.

01:34:43.710 --> 01:34:46.637
If you had gone to Bukhara
or Samarkand or Kashgar

01:34:46.637 --> 01:34:49.220
1,500 years ago, you would have
been speaking to the merchants

01:34:49.220 --> 01:34:52.440
with this language, now spoken
by around 1,500 people who,

01:34:52.440 --> 01:34:55.370
historically, have lived in
the remote Zeravshan River

01:34:55.370 --> 01:34:57.130
Valley of northern Tajikistan.

01:34:57.130 --> 01:35:00.150
Most have now been resettled
to the capital, Duchanbe,

01:35:00.150 --> 01:35:02.380
and their kids learn to
speak Russian and Tajik.

01:35:02.380 --> 01:35:05.070
And so the language is literally
on the verge of extinction.

01:35:05.070 --> 01:35:08.150
We're helping to fund school
curricula in the Yaghnobi

01:35:08.150 --> 01:35:09.450
language.

01:35:09.450 --> 01:35:12.179
Project to preserve a
traditional dance pattern

01:35:12.179 --> 01:35:14.220
among the aborigines in
the northern territories.

01:35:14.220 --> 01:35:19.870
Their song lines, their stories
of where they came from.

01:35:19.870 --> 01:35:23.390
A project along the Yukon River,
an intertribal collaboration

01:35:23.390 --> 01:35:26.360
with tribes from Northwest
Territories in Alaska

01:35:26.360 --> 01:35:28.490
to raise awareness about
the environmental issues

01:35:28.490 --> 01:35:30.390
that are affecting, in
particular, the salmon

01:35:30.390 --> 01:35:33.117
population there, which is so
important their way of life.

01:35:33.117 --> 01:35:34.700
And this is a great
example for people

01:35:34.700 --> 01:35:38.600
who need a practical reason
for saving this information

01:35:38.600 --> 01:35:39.930
and these cultures.

01:35:39.930 --> 01:35:41.450
The Shuar people
trying to preserve

01:35:41.450 --> 01:35:43.820
their ethnobotanical knowledge.

01:35:43.820 --> 01:35:46.760
Now, how many people have
been prescribed a medication

01:35:46.760 --> 01:35:48.970
by their physician recently?

01:35:48.970 --> 01:35:50.450
Probably most of us.

01:35:50.450 --> 01:35:53.520
And about 30% to 40%
of those ultimately

01:35:53.520 --> 01:35:55.880
trace back to plant sources.

01:35:55.880 --> 01:35:57.720
We often know about
these plant sources

01:35:57.720 --> 01:36:00.410
because of accumulated
traditional knowledge.

01:36:00.410 --> 01:36:04.560
Tens of thousands of years
by thousands of populations

01:36:04.560 --> 01:36:06.290
experimenting with
their environment,

01:36:06.290 --> 01:36:09.560
learning which plants do
certain things and which don't.

01:36:09.560 --> 01:36:12.350
When we lose that
body of knowledge,

01:36:12.350 --> 01:36:16.420
how many potential treatments
for cancer or Ebola or HIV

01:36:16.420 --> 01:36:18.050
might we be missing out on?

01:36:18.050 --> 01:36:18.699
We don't know.

01:36:18.699 --> 01:36:20.115
But I think it's
worth preserving.

01:36:23.120 --> 01:36:27.134
So I'm often asked, what's
your biggest surprise?

01:36:27.134 --> 01:36:29.800
What's the most surprising thing
that's come out of the project?

01:36:29.800 --> 01:36:31.830
And there are
scientific discoveries,

01:36:31.830 --> 01:36:35.700
ranging from populations
fissioning off in Africa long

01:36:35.700 --> 01:36:38.600
before we started to leave
and headed toward becoming

01:36:38.600 --> 01:36:42.490
separate species, or the
genetic impact of Ghengis Khan,

01:36:42.490 --> 01:36:43.910
whatever it might be.

01:36:43.910 --> 01:36:46.896
But the big surprise for
me has been the excitement

01:36:46.896 --> 01:36:48.270
on the part of
the general public

01:36:48.270 --> 01:36:50.420
in getting involved
in this project.

01:36:50.420 --> 01:36:53.960
In particular, the power of
what we call citizen science--

01:36:53.960 --> 01:36:56.340
non-specialists getting
actively involved

01:36:56.340 --> 01:36:57.802
in the research project.

01:36:57.802 --> 01:36:59.010
And I've got a great example.

01:36:59.010 --> 01:37:02.470
This came to light by
accident a few years ago.

01:37:02.470 --> 01:37:04.420
A woman writes into
the project and says,

01:37:04.420 --> 01:37:05.580
love what you're doing.

01:37:05.580 --> 01:37:08.342
Lots of members of my extended
family have taken part.

01:37:08.342 --> 01:37:09.800
We've told lots of
people about it.

01:37:09.800 --> 01:37:11.180
It's very, very exciting.

01:37:11.180 --> 01:37:12.450
So cool.

01:37:12.450 --> 01:37:17.520
However, it seems like
you got my results wrong.

01:37:17.520 --> 01:37:19.250
And I'd like you to retest me.

01:37:19.250 --> 01:37:21.320
Because what you've
told me is I'm

01:37:21.320 --> 01:37:24.740
carrying a mitochondrial type
that's common in Central Asia

01:37:24.740 --> 01:37:26.410
and Siberia.

01:37:26.410 --> 01:37:29.040
And I know for a fact from
the genealogical records

01:37:29.040 --> 01:37:30.900
that my family came
from a little village

01:37:30.900 --> 01:37:33.000
just outside of
Budapest, which you're

01:37:33.000 --> 01:37:34.210
looking at here in Hungary.

01:37:34.210 --> 01:37:35.760
So clearly, I've
got to be European.

01:37:35.760 --> 01:37:38.630
I can show you records going
back to the 16th century.

01:37:38.630 --> 01:37:39.790
Please retest me.

01:37:39.790 --> 01:37:41.130
Thank you very much.

01:37:41.130 --> 01:37:44.140
Now, when I heard about
this, I got really excited,

01:37:44.140 --> 01:37:45.770
not because I enjoy
asking the lab

01:37:45.770 --> 01:37:49.070
to cherry-pick one sample
out of 3/4 of a million.

01:37:49.070 --> 01:37:50.960
They tend to get a little
annoyed about that.

01:37:50.960 --> 01:37:53.010
But rather, because
the Hungarians

01:37:53.010 --> 01:37:54.180
have a fascinating history.

01:37:54.180 --> 01:37:57.862
Linguistically, they're very
different from other groups

01:37:57.862 --> 01:37:58.570
living in Europe.

01:37:58.570 --> 01:38:02.820
Most of Europe's languages fall
into the Indo-European language

01:38:02.820 --> 01:38:04.690
family that we
heard about before.

01:38:04.690 --> 01:38:07.320
A Western Eurasian collection
of languages that includes

01:38:07.320 --> 01:38:08.890
the one I'm speaking now.

01:38:08.890 --> 01:38:12.830
Part of the Germanic branch
of Indo-European languages.

01:38:12.830 --> 01:38:15.410
Romance languages--
French, Italian,

01:38:15.410 --> 01:38:18.210
and Spanish-- the
Celtic languages,

01:38:18.210 --> 01:38:20.110
the Slavic languages,
and so on, all parts

01:38:20.110 --> 01:38:24.220
of the single language family
that probably originated

01:38:24.220 --> 01:38:27.260
somewhere in the southern
Russian or Ukrainian steppe

01:38:27.260 --> 01:38:28.780
6,000 to 8,000 years ago.

01:38:28.780 --> 01:38:31.341
And the languages have
diversified over time.

01:38:31.341 --> 01:38:33.340
Except there are a couple
of languages in Europe

01:38:33.340 --> 01:38:36.030
that don't fall into that
category, into that family.

01:38:36.030 --> 01:38:39.750
One is Basque, which is what
we call a linguistic isolate.

01:38:39.750 --> 01:38:41.474
It's unrelated to
anything else on Earth,

01:38:41.474 --> 01:38:42.390
as far as we can tell.

01:38:42.390 --> 01:38:45.380
It could've been
brought here from Mars.

01:38:45.380 --> 01:38:47.629
Might be distantly related
to ancient Sumerian

01:38:47.629 --> 01:38:49.920
and some of the languages
spoken in the north Caucasus,

01:38:49.920 --> 01:38:53.061
like Daghastani, but
it's very, very tenuous.

01:38:53.061 --> 01:38:53.560
OK.

01:38:53.560 --> 01:38:56.410
That's off on its own.

01:38:56.410 --> 01:38:59.470
Hungarian is a member of a
different language family.

01:38:59.470 --> 01:39:01.800
It's related to languages
spoken in Finland,

01:39:01.800 --> 01:39:05.290
in Lapland, the Saami languages
of northern Scandinavia.

01:39:05.290 --> 01:39:08.390
All part of what we call
the Uralic language family.

01:39:08.390 --> 01:39:10.820
And as you can see, most of
the diversity in that family

01:39:10.820 --> 01:39:13.210
lies over in Siberia.

01:39:13.210 --> 01:39:14.930
And this makes
sense, because it's

01:39:14.930 --> 01:39:19.020
believed that the ancestors
of the Laplanders, the Saami

01:39:19.020 --> 01:39:21.580
people, migrated into
northern Scandinavia

01:39:21.580 --> 01:39:24.250
from Siberia within
the last 5,000 years,

01:39:24.250 --> 01:39:25.960
bringing with them
their language that

01:39:25.960 --> 01:39:27.850
belong to this Siberian group.

01:39:27.850 --> 01:39:30.240
We also know from
historical sources

01:39:30.240 --> 01:39:33.660
that people from somewhere
further east-- the Magyar

01:39:33.660 --> 01:39:37.800
people-- around 1,000 AD
migrated into central Europe,

01:39:37.800 --> 01:39:40.610
settled there and created
present-day Hungary, bringing

01:39:40.610 --> 01:39:44.252
with them their culture, their
love of chicken paprikash--

01:39:44.252 --> 01:39:46.460
that actually came later,
because peppers, of course,

01:39:46.460 --> 01:39:48.220
come from the new world.

01:39:48.220 --> 01:39:49.690
But anyway, the
Hungarian language.

01:39:49.690 --> 01:39:53.820
So they had a massive cultural
impact on central Europe.

01:39:53.820 --> 01:39:56.530
And so geneticists,
using this as a guide--

01:39:56.530 --> 01:39:58.250
and we often use
linguistic patterns

01:39:58.250 --> 01:40:01.266
as a guide when we're thinking
about the sampling-- went in

01:40:01.266 --> 01:40:03.140
and sample the number
of people you typically

01:40:03.140 --> 01:40:05.180
study in one of these projects.

01:40:05.180 --> 01:40:06.770
50, 75 people.

01:40:06.770 --> 01:40:09.380
And what they found is that
the Hungarians are identical,

01:40:09.380 --> 01:40:12.380
essentially, genetically to
the surrounding non-Hungarian

01:40:12.380 --> 01:40:13.870
speakers.

01:40:13.870 --> 01:40:15.390
You don't see any
genetic evidence

01:40:15.390 --> 01:40:18.230
for this huge cultural shift.

01:40:18.230 --> 01:40:21.580
So when this woman
wrote in to us, I said,

01:40:21.580 --> 01:40:24.630
well, here's an opportunity to
see if this public database is

01:40:24.630 --> 01:40:25.990
actually useful.

01:40:25.990 --> 01:40:28.870
We don't have to limit ourselves
to the scientific sample sizes.

01:40:28.870 --> 01:40:32.190
How many samples do we have
in the database from people

01:40:32.190 --> 01:40:33.400
with Hungarian ancestry?

01:40:33.400 --> 01:40:36.530
Well, we had 2,300 at that time.

01:40:36.530 --> 01:40:39.470
And lo and behold, we
found that 2% to 3%

01:40:39.470 --> 01:40:41.770
of the lineages on both
the male and female side

01:40:41.770 --> 01:40:43.560
were coming out of Asia.

01:40:43.560 --> 01:40:44.740
So that makes sense.

01:40:44.740 --> 01:40:45.700
Power of large numbers.

01:40:45.700 --> 01:40:48.930
We knew that was going to be
something cool about creating

01:40:48.930 --> 01:40:50.610
this large database.

01:40:50.610 --> 01:40:55.260
But the only reason we knew
to look for this pattern

01:40:55.260 --> 01:40:57.980
is because this
woman wrote in to us.

01:40:57.980 --> 01:41:00.730
And that is the power
of citizen science.

01:41:00.730 --> 01:41:03.810
Instead of having a few
scientists sit back and say,

01:41:03.810 --> 01:41:06.210
these are the important
things we should be studying,

01:41:06.210 --> 01:41:09.290
we dispersed that out
into the community.

01:41:09.290 --> 01:41:11.470
And you've got, effectively,
hundreds of thousands

01:41:11.470 --> 01:41:14.756
of scientists, now, who
are looking independently

01:41:14.756 --> 01:41:16.630
at their own data, trying
to make sense of it

01:41:16.630 --> 01:41:18.910
and finding patterns like this.

01:41:18.910 --> 01:41:21.430
And building that kind of
citizen science functionality

01:41:21.430 --> 01:41:25.040
into the project has been a very
important part of the relaunch

01:41:25.040 --> 01:41:26.680
that we did a
couple of years ago

01:41:26.680 --> 01:41:30.520
in the creation of Geno 2.0.

01:41:30.520 --> 01:41:34.580
I'm going to end by talking
a little bit about consumer

01:41:34.580 --> 01:41:35.170
genomics.

01:41:35.170 --> 01:41:38.390
And I despise the term
direct-to-consumer genomics,

01:41:38.390 --> 01:41:41.580
because we don't talk about
direct-to-consumer bookselling.

01:41:41.580 --> 01:41:43.150
Direct-to-consumer
implies that there

01:41:43.150 --> 01:41:45.607
should be a mediator that's
making decisions for you.

01:41:45.607 --> 01:41:47.940
And I feel very strongly that
genomic information should

01:41:47.940 --> 01:41:50.889
be available to
anybody who wants it.

01:41:50.889 --> 01:41:52.430
I want to talk a
little bit about how

01:41:52.430 --> 01:41:53.740
the industry has progressed.

01:41:53.740 --> 01:41:56.530
And it's really
reflected in this graph.

01:41:56.530 --> 01:42:01.070
These are number of people who
have bought kits, DNA testing

01:42:01.070 --> 01:42:01.980
kits.

01:42:01.980 --> 01:42:05.070
So the industry traces
back to around 2002, when

01:42:05.070 --> 01:42:08.050
Bennett Greenspan founded
Family Tree DNA down

01:42:08.050 --> 01:42:11.210
in Houston, primarily
because he was

01:42:11.210 --> 01:42:13.440
interested in looking
at his Y chromosome

01:42:13.440 --> 01:42:16.040
to see if he is a
descendant of Aaron,

01:42:16.040 --> 01:42:18.789
carrying the Cohen
modal haplotype.

01:42:18.789 --> 01:42:21.080
And I'm not going to go into
the details on that story.

01:42:21.080 --> 01:42:22.934
But there is very,
very good evidence

01:42:22.934 --> 01:42:24.600
that you can find a
genetic pattern that

01:42:24.600 --> 01:42:29.810
links Ashkenazi Jews living
today to this historical figure

01:42:29.810 --> 01:42:32.780
within the last
3,000 to 4,000 years.

01:42:32.780 --> 01:42:34.700
So he founded this
company, primarily driven

01:42:34.700 --> 01:42:35.710
by personal curiosity.

01:42:35.710 --> 01:42:38.470
It was very much a
cottage industry.

01:42:38.470 --> 01:42:41.970
Literally, a few hundred
people would hear about this

01:42:41.970 --> 01:42:44.340
and decide to get themselves
tested every year.

01:42:44.340 --> 01:42:47.710
And then we went live
with Geographic in 2005.

01:42:47.710 --> 01:42:50.760
And the numbers started
to tick up significantly.

01:42:50.760 --> 01:42:55.100
23 and Me and Navigenics
launched in 2007,

01:42:55.100 --> 01:42:56.940
in part off of the
back of our success

01:42:56.940 --> 01:42:59.170
showing that there was
a viable business there.

01:42:59.170 --> 01:43:00.878
But they launched with
products that were

01:43:00.878 --> 01:43:03.390
priced at $1,000 and $2,500.

01:43:03.390 --> 01:43:05.940
So not a lot of
people buying those.

01:43:05.940 --> 01:43:08.800
They dropped the
price in 2008, 2009.

01:43:08.800 --> 01:43:10.830
And you see this uptick here.

01:43:10.830 --> 01:43:13.850
We continue up until 2013.

01:43:13.850 --> 01:43:16.250
End of 2012 beginning of 2013.

01:43:16.250 --> 01:43:20.910
The millionth person
purchases a test kit.

01:43:20.910 --> 01:43:25.720
So it took us 11 years to
go from zero to a million.

01:43:25.720 --> 01:43:30.610
The second millionth person
bought a kit a year later.

01:43:30.610 --> 01:43:33.250
And we're over four
million now, or will

01:43:33.250 --> 01:43:35.500
be by the end of this year.

01:43:35.500 --> 01:43:37.200
No signs of it asymptoting.

01:43:37.200 --> 01:43:40.380
And this is a really,
really interesting curve

01:43:40.380 --> 01:43:41.650
from a business point of view.

01:43:41.650 --> 01:43:43.260
So there are lots
of companies that

01:43:43.260 --> 01:43:46.630
have piled into this space.

01:43:46.630 --> 01:43:49.165
My buddy Ken Shaheen
at Ancestry tells me

01:43:49.165 --> 01:43:51.290
that they're probably going
to sell between 500,000

01:43:51.290 --> 01:43:54.600
and 700,000 kits
next year alone.

01:43:54.600 --> 01:43:57.340
So why is this happening now?

01:43:57.340 --> 01:43:58.690
Or in the last couple of years.

01:43:58.690 --> 01:44:00.510
Well, there are a few reasons.

01:44:00.510 --> 01:44:03.670
I think DNA has become part
of the national consciousness.

01:44:03.670 --> 01:44:06.030
Big corporations
talk about whatever

01:44:06.030 --> 01:44:07.990
it is being in their DNA.

01:44:07.990 --> 01:44:10.501
People are less afraid of
Jurassic Park scenarios,

01:44:10.501 --> 01:44:12.250
because they know that
it's very unlikely.

01:44:12.250 --> 01:44:14.650
They're less concerned
about being cloned.

01:44:14.650 --> 01:44:20.447
All of these were major issues
in 2005 when we launched.

01:44:20.447 --> 01:44:22.280
People are also more
comfortable now sharing

01:44:22.280 --> 01:44:23.870
their most private information.

01:44:23.870 --> 01:44:26.350
When we launched in 2005,
there was no Twitter.

01:44:26.350 --> 01:44:27.390
There was no Facebook.

01:44:27.390 --> 01:44:29.370
And people dump stuff
out onto the internet

01:44:29.370 --> 01:44:32.340
for public consumption now
that a generation ago, people

01:44:32.340 --> 01:44:34.000
would have been appalled at.

01:44:34.000 --> 01:44:35.100
And now it's standard.

01:44:35.100 --> 01:44:37.360
And I think part of that
is trusting companies

01:44:37.360 --> 01:44:40.150
with their genetic information.

01:44:40.150 --> 01:44:43.550
And I think this is a
really important part of it.

01:44:43.550 --> 01:44:48.200
We've hit enough people having
tested themselves now that it's

01:44:48.200 --> 01:44:51.460
very likely when you
go to a cocktail party

01:44:51.460 --> 01:44:53.370
with 30 or 40
people in the room,

01:44:53.370 --> 01:44:55.870
at least one or two of them
will have tested their DNA.

01:44:55.870 --> 01:44:57.840
And they may be
talking about it.

01:44:57.840 --> 01:45:00.900
And so we've reached this
threshold for viral spread.

01:45:00.900 --> 01:45:04.520
Word of mouth, so important.

01:45:04.520 --> 01:45:06.580
A great parallel would
be the film industry.

01:45:06.580 --> 01:45:10.410
This is what the film industry
typically wants to see.

01:45:10.410 --> 01:45:14.110
You pump a ton of money upfront
before the film comes out

01:45:14.110 --> 01:45:16.890
into promotion,
marketing, advertising.

01:45:16.890 --> 01:45:19.590
And you make all your
money in the first weekend,

01:45:19.590 --> 01:45:21.260
or the first couple of weeks.

01:45:21.260 --> 01:45:24.440
So ideally, you're going to see
in the film industry something

01:45:24.440 --> 01:45:27.130
like that in terms of revenue.

01:45:27.130 --> 01:45:30.870
But occasionally, a
film will come out.

01:45:30.870 --> 01:45:32.370
And it's released
in a few theaters.

01:45:32.370 --> 01:45:35.090
And it generates some buzz and
starts to get good reviews.

01:45:35.090 --> 01:45:37.459
And the filmmakers and the
distributors say, well,

01:45:37.459 --> 01:45:39.750
maybe we should release it
in more theatres, and so on.

01:45:39.750 --> 01:45:41.540
And it continues to grow.

01:45:41.540 --> 01:45:43.100
And I think that's
what we're seeing

01:45:43.100 --> 01:45:45.020
in the genomics industry.

01:45:45.020 --> 01:45:48.400
My Big Fat Greek Wedding being
one of my favorite films,

01:45:48.400 --> 01:45:49.340
a really good example.

01:45:49.340 --> 01:45:51.423
And you'll notice that it
actually made more money

01:45:51.423 --> 01:45:52.720
in the end than Twilight did.

01:45:52.720 --> 01:45:56.406
So anyway, I'm
going to end there.

01:45:56.406 --> 01:45:59.030
And if you want more information
about the Genographic project,

01:45:59.030 --> 01:46:01.022
there's the url.

01:46:01.022 --> 01:46:02.018
Thank you.

01:46:02.018 --> 01:46:05.382
[APPLAUSE]

01:46:11.110 --> 01:46:12.420
-OK.

01:46:12.420 --> 01:46:15.650
So what we'll do now is
have a little discussion

01:46:15.650 --> 01:46:17.140
among ourselves
for a few minutes

01:46:17.140 --> 01:46:19.760
as people collect their
thoughts in the audience.

01:46:19.760 --> 01:46:23.320
And I'll ask when we
transition to the audience

01:46:23.320 --> 01:46:27.170
in a few minutes that you
stand in front of the mic,

01:46:27.170 --> 01:46:30.090
and that will be my signal
to make that transition.

01:46:30.090 --> 01:46:34.310
And put your comments in
the form of a question.

01:46:34.310 --> 01:46:35.415
Just like Jeopardy.

01:46:35.415 --> 01:46:38.720
A short question, ideally.

01:46:38.720 --> 01:46:42.460
And we'll ask you to
identify yourself, as well.

01:46:42.460 --> 01:46:50.110
So I'll start this off by
asking John a question.

01:46:50.110 --> 01:46:54.065
So you had a tree that included
Neanderthals and Denisovans

01:46:54.065 --> 01:46:55.360
and modern.

01:46:55.360 --> 01:47:01.880
And the Neanderthal had all this
flat, non-diverse branching.

01:47:01.880 --> 01:47:06.020
But the Denisovan
had just one branch.

01:47:06.020 --> 01:47:07.850
But you described all
kinds of modern DNA.

01:47:07.850 --> 01:47:14.520
Is there a difficulty there in
characterizing the diversity?

01:47:14.520 --> 01:47:15.550
Tell us about that.

01:47:15.550 --> 01:47:17.720
Sure.

01:47:17.720 --> 01:47:21.070
The Denisovan we only know about
from one genome, fundamentally.

01:47:21.070 --> 01:47:23.040
We have a couple
of other specimens

01:47:23.040 --> 01:47:24.980
that have mitochondrial
genomes that we know

01:47:24.980 --> 01:47:26.740
that it's not just a one-off.

01:47:26.740 --> 01:47:31.000
But we only a very limited
amount about its diversity.

01:47:31.000 --> 01:47:33.600
We have two ways of
looking at diversity

01:47:33.600 --> 01:47:35.930
with genomes in this sense.

01:47:35.930 --> 01:47:38.940
We could look at between
the samples, in a sense.

01:47:38.940 --> 01:47:41.030
And we can look
at within samples,

01:47:41.030 --> 01:47:43.960
because a genome
encompasses variation

01:47:43.960 --> 01:47:48.350
from the entire population
that produced it, in a sense.

01:47:48.350 --> 01:47:50.570
With Denisovans, we have
an additional option,

01:47:50.570 --> 01:47:53.910
which is to look at the
present-day people that

01:47:53.910 --> 01:47:56.490
carry some fraction
of Denisovan genes,

01:47:56.490 --> 01:47:59.720
and characterize the diversity
between that fraction

01:47:59.720 --> 01:48:04.260
in living people and that same
fraction in the ancient genome.

01:48:04.260 --> 01:48:05.760
Sort of interesting
with Denisovans,

01:48:05.760 --> 01:48:09.852
because when you do
that, the Denisovans-- I

01:48:09.852 --> 01:48:11.810
love the fact that we
have a name for something

01:48:11.810 --> 01:48:13.790
that we can't see.

01:48:13.790 --> 01:48:17.810
But the Denisovans that
contributed to living people

01:48:17.810 --> 01:48:21.440
are different from the Denisovan
that we have in this cave.

01:48:21.440 --> 01:48:23.840
That may be not too
terribly unexpected,

01:48:23.840 --> 01:48:25.990
considering that the
living people that carry it

01:48:25.990 --> 01:48:29.570
are in Australia and in
the Sahul ancient land

01:48:29.570 --> 01:48:34.160
mass, and the cave where we
find them is in the Altai.

01:48:34.160 --> 01:48:36.540
But this may have been a
population that, itself,

01:48:36.540 --> 01:48:41.020
was diverse, maybe as diverse
as living peoples' populations.

01:48:41.020 --> 01:48:44.300
Yeah, there's always a problem
comparing variation that way.

01:48:44.300 --> 01:48:46.500
But we can try to parse it out.

01:48:46.500 --> 01:48:48.280
And you look within
those genomes,

01:48:48.280 --> 01:48:52.250
and you're looking at what
are homogeneous ancestral

01:48:52.250 --> 01:48:53.900
populations of them.

01:48:53.900 --> 01:48:56.290
And where we see
divisions between them,

01:48:56.290 --> 01:48:58.830
they really stick out to us.

01:48:58.830 --> 01:49:01.960
With living people,
you're looking at-- I

01:49:01.960 --> 01:49:05.740
like to emphasize to people--
you're looking at a population

01:49:05.740 --> 01:49:09.810
structure where it's actually
very difficult to create

01:49:09.810 --> 01:49:12.590
a tree like that, because
it creates the impression

01:49:12.590 --> 01:49:14.560
that people are
quite separate, when

01:49:14.560 --> 01:49:18.000
in reality, every different
component of our genome

01:49:18.000 --> 01:49:20.030
has different geographic
distributions.

01:49:20.030 --> 01:49:22.520
In fact, we're sort of a smear.

01:49:22.520 --> 01:49:25.420
In the distant past, it looks
like we were less of a smear.

01:49:25.420 --> 01:49:31.810
It looks like we really were,
in some sense, subspecies

01:49:31.810 --> 01:49:33.220
once upon a time.

01:49:33.220 --> 01:49:34.670
And today's humans are not.

01:49:34.670 --> 01:49:37.220
Today's humans are really
clinal in their variation,

01:49:37.220 --> 01:49:40.430
and are exceptionally
similar compared

01:49:40.430 --> 01:49:41.860
to these ancient people.

01:49:41.860 --> 01:49:44.480
-So just to follow
a tiny bit more.

01:49:44.480 --> 01:49:47.060
If you did that same
exercise of comparing

01:49:47.060 --> 01:49:51.810
modern Denisovans with
ancient Denisovans, and it

01:49:51.810 --> 01:49:53.220
looks diverse.

01:49:53.220 --> 01:49:56.500
And the Neanderthals, your
whole tree was ancient.

01:49:56.500 --> 01:49:59.950
What if you look at modern
Neanderthals, like you and me?

01:49:59.950 --> 01:50:03.690
And are we non-diverse, as well?

01:50:03.690 --> 01:50:07.110
-It's a super question,
because it's the obvious one.

01:50:07.110 --> 01:50:09.040
And people haven't done it yet.

01:50:09.040 --> 01:50:13.340
We are looking at, in you
and me, 3% of our genome

01:50:13.340 --> 01:50:14.840
coming from Neanderthals.

01:50:14.840 --> 01:50:18.440
And that 3% in you
and that 3% in me

01:50:18.440 --> 01:50:20.390
doesn't overlap a whole lot.

01:50:20.390 --> 01:50:23.020
They're fundamentally
rare genes.

01:50:23.020 --> 01:50:25.420
And we are mostly
not overlapping.

01:50:25.420 --> 01:50:29.990
-So that means there is 6%
between the two of us, right?

01:50:29.990 --> 01:50:32.180
-We don't know what
the asymptote is.

01:50:32.180 --> 01:50:33.720
But if you start
adding up people,

01:50:33.720 --> 01:50:37.270
you start to get up
to-- we, today, sample,

01:50:37.270 --> 01:50:40.360
among probably everyone in
this room, more than half

01:50:40.360 --> 01:50:41.930
of the Neanderthal genome.

01:50:41.930 --> 01:50:45.820
But it's distributed
as rare segments

01:50:45.820 --> 01:50:47.720
in different ones of us.

01:50:47.720 --> 01:50:51.810
-So somebody might
have all of it, huh?

01:50:51.810 --> 01:50:56.780
-If they do, I want to write
a comic book about them.

01:50:56.780 --> 01:50:59.880
-They'll be my superhero.

01:50:59.880 --> 01:51:01.630
So quick one for Beth.

01:51:01.630 --> 01:51:04.730
By the way, any of
you can chime in here.

01:51:04.730 --> 01:51:10.680
You are making the argument
that as the habitat degraded

01:51:10.680 --> 01:51:15.620
or disappeared or went
up, the populations

01:51:15.620 --> 01:51:19.640
would track for your
stuffed animals, the horse

01:51:19.640 --> 01:51:22.860
and the caribou and so on.

01:51:22.860 --> 01:51:25.430
But for the caribou, it
looked like the population

01:51:25.430 --> 01:51:29.410
is almost perfectly flat, while
the habitat was going really

01:51:29.410 --> 01:51:30.870
south fast.

01:51:30.870 --> 01:51:33.470
So did I misinterpret that plot?

01:51:33.470 --> 01:51:34.370
-No, it's right.

01:51:34.370 --> 01:51:37.300
Caribou was
non-significant as far

01:51:37.300 --> 01:51:39.760
as tracking the habitat changes.

01:51:39.760 --> 01:51:46.640
And caribou, they've lived
in the very high Arctic,

01:51:46.640 --> 01:51:47.930
and they need this.

01:51:47.930 --> 01:51:50.890
They have a very good strategy
for surviving long-term.

01:51:50.890 --> 01:51:54.589
And that is that they hang out
in places where people don't.

01:51:54.589 --> 01:51:56.380
So they still live in
the very high Arctic.

01:51:56.380 --> 01:51:59.300
They eat lichens and
things like this.

01:51:59.300 --> 01:52:01.717
And their populations have
actually done really well,

01:52:01.717 --> 01:52:04.050
as other things that would
have been competing with them

01:52:04.050 --> 01:52:06.020
for resources have collapsed.

01:52:06.020 --> 01:52:08.600
So what you see there
is a second-order effect

01:52:08.600 --> 01:52:10.310
of the horses and
bison and mammoths

01:52:10.310 --> 01:52:12.215
disappearing from
the part of the range

01:52:12.215 --> 01:52:14.090
that they would have
overlapped with caribou.

01:52:14.090 --> 01:52:16.010
And even though the
habitat is declining,

01:52:16.010 --> 01:52:17.486
caribou have hung on.

01:52:17.486 --> 01:52:19.610
Something about their
ecology makes them different.

01:52:19.610 --> 01:52:21.620
And because there's no
longer any competition,

01:52:21.620 --> 01:52:24.275
their populations have
actually increased in size,

01:52:24.275 --> 01:52:26.400
even though the amount of
habitat available to them

01:52:26.400 --> 01:52:27.250
is declining.

01:52:27.250 --> 01:52:29.870
This is just further
proof-- like we needed any--

01:52:29.870 --> 01:52:32.640
that things don't
act in isolation.

01:52:32.640 --> 01:52:35.530
Species and organisms
are part of an ecosystem.

01:52:35.530 --> 01:52:38.110
And the ecosystem is
dynamic and always changing.

01:52:38.110 --> 01:52:40.050
And what we observe in
these different species

01:52:40.050 --> 01:52:42.524
is a combination of
effects from everything

01:52:42.524 --> 01:52:43.940
that's going on
in that ecosystem.

01:52:47.620 --> 01:52:51.150
-Spencer, you concluded on
