01:57:53.980 --> 01:57:55.440
of the past in
prehistoric creatures,

01:57:55.440 --> 01:57:57.731
whether they be people or
mammoths or other things that

01:57:57.731 --> 01:57:59.240
used to walk, so
much of, I think,

01:57:59.240 --> 01:58:02.302
our understanding of them
is through the hard tissue

01:58:02.302 --> 01:58:03.510
remains that we have of them.

01:58:03.510 --> 01:58:05.370
So the experience of
going into a museum

01:58:05.370 --> 01:58:08.550
and seeing a mounted skeleton,
or thinking about physically

01:58:08.550 --> 01:58:09.920
what they appeared like.

01:58:09.920 --> 01:58:13.202
How much do you think
the further progression

01:58:13.202 --> 01:58:14.660
of ancient genetic
technologies are

01:58:14.660 --> 01:58:17.160
going to allow us to
conceive of the soft tissue

01:58:17.160 --> 01:58:20.990
and the physiological processes
that made them different, as

01:58:20.990 --> 01:58:23.640
opposed to simply the fact
that they look different.

01:58:23.640 --> 01:58:24.830
-Please state your name.

01:58:24.830 --> 01:58:25.580
-Adam [INAUDIBLE].

01:58:28.850 --> 01:58:30.320
-Well, from the
human perspective,

01:58:30.320 --> 01:58:32.390
I would say we're
talking about things

01:58:32.390 --> 01:58:36.970
like Neanderthal immunity
and Denisovan altitude

01:58:36.970 --> 01:58:38.310
and metabolism.

01:58:38.310 --> 01:58:40.850
And that the genes
that we have today

01:58:40.850 --> 01:58:42.660
from Neanderthals in
northern Europeans

01:58:42.660 --> 01:58:45.350
seem to be associated
with lipid metabolism.

01:58:45.350 --> 01:58:47.160
It's stuff that you
never would have

01:58:47.160 --> 01:58:49.490
seen in the archaeological
fossil record.

01:58:49.490 --> 01:58:51.000
And that's really exciting.

01:58:51.000 --> 01:58:53.040
But the other side
of that excitement

01:58:53.040 --> 01:58:56.190
is that our inability--
when we see this gene

01:58:56.190 --> 01:58:57.470
is there, what does it do?

01:58:57.470 --> 01:58:59.630
Our inability to
understand that is not

01:58:59.630 --> 01:59:02.690
based on our lack of
fossil evidence anymore.

01:59:02.690 --> 01:59:05.770
It's based on what we don't
know about human biology.

01:59:05.770 --> 01:59:09.860
And so what for me
the promise of this

01:59:09.860 --> 01:59:12.530
is that by studying the
evolution of these things,

01:59:12.530 --> 01:59:14.380
we actually get a
different avenue

01:59:14.380 --> 01:59:17.050
on understanding their
biological significance.

01:59:17.050 --> 01:59:19.990
So it's actually not just
about figuring out what

01:59:19.990 --> 01:59:21.340
the Neanderthals were like.

01:59:21.340 --> 01:59:23.960
It's about using the
fact that Neanderthals

01:59:23.960 --> 01:59:26.940
have an evolutionary history
and a relationship to us

01:59:26.940 --> 01:59:29.230
to figure out how
our bodies work.

01:59:29.230 --> 01:59:30.230
And that's pretty cool.

01:59:30.230 --> 01:59:32.970
-Do you think that the majority
of Neanderthal DNA that

01:59:32.970 --> 01:59:36.026
stuck around in the human
genome has been selected for?

01:59:36.026 --> 01:59:38.160
-I think that the
majority is neutral.

01:59:38.160 --> 01:59:41.820
I think the majority
is just, here it is.

01:59:41.820 --> 01:59:45.450
It's a marker of interactions.

01:59:45.450 --> 01:59:50.480
And we know that there are
windows where nobody today has

01:59:50.480 --> 01:59:51.530
the Neanderthal version.

01:59:51.530 --> 01:59:54.070
So we know that there are
gaps that represent things

01:59:54.070 --> 01:59:55.530
that they had that didn't work.

01:59:55.530 --> 01:59:58.380
There are some things that
look like they're useful,

01:59:58.380 --> 02:00:00.960
that they've really grown in
frequency beyond what you'd

02:00:00.960 --> 02:00:02.200
expect.

02:00:02.200 --> 02:00:03.270
-MHC alleles.

02:00:03.270 --> 02:00:05.152
-Exactly.

02:00:05.152 --> 02:00:06.860
-I think this question
actually brings up

02:00:06.860 --> 02:00:09.193
something that's important,
both to the work that you're

02:00:09.193 --> 02:00:11.909
doing with mammoths and to
a lot of work that we're

02:00:11.909 --> 02:00:12.950
doing with other animals.

02:00:12.950 --> 02:00:16.120
And that is that we
now have more letters,

02:00:16.120 --> 02:00:19.550
more A's, G's, C's, and
T's than we understand.

02:00:19.550 --> 02:00:21.170
And for humans,
it's a special case.

02:00:21.170 --> 02:00:22.830
We know a lot more
about human biology

02:00:22.830 --> 02:00:24.910
than we do about
elephant biology or bison

02:00:24.910 --> 02:00:26.300
biology or horse biology.

02:00:26.300 --> 02:00:30.920
So we have the capacity to
make these lists of genes that

02:00:30.920 --> 02:00:34.130
were identified, mostly in
models-- model organisms,

02:00:34.130 --> 02:00:37.400
not wild animals-- and guess
what they might have done.

02:00:37.400 --> 02:00:39.270
But we're very much
at the point right now

02:00:39.270 --> 02:00:41.260
of trying to figure it all out.

02:00:41.260 --> 02:00:45.940
We have a lot of massive phone
books filled with numbers,

02:00:45.940 --> 02:00:48.640
but no names associated
with those numbers.

02:00:48.640 --> 02:00:51.480
-Which is a huge
shift in genetics.

02:00:51.480 --> 02:00:54.289
When I was getting my PhD
in Dick Lewontin's lab,

02:00:54.289 --> 02:00:55.830
Lewontin was famous
for saying, we've

02:00:55.830 --> 02:00:58.870
created this huge apparatus in
terms of theoretical population

02:00:58.870 --> 02:00:59.370
genetics.

02:00:59.370 --> 02:01:01.453
And we're ready to crank
the handle on the machine

02:01:01.453 --> 02:01:02.570
and get it analyzing data.

02:01:02.570 --> 02:01:03.709
Where is the data?

02:01:03.709 --> 02:01:06.000
Generating the data was the
hard part back in the '80s.

02:01:06.000 --> 02:01:07.250
And now, it's just ubiquitous.

02:01:10.460 --> 02:01:12.210
-This has been a really
wonderful morning.

02:01:12.210 --> 02:01:13.800
Thank you, all of you.

