Could that be figured
out by comparing it

02:04:03.500 --> 02:04:07.410
to non-human primates who do
not have concealed ovulation?

02:04:07.410 --> 02:04:12.600
And once you have identified
the genes associated

02:04:12.600 --> 02:04:15.150
with concealed
ovulation, I'm wildly

02:04:15.150 --> 02:04:18.900
curious to know if
the fossil records,

02:04:18.900 --> 02:04:20.730
if any of these
ancient fossils--

02:04:20.730 --> 02:04:23.590
I think if we can find an
indication that they had

02:04:23.590 --> 02:04:27.230
concealed ovulation, then I'm
really willing to speculate

02:04:27.230 --> 02:04:29.970
that they might have language
skills for a whole lot

02:04:29.970 --> 02:04:31.080
of other reasons.

02:04:31.080 --> 02:04:33.998
But I'm just wondering if
anybody's thought about that,

02:04:33.998 --> 02:04:36.664
and if that could be identified,
and what the significance of it

02:04:36.664 --> 02:04:37.164
might be.

02:04:37.164 --> 02:04:38.412
-That's a good question.

02:04:38.412 --> 02:04:40.870
--[INAUDIBLE], presumably, is
looking into stuff like that.

02:04:40.870 --> 02:04:41.180
-Yeah.

02:04:41.180 --> 02:04:42.830
There are a number
of people looking

02:04:42.830 --> 02:04:44.820
into these sorts of things.

02:04:44.820 --> 02:04:46.220
A significant problem.

02:04:46.220 --> 02:04:49.620
This falls into the category
of we don't really understand

02:04:49.620 --> 02:04:51.190
how it works in humans.

02:04:51.190 --> 02:04:53.500
And comparisons
with other primates

02:04:53.500 --> 02:04:55.310
where it's not
concealed ovulation

02:04:55.310 --> 02:04:57.520
are a window of looking at that.

02:04:57.520 --> 02:05:01.940
But also, experimental
models become a possibility.

02:05:01.940 --> 02:05:03.850
And people make
transgenic mice and try

02:05:03.850 --> 02:05:06.850
to figure out what's going on.

02:05:06.850 --> 02:05:08.920
But at the moment, we
don't know the answer.

02:05:12.760 --> 02:05:14.150
-Good morning.

02:05:14.150 --> 02:05:15.450
I'm [INAUDIBLE].

02:05:15.450 --> 02:05:17.220
I'm researcher at UMass Boston.

02:05:17.220 --> 02:05:22.186
I have a question about a very
widespread kind of notion.

02:05:22.186 --> 02:05:25.830
While both John and Spencer
pointed out that notion again,

02:05:25.830 --> 02:05:28.850
it is that I want
to see how truthful

02:05:28.850 --> 02:05:33.370
the fact that we all
originated from Africa.

02:05:33.370 --> 02:05:35.515
How about ancient people
in the Middle East?

02:05:35.515 --> 02:05:38.660
I'm Originally from
Iraq, Babylonian Assyria.

02:05:38.660 --> 02:05:41.130
And I have my own
family tree over there.

02:05:41.130 --> 02:05:44.610
And it goes back to, let's
say, just before Islam.

02:05:44.610 --> 02:05:46.490
And that's all.

02:05:46.490 --> 02:05:48.580
There's known lineage.

02:05:48.580 --> 02:05:50.280
We cannot be sure about that.

02:05:50.280 --> 02:05:52.320
So I want to know why is that?

02:05:52.320 --> 02:05:53.730
How far is that?

02:05:53.730 --> 02:05:56.500
How truthful that
kind of notion?

02:05:56.500 --> 02:06:01.300
On what basis scientists
based their notion that we all

02:06:01.300 --> 02:06:05.350
share African genes originally?

02:06:05.350 --> 02:06:06.910
-It's based on the
fact that Africans

02:06:06.910 --> 02:06:09.550
have far more genetic
diversity than people

02:06:09.550 --> 02:06:11.230
living outside of Africa.

02:06:11.230 --> 02:06:12.460
It's just absolutely clear.

02:06:12.460 --> 02:06:15.940
If I could show you a tree of
what the mitochondrial lineages

02:06:15.940 --> 02:06:19.340
really look like,
98% of the variation

02:06:19.340 --> 02:06:20.900
is found in African populations.

02:06:20.900 --> 02:06:22.562
The non-Africans
are a tiny subset.

02:06:22.562 --> 02:06:24.020
Now, we've given
them more letters,

02:06:24.020 --> 02:06:27.370
because scientists started off
looking at Native Americans

02:06:27.370 --> 02:06:28.070
and Europeans.

02:06:28.070 --> 02:06:29.790
And so they just
added new letters.

02:06:29.790 --> 02:06:31.410
So everybody in
Africa falls into what

02:06:31.410 --> 02:06:32.890
they call the L branch.

02:06:32.890 --> 02:06:35.240
But L is huge, and
very, very diverse.

02:06:35.240 --> 02:06:36.870
This is mitochondrial DNA.

02:06:36.870 --> 02:06:38.280
Same thing for nuclear DNA.

02:06:38.280 --> 02:06:40.170
You see far more
diversity within Africa

02:06:40.170 --> 02:06:41.520
than outside that.

02:06:41.520 --> 02:06:43.380
And the only way
to explain that is

02:06:43.380 --> 02:06:45.670
that people have been
living in Africa for longer,

02:06:45.670 --> 02:06:47.530
accumulating more diversity.

02:06:47.530 --> 02:06:49.699
It's had a larger
effective population size.

02:06:49.699 --> 02:06:51.740
It hasn't gone through
the sequential bottlenecks

02:06:51.740 --> 02:06:53.550
that you see in
non-African populations

02:06:53.550 --> 02:06:56.090
as they move into the Middle
East, then East Asia, then

02:06:56.090 --> 02:06:57.960
the Americas, and so on.

02:06:57.960 --> 02:07:01.180
It's just it's very clear
from the genetic information.

02:07:01.180 --> 02:07:02.990
-Yeah.

02:07:02.990 --> 02:07:06.340
We do have ancestry from
some non-African peoples.

02:07:06.340 --> 02:07:08.930
But the fraction is quite
small from Neanderthals

02:07:08.930 --> 02:07:09.870
and other people.

02:07:09.870 --> 02:07:12.920
One thing to keep in mind is
that the time scale that we're

02:07:12.920 --> 02:07:15.400
talking about for the
colonization of the world,

02:07:15.400 --> 02:07:18.540
initially, by these
African people

02:07:18.540 --> 02:07:22.790
is on the time scale of
50,000 to 70,000 years

02:07:22.790 --> 02:07:25.720
or longer, which, in
historic terms, of course,

02:07:25.720 --> 02:07:28.920
is 10 times the length
of all recorded history.

02:07:28.920 --> 02:07:33.440
So we are talking about events
that are shaded in the past.

02:07:33.440 --> 02:07:35.160
But they were events
that fundamentally

02:07:35.160 --> 02:07:37.950
shaped what today's genetic
variation throughout the world

02:07:37.950 --> 02:07:38.940
is.

02:07:38.940 --> 02:07:42.030
-Now, there are some
paleoanthropologists

02:07:42.030 --> 02:07:45.650
who feel that Homo
erectus originated in Asia

02:07:45.650 --> 02:07:48.460
and migrated back into
Africa, and ultimately that's

02:07:48.460 --> 02:07:51.280
the source of modern humans.

02:07:51.280 --> 02:07:54.140
In a long circuitous
way, ultimately, erectus

02:07:54.140 --> 02:07:55.600
does come out of Africa as well.

02:07:55.600 --> 02:07:58.120
But they went out into Asia,
and possibly came back,

02:07:58.120 --> 02:07:59.160
and then went back out.

02:07:59.160 --> 02:08:00.820
It's very complicated.

02:08:00.820 --> 02:08:04.530
-The earliest good erectus stuff
we have is outside of Africa.

02:08:04.530 --> 02:08:05.306
-Dmanisi.

02:08:05.306 --> 02:08:05.930
-Yeah, Dmanisi.

02:08:05.930 --> 02:08:10.530
So it's quite possible that
there were multiple foci that

02:08:10.530 --> 02:08:14.060
led to, ultimately, the success
and proliferation of what

02:08:14.060 --> 02:08:19.600
is today a fundamentally
African origin population.

02:08:19.600 --> 02:08:21.860
-Leonard Katz, MIT.

02:08:21.860 --> 02:08:24.700
There's been debate
about what role

02:08:24.700 --> 02:08:26.840
lethal raiding
between groups may

02:08:26.840 --> 02:08:29.850
have played in human evolution.

02:08:29.850 --> 02:08:33.540
Besides some evidence from
hunter gatherer groups,

02:08:33.540 --> 02:08:36.040
there's that of
chimpanzees, which

02:08:36.040 --> 02:08:38.980
practice lethal intergroup
raiding, which can lead

02:08:38.980 --> 02:08:41.630
to local extinctions of groups.

02:08:41.630 --> 02:08:43.790
On the other hand,
there were the bonobos,

02:08:43.790 --> 02:08:47.830
which seem to be nicer.

02:08:47.830 --> 02:08:51.230
In something that
NPR ran this summer,

02:08:51.230 --> 02:08:56.110
they seem to be suggesting
that that interbreeding shows

02:08:56.110 --> 02:08:58.350
that our ancestors
were like bonobos.

02:08:58.350 --> 02:09:02.220
On the other hand,
there is genetic data

02:09:02.220 --> 02:09:07.520
that seem to show differences
between mitochondrial DNA and Y

02:09:07.520 --> 02:09:09.930
chromosome DNA in
populations, which

02:09:09.930 --> 02:09:14.050
may show selective
wiping out of local males

02:09:14.050 --> 02:09:15.970
by conquering males.

02:09:15.970 --> 02:09:19.850
Now, how do you see
the data that you know,

02:09:19.850 --> 02:09:23.830
which is much greater,
connecting with this debate?

02:09:23.830 --> 02:09:27.110
-This is one of the big
shifts in our understanding.

02:09:27.110 --> 02:09:29.910
Archaeology has been through
a very interesting history

02:09:29.910 --> 02:09:30.890
over the last century.

02:09:30.890 --> 02:09:32.640
So a century ago,
it was a question

02:09:32.640 --> 02:09:35.940
of looking for homelands and
the wandering of peoples,

02:09:35.940 --> 02:09:38.350
and as they spread, they
spread their culture.

02:09:38.350 --> 02:09:42.310
And there was a lot of
talk of conquest and so on.

02:09:42.310 --> 02:09:46.039
And that fell out of favor in
the middle of the 20th century.

02:09:46.039 --> 02:09:48.580
What seems pretty clear there,
though, from the genetic data,

02:09:48.580 --> 02:09:51.140
is that that's probably
the way things happened.

02:09:51.140 --> 02:09:53.500
So as part of the
Genographic project

02:09:53.500 --> 02:09:56.750
we had an ancient DNA team led
by Alan Cooper and Wolfgang

02:09:56.750 --> 02:09:57.840
Haak.

02:09:57.840 --> 02:10:00.407
And they, as part of their
contribution to the project,

02:10:00.407 --> 02:10:02.490
did these things they call
transects through time.

02:10:02.490 --> 02:10:05.525
Very well-studied archaeological
sites-- Central Germany,

02:10:05.525 --> 02:10:07.900
there is one in Spain, there's
one in northeastern Europe

02:10:07.900 --> 02:10:11.340
as well-- where they go back to
about 6,000 years of history.

02:10:11.340 --> 02:10:12.530
It's well-documented.

02:10:12.530 --> 02:10:13.500
We have carbon dates.

02:10:13.500 --> 02:10:15.310
We know exactly what
the cultures are.

02:10:15.310 --> 02:10:18.520
When you see a cultural shift
at a certain point in time,

02:10:18.520 --> 02:10:20.970
you see an abrupt
genetic shift, as well.

02:10:20.970 --> 02:10:25.540
So maybe the people wandered
away and another group came in.

02:10:25.540 --> 02:10:27.830
But I think what's more
likely is that you literally

02:10:27.830 --> 02:10:30.288
had conquering groups of people
who came in and killed them

02:10:30.288 --> 02:10:31.300
off.

02:10:31.300 --> 02:10:32.111
Like it or not.

02:10:36.260 --> 02:10:37.980
My name is Irwin Shapiro.

02:10:37.980 --> 02:10:41.190
And I'm an astrophysicist
by profession.

02:10:41.190 --> 02:10:44.630
I have an interest
in biology, just as

02:10:44.630 --> 02:10:46.780
an avocation, if you will.

02:10:46.780 --> 02:10:50.670
I have a question in
regard to the DNA.

02:10:50.670 --> 02:10:56.790
I hear statements like
99.6% of the DNA of humans

02:10:56.790 --> 02:11:00.030
is the same as
chimpanzees or whatever.

02:11:00.030 --> 02:11:05.340
And I also hear
that we only know

02:11:05.340 --> 02:11:09.390
what something like
few percent of our DNA

02:11:09.390 --> 02:11:11.290
is good for-- making proteins.

02:11:11.290 --> 02:11:14.730
There are 23,000 genes,
or whatever they are.

02:11:14.730 --> 02:11:19.480
I was wondering if the
differences between individuals

02:11:19.480 --> 02:11:23.490
in a given species and between
species, whether anyone has

02:11:23.490 --> 02:11:26.200
looked at the
percent differences

02:11:26.200 --> 02:11:31.100
in the stuff we know what it
does versus the stuff we don't

02:11:31.100 --> 02:11:34.460
know what it does, and
whether this could give us

02:11:34.460 --> 02:11:39.430
any insights into possible
testing with lower animals

02:11:39.430 --> 02:11:43.530
or whatever as to what the
stuff we don't know about

02:11:43.530 --> 02:11:45.610
might be good for?

02:11:45.610 --> 02:11:47.090
If that's a coherent question.

02:11:51.240 --> 02:11:55.340
Protein-coding genes-- the
things that we know, at least,

02:11:55.340 --> 02:11:57.870
that make a protein--
tend to be conserved,

02:11:57.870 --> 02:12:02.050
which means that they don't vary
as much as other genetic parts

02:12:02.050 --> 02:12:07.250
of our genome, because if they
change, it often breaks it.

02:12:07.250 --> 02:12:09.130
Conserved means that
different species

02:12:09.130 --> 02:12:12.480
are more similar than they are
for the rest of the genome.

02:12:12.480 --> 02:12:15.790
So in that sense,
the parts that we

02:12:15.790 --> 02:12:18.380
think we know that, at
least, they make a product,

02:12:18.380 --> 02:12:22.140
and here's what it is,
tend to be less variable.

02:12:22.140 --> 02:12:24.720
But, of course, the variations
that occur in those parts

02:12:24.720 --> 02:12:28.090
tend to be pretty significant,
because they are variations

02:12:28.090 --> 02:12:29.650
that change the function.

02:12:29.650 --> 02:12:32.480
In part, we use
evidence about how much

02:12:32.480 --> 02:12:34.510
different parts
of the genome vary

02:12:34.510 --> 02:12:37.190
to try to understand how
that evolution happened.

02:12:37.190 --> 02:12:38.690
And that's true not
only, of course,

02:12:38.690 --> 02:12:40.220
within humans and
other primates,

02:12:40.220 --> 02:12:42.705
but across huge
swaths of species.

02:12:47.820 --> 02:12:49.520
-I'm Catherine [INAUDIBLE].

02:12:49.520 --> 02:12:52.320
I work with students
at Regis College.

02:12:52.320 --> 02:12:56.990
And I wanted to ask a question
related to probabilities.

02:12:56.990 --> 02:12:59.370
In other words,
when we say there's

02:12:59.370 --> 02:13:04.340
been a genetic change
discovered here,

02:13:04.340 --> 02:13:07.070
and we see that
same change here,

02:13:07.070 --> 02:13:08.870
we assume there's relationship.

02:13:08.870 --> 02:13:12.340
But what's the mathematical
probability that these two

02:13:12.340 --> 02:13:16.142
changes happened independently?

02:13:16.142 --> 02:13:17.600
-So there are
regions of the genome

02:13:17.600 --> 02:13:19.190
that change very rapidly.

02:13:19.190 --> 02:13:20.880
They're hyper-variable.

02:13:20.880 --> 02:13:23.330
Microsatellites would
be an example of that.

02:13:23.330 --> 02:13:28.560
So repeats of, say, 10
or 12 or 14 CAG CAG CAG.

02:13:28.560 --> 02:13:30.520
And they tend to
add and subtract

02:13:30.520 --> 02:13:33.930
repeats very, very rapidly
in an evolutionary sense.

02:13:33.930 --> 02:13:36.320
So in that case, you
do have convergence.

02:13:36.320 --> 02:13:40.260
We do have homoplasy, as
it's known phylogenetically.

02:13:40.260 --> 02:13:41.901
But for the typical
point mutation,

02:13:41.901 --> 02:13:43.650
unless you happen to
be in a region that's

02:13:43.650 --> 02:13:45.130
prone to a high
mutation rate, it's

02:13:45.130 --> 02:13:46.810
exceedingly rare
that you're going

02:13:46.810 --> 02:13:49.672
to see exactly the same
mutation in the same location.

02:13:49.672 --> 02:13:50.380
Just do the math.

02:13:50.380 --> 02:13:52.680
You've got 3 billion
some-odd nucleotides

02:13:52.680 --> 02:13:55.210
in the human genome.

02:13:55.210 --> 02:13:57.280
Depending on the
population size,

02:13:57.280 --> 02:13:59.420
yes, if the human population
size were infinite,

02:13:59.420 --> 02:14:01.794
you would see the same mutations
occurring independently.

02:14:01.794 --> 02:14:03.570
But the human population
size has actually

02:14:03.570 --> 02:14:06.090
been relatively small
throughout most of our history.

02:14:06.090 --> 02:14:08.090
And we went through a
near-extinction event,

02:14:08.090 --> 02:14:10.920
probably around 70,000
to 75,000 years ago,

02:14:10.920 --> 02:14:12.680
where we think the
total number of humans

02:14:12.680 --> 02:14:14.790
alive dropped down
to fewer than 10,000.

02:14:14.790 --> 02:14:16.870
Possibly as few as a
couple of thousand.

02:14:16.870 --> 02:14:17.850
We came back from that.

02:14:17.850 --> 02:14:19.970
And that's why we have
a remarkably low level

02:14:19.970 --> 02:14:22.390
of genetic variation
as a species.

02:14:22.390 --> 02:14:26.001
So it really depends on
the region of the genome

02:14:26.001 --> 02:14:26.750
you're looking at.

02:14:26.750 --> 02:14:30.460
The ones that we tend to use
to reconstruct these trees

02:14:30.460 --> 02:14:32.690
don't change that often.

02:14:32.690 --> 02:14:35.220
And because of the tree
structure and the context

02:14:35.220 --> 02:14:37.660
and the fact that
they're not recombining,

02:14:37.660 --> 02:14:40.720
and so you're dealing with
a single intact chunk of DNA

02:14:40.720 --> 02:14:42.490
for the Y chromosome
and mitochondrial

02:14:42.490 --> 02:14:45.160
DNA, when you do see
recurrent mutations,

02:14:45.160 --> 02:14:46.790
you can actually notice them.

02:14:46.790 --> 02:14:48.360
They stand out very clearly.

02:14:48.360 --> 02:14:50.610
And you can exclude
that as a marker.

02:14:50.610 --> 02:14:53.650
-In fact, we use the rates of
the genome that mutate really

02:14:53.650 --> 02:14:55.750
quickly, that change
a lot, when we're

02:14:55.750 --> 02:14:59.030
interested in learning something
that happened recently in time,

02:14:59.030 --> 02:15:01.980
and the regions of the genome
that are more conserved when

02:15:01.980 --> 02:15:04.390
we want to understand
deeper evolutionary history.

02:15:04.390 --> 02:15:06.210
So if we're trying
to reconstruct

02:15:06.210 --> 02:15:08.360
the relationship between
all great ape species,

02:15:08.360 --> 02:15:10.990
we're going to focus on
parts of the genome that

02:15:10.990 --> 02:15:12.960
mutate more slowly
than if we were going

02:15:12.960 --> 02:15:17.690
to focus on reconstructing the
population history of the bison

02:15:17.690 --> 02:15:19.170
from Wood Buffalo National Park.

02:15:19.170 --> 02:15:22.660
We might use something
that's really fast-changing.

02:15:22.660 --> 02:15:25.260
And there, you really do have
to incorporate the possibility

02:15:25.260 --> 02:15:27.190
that you see the same
mutation happening

02:15:27.190 --> 02:15:28.440
more than once in your models.

02:15:28.440 --> 02:15:29.919
And that's done
probabilistically.

02:15:33.492 --> 02:15:37.156
-We're getting close to the
last two questions, I think.

02:15:37.156 --> 02:15:38.280
-My name is Charlotte Seed.

02:15:38.280 --> 02:15:40.250
And I manage a
genetic biorepository

02:15:40.250 --> 02:15:41.730
at Northeastern University.

02:15:41.730 --> 02:15:43.980
And my question is
primarily for Beth.

02:15:43.980 --> 02:15:46.410
In the field of
ancient DNA, what

02:15:46.410 --> 02:15:47.840
are considered
the best practices

02:15:47.840 --> 02:15:49.905
for preserving these
incredibly precious samples?

02:15:49.905 --> 02:15:51.620
Do you, say, treat
them any different

02:15:51.620 --> 02:15:53.210
from the other
samples in your lab?

02:15:53.210 --> 02:15:57.300
And has your work
with these DNA samples

02:15:57.300 --> 02:16:00.840
changed, maybe, your approach
to archiving and storing

02:16:00.840 --> 02:16:03.481
current DNA?

02:16:03.481 --> 02:16:03.980
-Yes.

02:16:03.980 --> 02:16:07.360
So the biggest problem
with ancient DNA

02:16:07.360 --> 02:16:12.170
is contaminating the sample
that you already have.

02:16:12.170 --> 02:16:14.560
So we have a separate
lab that everybody

02:16:14.560 --> 02:16:15.640
wears the bunny suit in.

02:16:15.640 --> 02:16:19.540
It looks like a lab
that you might work in

02:16:19.540 --> 02:16:21.816
if you're working with
really terrible diseases.

02:16:21.816 --> 02:16:23.690
But rather than having
negative air pressure,

02:16:23.690 --> 02:16:26.452
we have positive air pressure
to push stuff out of the labs

02:16:26.452 --> 02:16:27.660
that we don't want to get in.

02:16:27.660 --> 02:16:29.110
Everybody covers up.

02:16:29.110 --> 02:16:32.040
And we never do any
sort of amplification

02:16:32.040 --> 02:16:34.440
of DNA in the ancient DNA lab.

02:16:34.440 --> 02:16:37.049
And there's only
one-directional workflow.

02:16:37.049 --> 02:16:39.190
There's all sorts of
things that we implement.

02:16:39.190 --> 02:16:40.900
Sterilize everything
that we're using.

02:16:40.900 --> 02:16:41.956
Try to eliminate DNA.

02:16:41.956 --> 02:16:42.830
And it's still there.

02:16:42.830 --> 02:16:45.129
If you do deep
sequencing of nothing,

02:16:45.129 --> 02:16:47.730
you will get all sorts of
domestic animals and human DNA.

02:16:47.730 --> 02:16:49.520
It just happens.

02:16:49.520 --> 02:16:52.480
And microbial DNA, obviously.

02:16:52.480 --> 02:16:54.870
We do know that
short-term storage affects

02:16:54.870 --> 02:16:57.000
the preservation of DNA.

02:16:57.000 --> 02:17:00.540
In 2000, long time ago,
we were using PCR just

02:17:00.540 --> 02:17:02.500
to amplify different
length fragments

02:17:02.500 --> 02:17:04.020
from different samples.

02:17:04.020 --> 02:17:06.430
In the '50s, there
was gold mining taking

02:17:06.430 --> 02:17:08.440
place in Fairbanks, Alaska.

02:17:08.440 --> 02:17:10.487
And the samples that
were discovered,

02:17:10.487 --> 02:17:13.070
the bones that were discovered
as part of this, were split up.

02:17:13.070 --> 02:17:15.542
And some of them stayed
in Alaska and some of them

02:17:15.542 --> 02:17:18.000
went to the American Museum of
Natural History in New York,

02:17:18.000 --> 02:17:19.910
where they stored
them in the attic.

02:17:19.910 --> 02:17:21.930
And in Alaska at
the museum, there

02:17:21.930 --> 02:17:23.650
was a constant temperature.

02:17:23.650 --> 02:17:25.809
Little bit colder than
room temperature room

02:17:25.809 --> 02:17:26.870
where they were stored.

02:17:26.870 --> 02:17:29.639
So we took samples that were the
same age-- about 20,000 years

02:17:29.639 --> 02:17:31.100
old-- and amplified them.

02:17:31.100 --> 02:17:33.219
They were all taken out
of the ground in Fairbanks

02:17:33.219 --> 02:17:34.420
in the '50s.

02:17:34.420 --> 02:17:38.750
And the samples that were in
New York, the average fragment

02:17:38.750 --> 02:17:40.250
length that we could
get out of them

02:17:40.250 --> 02:17:42.059
was about 70 or 80 base pairs.

02:17:42.059 --> 02:17:44.959
But we could get 600 to
700 base pair fragments out

02:17:44.959 --> 02:17:45.980
of the Alaskan ones.

02:17:45.980 --> 02:17:48.990
In 50 years of being in the
attic, where in the summer

02:17:48.990 --> 02:17:51.320
it was 40 degrees above
0, in the winter it was

02:17:51.320 --> 02:17:55.709
40 degrees below 0
Celsius, this had

02:17:55.709 --> 02:17:58.170
broken all of these
fragments of DNA

02:17:58.170 --> 02:18:00.730
down in just that short
of an amount of time.

02:18:00.730 --> 02:18:03.700
So the preservation of samples
after they have been taken out

02:18:03.700 --> 02:18:05.330
of the ground is,
actually, critically

02:18:05.330 --> 02:18:08.510
important for
preserving their DNA.

02:18:08.510 --> 02:18:12.889
And yeah, we try to keep
things in cool and constant

02:18:12.889 --> 02:18:15.980
temperature environments, with
as little exposure to changes

02:18:15.980 --> 02:18:17.420
in ambient moisture as possible.

02:18:17.420 --> 02:18:20.930
I think the water, actually,
expansion and contraction

02:18:20.930 --> 02:18:24.049
of water molecules, may
physically break down the DNA.

02:18:24.049 --> 02:18:26.992
But yeah, it has changed the
way we think about things.

02:18:29.799 --> 02:18:30.299
Hi.

02:18:30.299 --> 02:18:31.450
My name is Beth Thomas.

02:18:31.450 --> 02:18:32.620
I'm with Harvard management.

02:18:32.620 --> 02:18:35.850
And I have a
question for Spencer.

02:18:35.850 --> 02:18:40.350
And it has to do with the
future utility of the data

02:18:40.350 --> 02:18:43.410
that you may be
collecting, or they

02:18:43.410 --> 02:18:47.549
are collecting in the
genographics project

02:18:47.549 --> 02:18:48.520
that you're doing.

02:18:48.520 --> 02:18:50.400
And it's been interesting
watching Facebook.

02:18:50.400 --> 02:18:53.709
Just in a few years, they're
well over a billion members,

02:18:53.709 --> 02:18:55.540
albeit it's free.

02:18:55.540 --> 02:18:59.209
But as the pricing for
these kits declines,

02:18:59.209 --> 02:19:04.500
and maybe more momentum and
just the word of mouth gets out,

02:19:04.500 --> 02:19:09.559
it's going to be interesting
to see just how many people do

02:19:09.559 --> 02:19:10.420
use those kits.

02:19:10.420 --> 02:19:13.040
And I'm just curious
what you think the maybe

02:19:13.040 --> 02:19:15.750
future of that data is?

02:19:15.750 --> 02:19:17.420
If there's been a
progressive reveal

02:19:17.420 --> 02:19:20.360
or progressive
realization about what

02:19:20.360 --> 02:19:23.870
might be what the
information from Facebook

02:19:23.870 --> 02:19:25.940
might be used for it
in the future-- ads,

02:19:25.940 --> 02:19:29.609
whatever-- is there
a similar trajectory

02:19:29.609 --> 02:19:32.190
with the data at that project?

02:19:32.190 --> 02:19:37.139
-So, again, what's driving a
lot of the interest in consumer

02:19:37.139 --> 02:19:41.420
genomics right now is
genealogy and ancestry.

02:19:41.420 --> 02:19:43.980
Some people literally know
nothing about their ancestry.

02:19:43.980 --> 02:19:45.520
They're just
curious to see, am I

02:19:45.520 --> 02:19:49.080
part European, part East
Asian, whatever it might be?

02:19:49.080 --> 02:19:51.050
Other people--
African Americans--

02:19:51.050 --> 02:19:53.264
are looking for a connection
to a tribal group,

02:19:53.264 --> 02:19:54.930
perhaps, in West
Africa, because they've

02:19:54.930 --> 02:19:59.050
lost that written history about
that side of their family.

02:19:59.050 --> 02:20:01.440
A lot of people are interested
in finding their cousins.

02:20:01.440 --> 02:20:03.270
They've got some issue
in their genealogy

02:20:03.270 --> 02:20:05.090
that can't be solved
with written records.

02:20:05.090 --> 02:20:06.465
And the only way
to resolve it is

02:20:06.465 --> 02:20:08.230
to test disparate parts
of the family tree

02:20:08.230 --> 02:20:10.600
and see if they
actually do connect.

02:20:10.600 --> 02:20:13.790
So ancestry is the
primary driver right now.

02:20:13.790 --> 02:20:15.260
That's for a couple of reasons.

02:20:15.260 --> 02:20:18.740
One is that the FDA shut down
that aspect of 23 and Me,

02:20:18.740 --> 02:20:23.810
which is one of the big players
in the field, the medical side.

02:20:23.810 --> 02:20:27.130
Part of the reason for doing
that is because of the way 23

02:20:27.130 --> 02:20:29.560
and Me chose to
deal with the FDA.

02:20:29.560 --> 02:20:32.350
I don't think if they had
handled things differently

02:20:32.350 --> 02:20:34.950
they would have necessarily
had that part shut down.

02:20:34.950 --> 02:20:37.230
Part of it, though, is
because we haven't really

02:20:37.230 --> 02:20:40.060
shown the utility of
medical genetic testing

02:20:40.060 --> 02:20:42.130
for most healthy people.

02:20:42.130 --> 02:20:44.850
We still don't know enough
about the underlying biology

02:20:44.850 --> 02:20:47.750
and what all of these millions
of SNPs-- single nucleotide

02:20:47.750 --> 02:20:49.450
polymorphisms-- really do.

02:20:49.450 --> 02:20:50.980
Do they have any effect?

02:20:50.980 --> 02:20:52.380
Is the effect significant?

02:20:52.380 --> 02:20:53.890
Is it actionable?

02:20:53.890 --> 02:20:57.180
If somebody tells you you've
got a 1.2% higher risk of type 2

02:20:57.180 --> 02:20:58.780
diabetes because
you've got a marker

02:20:58.780 --> 02:21:03.630
at whatever the locus is, is
that really meaningful to you?

02:21:03.630 --> 02:21:08.330
Those are the bigger
questions in human biology.

02:21:08.330 --> 02:21:12.130
I'm going to have to take strong
exception to both of those.

02:21:12.130 --> 02:21:14.350
When the FDA shut
down 23 and Me,

02:21:14.350 --> 02:21:19.720
it did not shut down 500 other
medical genetics centers.

02:21:19.720 --> 02:21:23.100
And they were providing
very high-quality data

02:21:23.100 --> 02:21:27.760
at many stages of
the human cycle.

02:21:27.760 --> 02:21:30.380
So there are very
valuable things

02:21:30.380 --> 02:21:33.530
that you can do pre-conception,
while you're still deciding

02:21:33.530 --> 02:21:37.430
who you're going to mate with.

02:21:37.430 --> 02:21:39.480
Noninvasive prenatal
testing you can now

02:21:39.480 --> 02:21:40.620
get from mother's blood.

02:21:40.620 --> 02:21:41.120
-Absolutely.

02:21:41.120 --> 02:21:43.720
-This is done in millions
of women around the world.

02:21:43.720 --> 02:21:46.790
-But I said the utility for
healthy adults hasn't really--

02:21:46.790 --> 02:21:51.290
-But you still have the market
includes healthy adults that

02:21:51.290 --> 02:21:53.540
are planning on procreating.

02:21:53.540 --> 02:21:57.260
And then, for healthy adults,
there is a long list of things

02:21:57.260 --> 02:21:58.230
we cannot do.

02:21:58.230 --> 02:22:01.400
But there is also a significant
list of things we can do,

02:22:01.400 --> 02:22:02.940
including various cancers.

02:22:02.940 --> 02:22:04.810
Angelina Jolie was the--

02:22:04.810 --> 02:22:05.920
-BRCA.

02:22:05.920 --> 02:22:08.900
---the person who really changed
consciousness a little bit

02:22:08.900 --> 02:22:10.210
on that.

02:22:10.210 --> 02:22:13.610
So I think there's been
a tendency in the media

02:22:13.610 --> 02:22:17.010
to focus on the half
empty part of the glass.

02:22:17.010 --> 02:22:21.300
But I think we've
reached the tipping point

02:22:21.300 --> 02:22:24.850
that Helix and others
will exploit and make

02:22:24.850 --> 02:22:26.580
it available to all of us.

02:22:26.580 --> 02:22:29.430
So it's not 20 years
away and always will be.

02:22:29.430 --> 02:22:30.725
It's happened a few years ago.

02:22:30.725 --> 02:22:31.600
-Oh, I totally agree.

02:22:31.600 --> 02:22:34.490
-It became valuable for
adults whether or not

02:22:34.490 --> 02:22:35.460
they're procreating.

02:22:35.460 --> 02:22:37.560
-Absolutely.

02:22:37.560 --> 02:22:40.640
The problem with the 23
and Me data, of course,

02:22:40.640 --> 02:22:43.015
is that it's all
based on chip results.

02:22:43.015 --> 02:22:45.140
The markers on chips are
relatively high frequency.

02:22:45.140 --> 02:22:47.389
-They're at a relative
minority of the medical record.

02:22:47.389 --> 02:22:49.209
-And we're not
discovering anything new.

02:22:49.209 --> 02:22:51.250
The real utility is going
to come from sequencing

02:22:51.250 --> 02:22:53.260
a lot of people, as you know.

02:22:53.260 --> 02:22:56.640
-And that's exactly
what the 500 others do.

02:22:56.640 --> 02:22:59.230
All the high-quality medical
data comes from them.

02:22:59.230 --> 02:23:02.613
And some of them are in
the $100 to $200 range.

02:23:08.214 --> 02:23:09.380
-I want to thank this panel.

02:23:09.380 --> 02:23:11.530
This has been fascinating.

